"5","Brunner_Emily","Wade Lang Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer January 30, 2017 Minneapolis, Minnesota Wade Lang-WL Amy Sullivan-AS AS: The first thing I’ll ask you to do is give me permission to interview you. 11, 16, 19 I give Dr. Amy Sullivan to use the content therewithin. 7, 9, 11 AS: Thank you.  It is January thirtieth and we are at my house in Minneapolis for this interview. 9, 11 You were holding a thought, so why don’t you just start with that. 6, 10, 16 WL: Well, I don’t know if I lost that thought. 10, 17 We were talking about opiates and— AS: And pain and trauma. 6, 17 I was stealing opiates at the height of the opiate epidemic. 17 AS: Where were you stealing them from?  WL: From customers.  AS: In your carpet cleaning business? 9, 12, 14, 15, 16 Let’s hold that one. 12, 16 [laughs] 10 WL: We will come back to it when it is chronologically appropriate. 11, 14, 17, 19 AS: That’s where the big jar came from you were talking about? 6, 13, 17 AS: When were you born? 5 Where did you grow up?  What was your family life like? 7, 8, 9, 14, 19 WL: I was born in 1972, Marshall, Minnesota. 5 I born to one Patricia Hanson. 5, 17 My birth name was Wade Hanson. 11, 17 I was raised by my grandmother and grandfather until I was four years old. 5, 10, 16 My grandpa, who up until that point I thought was my dad, had a massive heart attack and died. 6, 10, 14, 17 There is a blank in my life up until probably either five or six years old. 7, 8, 12, 13, 16 There is a year there where I really don’t remember anything after he died. 6, 7, 8, 13, 15, 16, 17 It is really cloudy. 6, 7, 8 I should probably get some therapy around that. 12, 13, 18, 20 The next memory that I have is my current stepdad coming into my life and moving into a little town called Sleepy Eye, Minnesota. 7, 8, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20 I didn’t know any of this information as far as my birth name being Wade Hanson until I was fourteen years old. 9, 11, 16, 17 I didn’t know I was adopted until I was fourteen. 16, 17 It was kept a secret. 7 AS: How old was your mom when she had you? 16, 17 WL: Eighteen.  AS: She never married? 12, 13, 16 I have no idea who my dad is. 5 I have a picture of him. 7 He looks like Cheech from Cheech and Chong sitting on a comforter made of several different colored—like a quilt, or something like that. 7, 13, 18 AS: The height of the seventies?  Pants that were sewn together and a long mustache that showed his ethnicity. 7, 9, 11, 16, 20 He was very Hispanic.  That’s about all I know. 17 I never met him. 12, 13 I looked for him when I was eighteen or nineteen for a little while. 13, 20 AS: Do you know his name? 11, 17 WL: My mom told my now wife, who was my girlfriend at the time, his name was John Rost, but it just doesn’t even sound right compared to what he looked like. 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 I grew up in a community where ethnicity was not celebrated. 7, 19 AS: That’s a nice way to put it. 14, 19 WL: I took a multicultural class. 6, 12 I know what I am supposed to say here. 14, 17 [laughs] 10 There was a lot of shame, I’m sure. 7 I was the darkest thing in my neighborhood probably until 1981 or 1982 when the migratory employees started to come to town. 6, 12, 13, 15, 17, 19 That was the first four or five years. 16 Because this is so closely tied to my opiate use and my drug use in general the first recollection I have at age five or six was being sexually molested by a female babysitter on a weekly basis. 6, 7, 9, 10, 13, 15, 16, 20 Every Friday and Saturday night because my step dad played in a three piece country band, and they would leave at four or five o’clock in the afternoon and return at two or three in the morning. 7, 9, 10, 16, 19 They left me and my baby sister that was probably a year or a year and a half at that time. 7, 8, 12, 13, 16, 19, 20 Then she would go down and the act would take place every time. 7, 8, 16, 19, 20 That was pretty impactful. 5, 7, 14 AS: You remember that? 7, 13, 15 WL: Here’s the thing. 19 I had repressed that memory until I was probably nine or ten years old. 7, 12, 13, 16 We had a little clubhouse that we built, me and the buddies back in the day, and we found a crumpled up old Playboy in a garbage somewhere. 7, 9, 10, 11, 15, 16, 17, 19, 20 We went Dumpster diving on our bicycles to find treasure. 7, 9 We found this magazine and we took it back to the clubhouse to look at it. 9, 10, 11, 17, 19 When I looked at the female anatomy everything rushed back. 11, 13, 17, 19 All the feelings. 13, 17, 18 The overwhelming loss of time, loss of location, I didn’t know where I was. 7, 16, 17, 19 I remember telling my best buddy at the time, “Carl,” I said, “There was this babysitter and she did this and this and this.” 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19, 20 Carl just was like, “What?” 9, 14 And I was like, “Yeah.” 9, 14 You know? 17 You can’t tell your mom! 13, 17 I had never told anybody. 13, 16 Not for many, many years. 16, 18 AS: So you didn’t tell your mom? 13, 17 WL: No, I didn’t tell my mother until I was thirty-three years old. 10, 13, 16 Probably almost to eight years old when that occured until my babysister got old enough to really get in the way and know what was going on. 6, 7, 8, 15, 16, 17, 20 It was the full gambit of sexual molestation. 7, 20 It was not good and it warped my sense of sexuality and perceived position and appropriateness. 6, 7, 9, 19 As a young six, seven, eight year old I would grab grown women in wrong spots because I thought it was okay. 6, 10, 12, 14, 16 I didn’t know any different. 7, 17, 18 I was punished for things but I didn’t know what was going on. 5, 17, 19 My stepfather uses a belt and a stick and his hand to try to correct everything. 7, 9, 13, 16 I am really confused. 6, 7, 8, 9 I have a double bind situation going on where I have this thing going on and I can’t tell because it is a secret and if I tell I am going to get in trouble, but I’m getting punished because of the behavior and the behavior is because of the thing that I can’t tell about. 7, 13, 15, 19, 20 I started to eat. 6, 15 Eating was my first addiction. 8, 15, 16 I would eat everything and anything.  Crackers, cups of sugar, anything I could find in the house to the degree that my mother had to put a lock on the refrigerator door. 7, 9, 10, 11, 17, 19 An actual combination lock on that and on the pantry doors because I would get up in the middle of the night and eat, or I would get up earlier than they because they were out doing this band thing until four in the morning. 9, 14, 17, 19, 20 They were exhausted and drunk and they would sleep until noon. 8, 11 She would lock us in our rooms. 9 They put locks on the outside of our doors so we would just have to stay in our rooms until noon. 9, 14, 17, 19 I remember as a kid I would piss in the closet because I couldn’t get out to pee or anything. 6, 7, 13, 15, 20 I would just pee in the corner of the closet. 6, 13 I had a boot that I would pee in every once in awhile and then pour it out the window. 20 I would hide food in there the night before because I knew I was going to be hungry. 6, 12, 19 I remember packs of white almond bark I would put in my underwear drawer and stack it in there because I knew the following morning I could sit and eat white almond bark. 6, 7, 9, 12, 13, 15, 19 AS: Were you in the same room as your sister? 9, 16 WL: At first, yes. 9, 14, 16 We stayed in the same room. 9, 14, 16 There was a time where we had to separate because I think I was being inappropriate with her. 7, 16, 19 They separated us in two different rooms. 7, 9, 18 We would talk to each other through the doors. 6, 17, 19 I would say, “Go holler for mom.” 14, 17 When she would holler she would come. 17 When I would holler for mom she wouldn’t. 17 I would entice her, “Go holler for mom.” 17 This is all normal. 18 This is just a stage. 15 [laugh]  You laugh because otherwise you cry, obviously.  I ate and ate and ate and at nine or ten years old I was pretty obese. 5, 7, 14, 16 I was getting teased I remember. 7, 13, 15, 20 Uncles used to grab my fat rolls and squeeze and shake them. 9 They would pinch so hard that it would leave black and blue marks. 6 It was as if they were going to try to rip it off me.  Again, I’m this dark skinned, young—the word they would use was bastard. 6, 9 They would call me a little bastard child. 9, 14, 17, 20 I didn’t even know what that was. 17 I ended up using it one time when my stepdad was around. 7, 10, 16, 18, 19 I was mad or something and I said bastard and he came at me with a wrench in his hand and ended up cutting my brow. 7, 13, 14, 17 He said, “We don’t use that language.” 9, 13, 14, 15 And I didn’t even know it was language. 15, 17 That’s what my uncles called me. 13, 14, 17 I didn’t even know that was a swear word. 17 I was learning. 5 I was getting it down one cut at a time. 7, 14, 15, 16, 19, 20 I ate to soothe.  By age twelve was my first drink. 15, 16, 19 I remember distinctly this young kid came over to the house and he had a can of Tab in his hand. 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15, 17 I said, “Give me a drink of that” and he said, “No, you don’t want any of that.” 13, 14, 19 I said, “Yeah. 13, 14 Give me a drink.” 19 He said, “You don’t want none of this.” 12, 13, 14 I said, “What is it?” 13, 14 He said, “It’s whiskey.” 13, 14 I was like, “I want some!” 9, 14 You can’t handle it.” 13 I grabbed that can away from him and guzzled half of it. 16, 20 I remember him getting mad because I was drinking all his whiskey. 7, 13, 15, 19 It was Tab and Sloe gin.  I’ll never forget that warmth in my belly and how fuzzy my mind felt. 6, 13, 20 That overwhelming warmth.  It was almost as if I was seeing the world through new eyes. 5, 6, 9, 12, 14, 15 Everything was brighter. 8, 14 I could run faster, jump higher, ride my bike faster. 8, 11, 17 I loved it. 17 I just recalled that my stepdad had some of this and it was in the basement. 7, 13, 14, 16, 17 They had a whole liquor cabinet .  A bar. 12 I was like, “We can get more now!” 9, 14, 17, 20 He said, “Okay!” 13, 14 So, the first time I drank I got intoxicated to puking because I didn’t know how much was enough. 7, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 Now, with my addiction you can see that I had this propensity to escape into whatever I could find. 5, 7, 8, 9, 15, 20 Having that I was like, “Okay, I am going to drink this.” 9, 14, 19 Twelve, thirteen, and fourteen— 16 AS: Did you get caught at that point? 10 Actually, I didn’t.  My parents were very removed from parenting. 7, 11, 12, 14 They were actually just like people that lived in the same house. 9, 11, 16, 18 We took care of ourselves. 7, 14, 20 We parented ourselves. 7 They would throw down a couple of bags of Doritos and a frozen pizza and they’d leave. 7 Probably at about twelve I started babysitting my nine year old sister, my six year old half brother, and my next half brother was three. 6, 7, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 I was taking care of them at age twelve and stealing from the old man’s liquor cabinet the second they walk out the door. 7, 14, 15, 16, 17, 20 That works. 8 Did you get a baby sitting badge? 7, 18, 20 [laughs] 10 WL: I went to babysitting training, but omitted that I used alcohol. 7, 8, 9, 10, 18, 20 I didn’t want to lose my badge. 13, 14 [laughs] 10 From eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve it was all food until I found liquor. 11, 12 It was quicker, so there was no reason to continue to eat. 7, 10, 17, 19 I still had a hard time with food and portion distortion and governing my amounts and kinds. 6, 7, 12, 16, 19 There was always this lack of food in our house. 9, 10, 11, 12 We were poor, we didn’t have much money. 7, 12 We had government cheese, powdered milk, WIC [Women, Infants, and Children] came out about that time. 7, 13, 16, 17, 19 Food was a commodity that was scarce. 14 When it did come around— AS: When it was there you ate as much as you could. 17, 18 WL: All of it to the point where my mother would not store food in open areas. 7, 10, 12, 20 My other siblings used food as their comfort as well. 8, 9, 12 She became obese very quickly because of it. 5, 13, 17 It was a great way to escape into Doritos or a frozen pizza instead of thinking of how shitty life is. 7, 8, 10, 18, 19 How we don’t get encouraged and loved. 15, 17, 20 There was no parenting at all. 7 Again, we lived with them. 11, 16 The drinking continued on an every other day or every day basis to the degree that I started stealing beer from garages around the community. 6, 7, 15, 19, 20 In Minnesota there is this thing where you have the house refrigerator and then you have the garage refrigerator. 7, 9, 11, 15, 19 The garage refrigerator is full of beer and liquor and wine coolers. 7, 15, 20 And sometimes old cake from graduation or something. 7, 12, 16, 19 You break into a garage and you steal a case of Stross thirty pack and a cake because you are going to get hammered and then maybe eat some cake after. 7, 10, 13, 15, 16 So, that was always a treat. 7, 10 We would steal beer for quite a long time there. 7, 16, 19, 20 The alcoholism really got to a point where I would drink at school. 6, 7, 8, 10, 11, 19 I remember taking paneling off the wall in my bedroom—a whole four by eight sheet of paneling—and I pulled the nails out, pulled the paneling away, and then on the cross member two by fours I stacked [unclear beer name] beers inside the wall when I would steal from these garages. 7, 9, 11, 13, 15, 18, 20 I had several cases of these beers stored in the walls. 7, 12, 13, 20 That way when I was quarantined to my room and locked in there I was okay. 9, 14 I could survive because I had several cases of beer in the wall. 12, 13, 20 My parents have since sold that house and I really thought I want to go back and pull that paneling—I wonder if they ever remodeled because to pull that off there there were empty cans of beer in that wall. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20 Lots.  There was another spot I put empties. 10, 19 Another piece of paneling that I took off where I left a four foot portion and then I crumpled them and put them in the wall in the insulation. 8, 19 Probably not much of an ‘r’ value there with the aluminum.  [laughs] 10 I wonder if some of the cans were tin?  No, I don’t think I was that old. 16 The drinking got really sickening for me to the point where I would buy booze—I would get other adults in the community to buy me booze. 6, 7, 8, 10, 15, 19, 20 I started working for a dairy farmer out of town and there was this man named Chizzy and he was one of the hired hands and he was an alcoholic. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 13, 15, 19 I think that out of all things I have this real intuitiveness. 5, 7, 19 As soon as I saw this guy I knew he was an alcoholic. 5, 6, 10, 12, 13 I knew he was a drinker. 6, 12, 19 I went up to Chizzy and I said, “Listen, if you get me a six pack of beer tonight I’ll buy you a six pack.” 13, 14, 19, 20 He said, “I better not do that.” 13, 14, 17 I said, “Come on.” 13, 14 “Alright.” 8, 14 So, that became our arrangement. 13, 17 He got a six pack then I got a six pack. 13 Pretty soon I would get a thirty pack of Strauss and he would still get a six pack because Chizzy started to rely on my income for his alcohol. 5, 6, 7, 10, 13, 15, 17, 20 That’s how I kept him.  I just made sure that he always knew that I was going to hook him up almost every day. 6, 7, 10, 12, 13, 15, 19 I became the guy to get alcohol from in ninth or tenth grade. 6, 10, 13, 17, 19, 20 If you needed beer you came to Wade, but I’m charging a premium. 7, 9, 13, 17, 20 If they want a case of beer it’s going to cost them double. 14, 20 One for you and I get one. 20 I would store it in my room. 7, 9 I would, at times, literally have hundreds of beers. 7, 16, 19, 20 Warm, in my room, stored. 7, 9 I drank warm beer and I didn’t care. 7, 14, 18, 20 I would slam them by the threes and fours and get the buzz on. 7, 20 It wasn’t for the flavor.  I graduated to alcohol and liquor and whiskey and I just got tired of beer. 7, 10, 11, 20 I went to everclear and it was the next level. 9, 13, 16, 19 Until I started blacking out and wandering around town and didn’t know where I was or how I got there. 6, 15, 17 Where’s my bicycle.  Pretty soon it was, 5, 7 Where did I leave my truck?  When I was sixteen I ended up getting and 1971 K-Ten Blazer. 15, 20 That probably was a bad mistake. 12, 13, 20 I never did get a DUI; I was smart enough to know that if I was going to drink I was going to walk. 13, 16, 17, 19, 20 I just knew I couldn’t drive. 6, 12, 14 I was not that good. 6, 19 I was a sloppy drunk. 8, 11 I didn’t want to drive. 14 It was too nervewracking for me.  I like to find a spot in the middle of nowhere with a bunch of people, or towards the end with just myself, and just drink. 7, 9, 10, 14, 17, 19 That’s how it went until I was seventeen years old when I was introduced to marijuana. 16 I took a job at Kentucky Fried Chicken and one of the employees who was an adult said to me, “Hey, I’m going to consult the dugout on break. 7, 10, 13, 14 Like you, I did the same thing. 19 Eyebrows down and I was like, What the hell does that mean? 9, 14 I didn’t want him to think I wasn’t cool, so I looked at him and said, “Sure.” 7, 13, 14 Breaktime comes around and we stand outside. 7, 9, 16, 17, 18, 19 He pulls out this little wooden box and puts this little steel bat in there and he goes, “Here.” 19, 20 I said, “Go ahead. 12, 13, 14 You go first” because I didn’t know how to do it! 16, 17 [laughs] 10 I had no idea how to do it. 5 AS: You had a good sense of how to get somebody else to show you. 6, 8, 9, 19, 20 WL: “You go ahead, go ahead.” 12 I’ll watch. 15 I’ll learn. 5 He hits this oneie [a smoking device], smokes his weed, and hands it to me and I did it. 10, 12, 13, 19 I think I took two, maybe three puffs, and then we went back in at the end of the break and I thought, This did nothing. 7, 10, 11, 16, 17, 19 I hate weed!  It’s stupid.  Ten minutes later I’m giggling. 5, 14, 16 I just can’t stop laughing.  We are throwing chicken across the kitchen, into the friers, I mean, I’m just doing stuff and it is the funnest, most funniest day in my entire life. 7, 8, 19 I can still remember today how we played with flour, throwing food, giggling at patrons as they are coming in. 5, 7, 12, 13, 15, 19 I was so in love with marijuana I thought, Where were you when I needed you most? 9, 10, 16, 17 Where were you when I was eight and nine years old? 16 I could have used you then, but welcome to my wonderful world. 9, 12, 17 We are going to have such a wonderful love affair. 17 I think I probably stopped drinking almost immediately. 12, 13, 15, 19 I asked him if I could get a little bit of that to go. 20 I asked him how I could get it. 20 He would sell me joints for a while until I said, “I can’t afford however many dollars for each joint. 13, 14, 18, 19 How much for a bag of that?”  Within a couple of weeks I’m walking around with a bag of pot in my pocket everyday. 6, 7, 10, 16, 18, 19 That became my new love affair. 6, 13, 17 In the tenth grade I met this gal who I really was head over heels for. 6, 7, 8, 12, 19 She was in college and I was in tenth grade and I thought that was great. 7, 8, 10, 19 I had scored. 7 I definitely scored. 7, 14 She was cute, but she didn’t like weed at all. 9, 14 I had to hide it.  That was hard to do because it’s stinky. 6 There was a lot of fighting back and forth. 5, 11, 13, 17, 19 “You can’t do that, but it is okay to drink.” 14, 19 That was the social expectation in my community: drinking was fine, but don’t smoke weed. 14, 15, 18, 19 Don’t be a druggie. 10 That’s what they would call them. 14, 17 It’s okay if you are bombed off your ass with alcohol, but not marijuana. 10, 14, 16 When I met her I tried really hard to moderate. 6, 7, 8, 12 I tried to not use, and it wasn’t easy. 9, 11 When I tried to stop using marijuana I’d go back to alcohol. 10, 11, 16, 17, 19 It was like, I can’t do this. 9, 14 She wound up getting pregnant when I was in the tenth grade. 7, 15, 19, 20 Now, I’m going to be a dad.  Now I need to get my poop in a group. 18, 20 This is not a good idea to do this and try to be a dad. 5, 6, 19 School is not good. 6, 19 I am starting to experience this—looking back on it I can see it plainly today—there’s this emotion disregulation that has happened because of all the prior stuff. 5, 6, 7, 11, 15, 17, 19 I go from zero to one hundred with anger.  So quickly. 5 AS: At this age, you mean? 15 Throwing things, breaking car windows, slashing tires. 5, 7, 10, 14, 19, 20 I don’t know if this is incriminating, but we’ll say I think the limits are out, but my principal at one point told me, “You’re nothing but a piece of shit. 7, 10, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 You’re going to end up in prison before you even graduate.” 7, 8, 17 He called me a bunch of names and I walked out of his office. 11, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19, 20 That night I went back to school and I cut every wire in his brand new Chevy S-10 that I could to teach him a lesson. 6, 7, 11, 14, 17, 19 That you don’t fuck with me.  I was that kind of person. 10, 17 Very malicious.  If you wronged me I will burn you’re house down. 6, 7, 9, 11 I will cut you’re car up. 7, 14 I will do something to hurt you. 14 I will do something to retaliate. 7 I can plainly see today that that was supressed anger and emotion from all the PTSD that I was dealing with at the time. 5, 7, 16, 19 I didn’t know how to deal with it. 17 If I wasn’t self medicating it was coming out other ways. 5, 7 In the eleventh grade I joined the military. 19 AS: What happened with the pregnancy? 5, 7 Zach was born on the sixth of November in my eleventh grade year. 5, 16, 19 I went on about being a teenager and a dad. 15 I went to basic training through my eleventh and twelfth year. 8, 16, 17 It was called spit training at that time. 7, 8, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 I went to basic and then came home for my senior year. 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 I was excused from ninth grade English all together. 9, 11, 16, 19, 20 I never took English. 13 Don’t tell my master’s program that. 8, 13 [laughs] 10 “Do you have all your credits?” 7 “Everything but ninth grade English.” 19 My senior year the principal and I had an understanding that I only needed to come to school twice a week. 9, 11, 16, 17 As long as I showed up and did the tests I didn’t have to do anything else. 7, 8, 9, 13 I worked two or three jobs at the time. 7, 12, 15, 16, 19 I worked at Perkins at night where I bused tables. 9, 12, 18, 19 I worked at Godfather’s Pizza during the rushes to deliver pizza’s, and another restaurant job someplace, but I can’t remember. 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16 But I had three jobs. 15 I finally fought back at that point with my stepdad. 10, 11, 16, 17, 19 I omitted most of this, but he used to hit me with everything. 9, 19 He used to have a two by four that he carved his hand into. 9, 13, 14 It said Board of Education on it. 13, 14 It literally was a fucking two by four.  When he would hit me I would put my hands behind my back to try to guard my ass and he’d break a finger periodically. 7, 10, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 That pinky finger right there has been broken so many times. 7, 8, 14, 16, 18, 19 It is just part of the deal, but I would never cry and I prided myself on the fact that I would never cry. 8, 13, 17 I remember him asking the question: 7, 13, 15 “Have you had enough?” 16, 20 My response: No. 7 He would bring it again.  Whack, whack, whack.  He would keep hitting until he was tired. 7, 17, 19 Guess who won?  You can beat the shit out of me, but you will not break my will. 7, 10, 19 It will not happen. 5 That has carried over into adulthood, of course. 14 AS: It also shows a very strong core person. 7, 9, 10, 17 WL: Tenacity.  Unending tenacity.  AS: Whatever we want to call it it is a survival— WL: 14, 17 He called it stubborn. 5, 13, 14, 17 I like to shift it into tenacity! 9, 14 AS: It is also a survival mechanism.  WL: I would just go to the other place. 8 When I’m getting hit I wou