liked. 5, 7, 9, 12, 14, 19 We had guys that really liked benzodiazepines. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 15 I would take them not because I like benzos, but because I could exchange them. 5, 9, 14, 20 It was a currency. 7 It has a value system.  One orange football Xanax is worth a specific dollar amount. 12 Very little, but very specific. 20 This continued until I lost my franchise in 2002. 19 I went to treatment a couple more times in between there. 7, 13, 16, 18, 19 Always for someone else, never for me. 8, 13 Colleen caught on that I was using again when things had gotten desperate and I went again when I was twenty six. 5, 7, 10, 19 One more time again when I was twenty-eight or twenty-nine. 7, 16, 19 It was always these outpatients that weren’t very effective. 10, 15 AS: Did you have kids by this point? 10, 15 WL: The twins were born in 2000. 5 This was 2002 so they were two at this point. 10 At the point they were born I was sober for a very short period of time. 5, 7, 10, 16, 19 The one thing that I’m not proud of, and I will share this, is that when the twins were born my wife almost died on the table because she was preaclapsic. 5, 7, 12, 15, 17, 18, 19 She had Josie and then she fell asleep and was bleeding internally. 11 Jake was still in there. 7 AS: She had a natural birth?  WL: The medication infiltrated. 16 The spinal tap didn’t work, it came out. 13, 17 It created this huge pustule in her back of medication that never got to her. 7, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 I convinced her that it was working because the doctor didn’t tell her it was working. 13, 20 They only told me and I said, “Don’t tell her.” 13, 14, 16 I looked at her and I grabbed her by the collar as she is in excruciating pain and dying because of blood loss. 13 She said, “It hurts so bad.” 13, 14 And I said, “Can you imagine how bad it would hurt if you didn’t have the pain medication? 13, 14, 16 Now push!”  She pushed and Jake was born. 5 He was born not breathing so they had to intubate him and he began to br