10, 12, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19 Why don’t you go ahead and get your stuff together and we will go up and get you some help. 11, 12, 16, 18, 20 It is going to suck, but you’ll be alright.” 8, 14 I said, “Okay.” 13, 14 AS: Is this your stepdad’s dad? 16 I said, “Okay.” 13, 14 He said, “Really? 13, 14 Okay.”  I took a teener of cocaine into my bathroom and my dad said, “Just keep the door open.” 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 17, 20 I said, “No, I’m taking a shower. 9, 13, 14 I’m not keeping the door open. 17, 20 I’ve got nothing in here.  We’re good.” 6, 7, 19 I put the teener in the spoon, drew it back as much as I could, and I shot the whole thing into my arm hoping I would overdose. 7, 11, 17, 19, 20 I got really, really sick to the point where I fell into the shower. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 They helped me up, got me dressed. 7, 18 On the way out the door I even asked if I could drink a few beers. 17, 19, 20 My grandpa said, “Go ahead. 12, 13, 14 It will be your last.”  I must have hammered four or five beers and then got back in that truck and headed to Minnesota. 7, 11, 12, 17, 19, 20 On the way there my family tried to call and get a bed and there wasn’t a bed at [unclear], there wasn’t a bed at teen challenge. 7, 14, 17, 19, 20 They finally said they had one over in South Dakota. 13, 14 Do you want to go to South Dakota? 14 By this time I’m eating Trazadone because it is all I have left. 7, 8, 16, 19 I was like, “I don’t give a shit where we go. 9, 10, 11, 14, 19 Let’s just go before I get sick again.” 20 After two and a half days in the car—we slept in the vehicle, we kept in the vehicle. 14, 16, 18, 19 They would stop periodically to get me a little more booze here and there just to keep me level. 9, 14, 17, 20 We got to Canton and at Canton I had just come around and they introduced me to a nurse. 17, 18 I stuck my hand out and gave them the best smile I could do. 13, 18 They gave me a room and they said, “We understand that you have been doing some pretty heavy amounts. 5, 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 18 We would like to make you as comfortable as possible. 9, 14, 18 Are you allergic to Xanax at all?”  I said, “Why, no. 13, 14 “Okay, take this. 20 This will really help you to be calm.” 6, 7, 8, 18 “I will, thank you.” 9 AS: This is what treatment looks like. 7, 9, 13, 14, 18 WL: I am allergic to Xanax because every time I take it the left side of my body goes numb; totally dead. 7, 8, 9, 16, 19, 20 I went back to my room and lay down. 9, 11, 17, 19 I woke up at about eight or nine at night and I left the treament center. 7, 8, 19 I went to the bar and I had a few drinks. 12, 19 I tried to steal a car, and I couldn’t. 14 There wasn’t anything pre-1985 that I could ‘Dukes of Hazzard’ this thing and leave. 19 I stole a bicycle and I drove that back to the treatment center after falling on the lawn a few different times because I must have drank a fifth of whiskey sitting at that bar plus a Xanax. 7, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 I found my way back there because I was going to bicycle all the way home but I asked someone where I was and they said, “You don’t know where you’re at?” 7, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 I said, “Just tell me what town I’m in.” 13, 14 “Canton.”  “Canton, Kentucky?”  “No, Canton, South Dakota.”  “How far is that from Kentucky?” 9 I literally thought I was going to go home. 10, 17, 19 I didn’t care. 7, 14, 20 I was going to get home. 17, 19, 20 I got to the edge of town and got tired. 7 I figured I better go back to the treatment center and figure it out tomorrow. 7, 11, 13, 17, 18, 19 I went back to the treatment center and threw the bike down on the lawn like I was a nine year old kid. 7, 11, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 I walked into the treatment center and went under my bed. 7, 13, 18, 20 The nurse came in and tried to get me out of there and I guess I tried to hurt her. 13, 14, 17, 19, 20 I used to hide underneath my bed when my stepdad used to hurt me. 9, 14, 16 I don’t know what happened. 5, 17 I must have reverted to something. 7, 13 The following day it happened again. 5, 19 They gave me Xanax again and I ended up going to the bar again. 12, 18 This time they sent one of the counselors named Bill. 7, 11, 16, 19, 20 I think he is still there. 7 He is a marine.  I was at the gas station this time drinking a Deuce and he finds me sitting up next to the gas station drinking this beer. 7, 9, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 He takes the beer and says, “You’re not going to need this to get in the back of my truck.” 7, 11, 14, 17, 19, 20 I got in the back of the truck. 11, 17, 19 I’m already drunk because I went to the bar first and then went to get more beer. 6, 7, 8, 11, 12, 16, 18, 20 Went back to the treatment center and they called this pastor Al Pratt. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19 He is a six foot five two hundred and eighty pound biker who is a pastor but did a lot of time but now had turned his life over. 7, 8, 16, 17, 18, 19 He settled me down, but they had to shoot me full of thorazine to get me to stay. 7, 14, 20 For the next three days I did the thorazine shuffle all around that treatment center. 7, 13, 16, 18, 19 I woke up three days later on the men’s wing. 5, 16, 18, 19 AS: The men’s wing of what?  WL: Of the treatment center. 7, 13, 18 Three days later I wake up bald and I’ve got no facial hair. 5, 16, 18, 19 I look in the mirror and go, “What the fuck.”  Everybody is laughing and I don’t know why they are laughing. 17 I thought it was really disturbing and not okay. 6, 7, 8, 10, 14 I don’t care how drunk they get. 7, 8, 11, 14, 20 You don’t shave their head. 12 I went to the director of the place and pitch a fit. 7, 8 I’m like, “Who shaved my head?” 9, 12, 14 She was like, “Wade, Wade, Wade. 9, 14 You were standing in the men’s bathroom stark naked, shaving your entire head. 7, 9, 12, 17 We weren’t going to stop you!  We figure the worst that could happen is that it would grow back.” 5, 7, 11, 17, 19 Okay.  Shaved every ounce off.  That began my forty-five day stay at that treatment center. 7, 13, 14, 18, 19 My daughter still reminds me of the time she saw me with no hair or beard. 5, 6, 7, 16, 19 It scarred her. 7, 14 We found a picture of it not long ago and she can’t look at it. 7, 11, 16 She does not like it. 9, 14 It’s not the daddy she left in Kentucky. 8, 19 They had to go stay with parents because I went to treatment. 7, 12, 13, 14, 18 My twins went to stay with my mother in Minnesota. 10, 14 Our one year old went to stay with my wife’s mom and dad in Iowa. 12, 14, 16, 17 My wife is still in Kentucky, and I’m in South Dakota. 7, 12 Split apart and I didn’t think we were ever getting back together again. 8, 11, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19, 20 AS: So pastor Al Pratt shows up. 8, 9 I want to hear about how you got into college, how you got here, and what you’re doing now. 7, 14, 17 WL: I met pastor Al Pratt and was enamored by his coolness. 7, 12 He’s got tattoos up and down his arms, wearing a biker jacket, says ‘pastor’ on it. 8, 14, 17 He’s got this story of drinking bleach to clean his system out prior to UA to such a degree that he has to have a steel lining in his gut because that is the degree that his addiction took him to. 7, 8, 13, 15, 16, 19 I’m thinking if that happened to you I am so much better than you. 5, 17 You make me feel really good about how it turned out for me. 6, 7, 8, 13, 18, 19 After going through that treatment and going home I got into an aftercare program. 7, 8, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19, 20 They had a counselor come to my house every week for a good eightteen months. 6, 9, 11, 16, 17, 19, 20 AS: Were you back in Kentucky at this point? 10, 11, 17, 19 WL: Sleepy Eye, Minnesota where I grew up. 7, 19 AS: So the whole family moved? 7, 11, 14, 19 My wonderful mom found a three bedroom branch home that was for sale and manipulated the sellers to rent it to us. 5, 7, 9, 11, 17, 19 My mom is a very dynamic person. 10, 17 She’s got us living in this 1974 home that is decorated in 1974. 6, 17, 19 I went from living in Louisville, Kentucky in a very prestigious neighborhood—even though I was dying from addiction I was used to finer things—to a house with shag carpets, linoleum, smoke colored walls, dark chocolate cabinetry, orange countertops. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 14, 15, 19 I’m just flabbergasted at where I’m at in now in my life, but at the same time it’s like I know I need to redeem myself. 7, 8, 16, 17, 19 We dig in the best we can. 13 My wife gets a job as a nurse in a geriatrics facility in a little town. 12, 20 My kids get enrolled in kindergarten. 15 We’ve got baby Jane and she’s doing well. 8, 20 I started going to meetings. 6, 12, 15 I went every day for a year. 16, 19 Sometimes I would go twice a day: an afternoon meeting and then a night meeting on top of that. 6, 7, 12, 16, 19 I got to the point where all I would do eat, live, breath, and shit recovery. 7, 8, 10, 11, 19 I’m chairing meetings now, I’m going to speak at treatment centers, and I go back to Canton every month to share my story about how I ran away from the treatment center and I ran down to the bar and got hammered. 6, 7, 11, 12, 13, 17, 18, 19, 20 I had become this celebrity in recovery where people were recognizing me. 7, 8, 17, 18 They would say, “Hey, Wade. 14 We have this date and can you come talk?” 6, 17 They would put stuff up with my name on it. 11, 19 It got to the degree where I was like, Is this what it is supposed to be like? 7, 9, 14, 19 But I was loving it.  I was having a great time. 7, 8, 16, 19 My spiritual life started to increase and I started really wanting to know god more and what he had in store for me if anything at all. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 15, 17 There was always the ‘why me’ every time I had that ontological argument of is there or isn’t there. 7, 10, 16, 19 If so he’s off his game because he could have saved me here and here and here and he never did. 13, 15 So why now? 17 I reached out to pastor 7, 8 Al and went back to Sioux Falls. 11, 17, 19 I went to his church a few times—it’s a biker church. 7, 16, 19 There are tattoos and bikes and Jesus.  I liked it. 9, 14 I liked being vulnerable. 9, 14, 18 I liked saying I needed something more than me in my life. 7, 8, 9, 14 I need a higher power in my life. 7, 8, 11 Pastor  Al said the thing that I keep hearing: you’ve really got the gift of gab. 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 17, 19 I told him one thing that happened to me—I had mentioned to you at the restaurant that I had this fight with god. 5, 7, 9, 12, 13, 16, 19 AS: Do you want to talk about that? 6, 14 WL: Sure. 7 At about day forty-four I was going to commit suicide. 19 I was told by my wife that we weren’t going to be together right away and it may not happen for awhile because we didn’t have a house and this and that. 5, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 20 She got on me about if I hadn’t done this it wouldn’t be my fault.  She threw some blame at me, which is totally justifiable. 7, 18 Definitely.  Tell that to a self centered, narcissistic, egotistical addict that’s got a wounded spirit. 5, 7, 15 That doesn’t work really well and that’s not what I needed to hear at the time. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 16, 19 I put a bag around my head and a belt around my neck and I went into my room and locked the door. 9, 12, 17, 19 I was bound and determined that asphyxiation was going to be the easiest way out because I would just simply pass out and die. 17 As soon as I did start to black out a hole is torn in the bag and it is a nurse. 5, 6 She says, “Wade, what are you doing?” 14, 17 A nurse never came back to that room ever that whole time I was there, and now all of a sudden there is a nurse outside of this locked door and happens to have a key in her hand? 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 And opens it up at that exact same time? 7, 16, 19, 20 That makes no sense to me. 9, 18 After that episode I went to the backyard where they have this dirt track and I just started to walk around the dirt track over and over. 6, 11, 15, 17, 19 I got into this big fight with god of, “You did this and I hate you.” 9, 13 I was trying to induce the wrath of god. 9 If you are real, zap me dead right here. 7, 8, 14 Finally I screamed at him to either do something with me or kill me. 7 I fell to the ground.  I just collapsed.  I don’t know if it was emotion or what it was. 17 I just went down and cried.  I remember just laying there crying for the longest time. 7, 13, 15, 16, 19 That deep visceral kind of thing. 19 You can’t catch your breath. 7 After that I went and sat in this lecture hall and listened to this speaker talk about getting beaten. 6, 7, 15, 20 When the old man sends you to the closet to the get the belt that he is going to beat you with do you get the wide belt or the thin belt. 6, 13, 16, 20 I said, “The wide belt.” 13, 14 AS: You said that out loud? 13, 14 The speaker says to me, “There is a man that has been beaten.” 14, 17 It pierced me.  It felt as if god was talking to me through this person. 6, 9, 10, 17 How did they know? 17 Is that really reminiscent of a beaten person that they would go get the wide belt? 6, 7, 8, 10, 17, 20 Of course it is because it has greater surface tension and it’s not going to hurt as bad. 7, 8, 14 I know that because it has happened. 5, 17 I am not going to give you the thin belt. 11 It was all of those things in combination that made me go back to visit Al Pratt. 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19 He was the speaker who said that. 13, 14 I went back to him and shared with him that something had happened on that dirt track. 5, 7, 11, 17, 19 There was a revelation that happened. 5, 7 I didn’t want to seem too weird, but god told me I was going to be a pastor. 5, 8, 9, 13, 14, 16 That was something that was almost a knowingness. 15, 17 I called my wife before I went into that lecture hall that night. 7, 12, 13, 14, 17, 19 I told her about that day and what happened. 5, 13, 16, 19 I told her I had this overwhelming knowingness that I’m supposed to be a pastor or something. 8, 13, 14, 16, 17 She was at a hotel with my parents at the time, and she goes, “That’s great.” 7, 8, 12, 16, 19 I could hear the patronizing tone. 12, 14 I said, “You don’t understand. 13, 14 This is real. 7 I really feel like there was a spiritual entity there and I had there experience. 6, 7, 8, 13, 15, 18 I can’t even explain it.”  “Honey. 12 That’s great. 7, 8 We are behind you no matter what.” 10 I just surrendered. 7 She was not going to believe me. 9 Not now; I’ve got to walk it out. 17 As I am home doing outpatient I just have this feeling that I need to go back and see him. 5, 11, 13, 17, 18, 19 He puts it on my heart to read the Bible, and I did. 6, 7, 14, 19 I sat down at my kitchen table with a pot of coffee and a pack of cigarettes and my recovery bible. 7, 8, 10, 13, 18 “In the beginning.”  My mother in law called to check up and see how we were. 5, 10, 13, 14, 16, 17 I never liked her because she was a godly woman and I never was a godly man at all. 9, 13, 14 This time I had a real hankering to ask her about god and what it means to her. 7, 9, 16, 19 I just talked to her for awhile. 6, 13 I said, “Mary Jane, I’m reading the Bible and I was interested in what your experience is.” 7, 13, 14, 15 She said, “What are you reading?” 7, 13, 14 I said, “Genesis, you know, in the beginning.” 13, 14, 17 She said, “You don’t want to start there!” 6, 13, 14 I was like, “What are you talking about?” 6, 9, 14 AS: So you had no religious upbringing? 7 WL: I was the CEO of the church—Christmas and Easter Only.  [laughs] 10 My parents would drop us off and we would go to Sunday School and they would pick us up. 5, 7, 12, 19 AS: So, you have some— WL: Not about the books.  I know the characters of the Bible, but not the order that I am supposed to know to get confirmed. 14, 17, 20 That never happened. 5, 13 I faked it.  She says, “You need to start in the gospels. 6, 14, 17 Start with John.  From there,” she said, “Once you get to Revelation stop. 13, 14, 20 Then go and read Genesis and read through that.” 7 I did it and I read through it. 7 I sat there day after day for hours and hours and read the Bible word for word. 7, 19 I did not miss one word.  I figured at the very end there was going to be some kind of an epiphany or knowingness. 7, 17, 19 A spell or a potion. 10 I don’t know. 17 I had this strong urge that I had to read every word. 7 Even in books where all they did was recite the family lineage. 7, 15, 19 I read every word to the best of my ability figuring there would something. 7, 13 “You faithful son! 17 Here is your reward. 7 There was a reward. 7 My faith grew so that today I do believe there was a man that walked this planet and was God incarnate who had every attribute of the living God and took upon himself every single sin past, present, future, and died an innocent man. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 17, 19, 20 When I talk about it it does get me. 6, 20 I’m appreciative of that. 7 I can’t think about how I could do that.  If I was asked to do that—no.  Of course not.  I don’t even stop to give people on the side of the road money let alone die for them. 7, 9, 11, 12 It gave me a perspective. 18 It opened my eyes and really got me to understand what it means to care for somebody other than myself. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 20 That was new for me up to that point. 6, 10 I was so busy trying to survive that I didn’t give a shit about anybody but me. 10, 11, 19 Reading the scriptures made me go, “Here is this man who is God and could stop time altogether, but he didn’t. 7, 11, 13, 16, 19, 20 He took it all and never once complained. 13 Here I am this little human complaining and whining: “Early recovery is hard.” 6, 7, 8, 20 I don’t know, it really helped. 6, 7, 8, 17, 18 It made me want to share it and go give it to someone else. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14 I contacted this pastor in Sleepy Eye and I said, “Would you mind if we gathered at your church on Saturday nights? 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 19 It would be me, my wife, a couple of other people who are in recovery. 7, 8, 12 We will bring our guitars down and we are just going to do some music, hang out, and talk about recovery and how God is a part of that. 5, 6, 7, 8 Is that okay?” 14 “Yeah, sure.” 7 We started with just that and it grew to one hundred and fifty people in just six months. 6, 7, 11, 15, 19 Pastor  Al recognized what was going on and took me under his wing. 7 The Southern Baptist Convention through the Dakota Baptist Convention recognized me and sent their guy out to underwrite our ministry. 6, 7 They funded it.  They gave us money every month to help us buy equipment and travel and train me. 7, 12, 18, 20 Within a short period of time, in 2007 7, 16, 19 I became ordained. 13, 17 AS: In the Baptist Church?  By this time we have our own church and congregation of about one hundred and nine people. 7, 16, 19 We are doing youth group every week, clothing drives, food drives, and we are speaking on the behalf of people in recovery in the church community to let them know, as I learn more about what drugs and alcohol can do to a human being, how to be mindful. 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16, 17, 18, 19 How to navigate this whole thing. 19 We told them, “Throw your old medications away, take them down to the police station because I will come to your house and steal them. 9, 11, 13, 16, 17, 20 I will eat them all and I will die.”  I would show up in the church with my vest and my tattoos and they would immediately be dumbfounded by the level of intelligence and then what I looked like. 9, 11, 12, 13 That’s the demon of meth. 10, 12 AS: You had the church for how long? 7 WL: Almost three years. 16 It grew into this really cool thing. 6, 7, 8, 19 Towards the last eight to ten months we had ‘normies’ come in—people that were seeing— AS: Before this had been pretty much people in recovery? 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, 14, 17 It was one of these recovery churches? 7, 8 WL: We called it a recovery bar. 7, 8, 12, 13, 14, 17 We got kicked out of that Lutheran Church on the 364th day. 11, 19 We were about to recognize one year and they came to me and said, “Wade” —and they wouldn’t call me pastor— “You guys are going to have to go. 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 We found cigarette butts out front and that’s not going to be acceptable.” 7, 11, 18 “Where are we supposed to go?” 14 “That’s not our problem. 7 I’m sorry, you just have to go.”  AS: Wow.  Because you had a very large crowd?  WL: People from Sunday morning were coming on Saturday night. 7, 9, 19 AS: And then not coming on Sunday. 7, 19 WL: That’s right. 8, 14 AS: When did you get the tattoos? 20 WL: Not until I got sober.  I didn’t get my first one until I was clean. 12, 15, 16, 20 I was arrested once. 7 Remember I told you I went to jail one day? 13, 16, 19 I went to jail one day and they took a mug shot. 13, 19, 20 I watched them take everyone else’s that was in line with me, and they made them take off their shirts and they took pictures of their tattoos. 7, 8, 13, 15, 20 I swore as a person dealing dope and running guns and doing stupid crap I was never going to get a mark on my body. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 17, 20 Too easy to recognize. 7, 11 This solidifies my recovery. 7, 8 Now I am very recognizable; it is hard to forget me. 6, 7, 18, 20 Hard to forget. 20 I want to mark myself. 14 I am marked with the cross literally because now people go, “That guy is marked with the cross, marked with a Jesus on his arm, he’s got scripture, how he has battled sin and wants to do the right thing. 6, 7, 8, 14, 17, 19 If it’s not him that does it is the sin that does it.”  I want to be recognized. 7, 14 I don’t want there to be a chance to ever go back to that life. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 I want to be marked. 14 AS: Would you mind sharing the scripture? 6, 7 WL: Corinthians five seventeen.  Romans six and seven.  Romans seven is  Paul talking about his battle with sin. 6 If you take it and replace the word sin with addiction it makes perfect sense. 7, 8, 9, 15, 18, 20 It is the addiction within me that does these evil things. 5, 8, 15, 19 “Oh what a wretched man that I am. 7 Who will free me from this life that is dominated by addiction?” 7, 8, 15 Thank God the answer is in Jesus.  That is what Pastor  Al showed me when I was in that treatment center that time. 7, 9, 13, 16, 18, 19 He challenged me.  He said that addiction was in the Bible. 8, 13, 14, 15 I said, “Yeah, right. 8, 13, 14 He said, “Replace the word addiction with sin in that paragraph.” 8, 13, 14, 15 The more I read it the more I started to cry. 6, 7, 15 I was like, “You mean Paul was an addict?” 9, 14, 15 “I don’t know if Paul was an addict, but the battle is the same, isn’t it?” 15, 17 He’s doing something that he doesn’t want to do. 14 Oh what a wretched man that I am. 7 Who will free me from this life that is dominated by all of this? 7, 8 Everything fell in line.  At the end of the three years in ministry, a lot of it had to do with normal, regular people that have great intentions, came in, and their traditions were not seen there because we didn’t do communion. 5, 7, 8, 13, 16, 17, 18 AS: You didn’t do their Baptist traditions.  I don’t have a comfort in that.  AS: So did the Baptist Church hear of you and then— WL: Pastor 14 Al took me under his wing and taught me all things. 5, 19 AS: Is he a Baptist minister?  WL: He is with the Dakota Baptist Convention.  Part of the Southern Baptist Convention.  I’m trying to think of the executive director’s name. 7, 11, 14 He was told by Pastor Al that he had this young protege and his is just sharp. 6, 13, 16 He is on fire for the Lord. 7 He has this gift of gab.  Man, he can preach up a storm. 7 He just brings it and the emotion behind it.  You’ve got to go see him. 5 He comes to Sleepy Eye and he sits in the pews like a visitor. 7, 17 Afterwards he goes, “Wow.”  I said, “What?” 13, 14 “You have a gift.”  I said, “Thank you. 13, 14 He introduced himself and said he wanted to underwrite my ministry. 13, 14 I said, “I don’t know what that means.” 13, 14, 17 “We will give you money.” 7, 11, 12 “Okay.”  [laughs] 10 “We need that.  What can we do with the money?” 7, 12 “Anything you need.”  “We need a trailer so we can go to a different church once in awhile on Sunday mornings to bring the message.” 7, 9, 15, 18, 19 It turned into a huge production. 18 It turned into a five piece band and a ten thousand dollar PA system and soundboards and computers and a board of directors. 7, 18, 19 “Normie” church.  We just started this thing with guitarists hanging out talking about what recovery really means and why it is so important to— AS: Have a spiritual life? 5, 6, 7, 8, 15, 19 Then it turned into money. 7, 12, 18 It turned into, “I want you to do a baptism for my grandson. 14, 17, 18 I want you to marry so and so. 14 I want you to do communion. 14 I want you to do a mass.” 14 Whoever came in with ten thousand dollars to donate wanted me to do something different for their family or their stuff. 7, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19 They thought themselves to be significant enough because they donated. 10, 16, 20 Pastor Wade will just do it.  AS: How long did it take you to figure out it wasn’t working? 7, 20 WL: Three years. 16 I told the congregation I was leaving. 7, 13, 16 I told them we had lost our mission and it doesn’t look anything like Set Free anymore. 7, 13, 16 AS: Set Free was the name of it? 7, 11 I just said I was done. 12, 13, 14 I’m going to go to graduate school now. 11, 17 I graduated with my four year degree. 7, 11, 16, 19 I didn’t start college until a year after I was sober. 6, 16 AS: How old were you? 16 I started my bachelor’s because my wife said, “You’re so smart. 6, 7, 12, 13, 14, 15, 20 I said, “You’re wrong. 6, 7, 13, 14 I’m not as smart as you think I am. 20 I’m a manipulator.  I’m really good at getting what I want.” 6, 7, 8, 14, 15, 19, 20 She said, “Do one class. 6, 12, 13, 14 It’s no big deal.”  “Fine, I’ll do one class.” 6, 12 I did one class. 6, 12 AS: What was the class? 6, 12 Was it psychology?  WL: Well, my undergrad is in human services; management. 15 It was probably literature or English or a writing course. 7, 12, 13 AS: But you liked it? 9, 14 Well, I had to take the textbook and set it next to the dictionary because every other sentence I did not know any word. 16, 17, 19, 20 The first word I had to look up was efficacious. 16 This is how far down the socioeconomic scale I came from. 9, 13, 17 Efficacious is not a word that my people use. 9 What are you talking about? 6 Even to know the definition wasn’t enough because it didn’t settle with me. 16, 17, 20 I didn’t get it. 20 Today I think learning is so great. 5, 7, 8, 19 The first class I got an A. 6, 12, 16 My excuse was that it was an easy class. 6, 9, 11, 12 The second one I got an A and I told my wife that everyone in that class got an A. 6, 12, 13, 16 It was an easy school. 11 It was a crappy school. 11 The third class I got an A in. 6, 12, 20 The teacher was a pushover and she didn’t care. 7, 14, 20 The fourth one I was sitting with peers and I was saying the same thing. 7, 12, 14, 18, 19 This girl with tears in her eyes looks at me and said, “If you say one more fucking time that this is easy I’m going to slap you. 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 19 I got a C last class.” 6, 12 That helped me. 18 Immediately I was like maybe Colleen is right. 8, 14, 16 Maybe I have some smarts. 20 I got through the bachelor’s and graduated with honors. 11 I went on to my master’s degree and took another master’s at night while I was going that. 7, 19 I got to meet Marv Seppala, the chief medical officer at Hazelden [Betty Ford Foundation]. 11, 18 We became weight room buddies and started talking about neurology. 6, 9, 13, 15, 17 He told me about addiction neurology for free as I taught him how to lift weights. 7, 8, 13, 15, 16 AS: You just happened to meet him? 5 WL: He is the chief medical officer at Hazelden. 11, 18 AS: Right, but how did you meet?  WL: I was a student there. 11 As he walks in I was like, “Hey, Dr. Seppala. 9, 14 “It looks like you lift weights!  I could never gain weight.” 13 “Well, you’re an ectomorph and this is why. 7 You need to eat this way and lift like this and you will put on a few pounds but you are never going to get huge, but you can feel better about your body.” 13, 17, 18, 19, 20 “I’ll tell you what I’m going to be in here every so and so. 13 Do you want to come in and talk about addiction and you can show me how to do this.” 6, 8, 9, 14, 15, 17 Done. 12 I got a free tutor. 7 That was the two years following ministry. 16 I stayed up in Center City during the week and came home on the weekends. 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 I became kind of an uncle to my kids. 13, 15, 17 My wife started drinking to cope with being a single mom. 6, 7, 12, 15, 17, 19 My meeting structure shifted. 6, 7 I maybe went once a week. 16 My eating disorder flared. 5, 7 I have been bulimic since I was twelve.  I learned how to meet weight when I was wrestling. 5, 7 Having low self esteem from growing up how I did was a way to keep my body composition in check. 5, 7, 17 I could binge purge and I wouldn’t drink or use when I was doing that. 9, 19 I did that pretty badly during graduate school. 5, 7, 11, 14 I got really thin and exercised twice a day. 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 I was feeling shitty about being a dad that’s not there, but trying to get to the next level of my life because I have to do this. 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 It wasn’t something I felt like I could do—I had to do it. 6 I felt compelled to do it. 6 Got to graduation day and got it done. 19 The only people there for graduation was my wife and my inlaws because five years prior to this I cut my mom, dad, brother, and sister out of my life for six years. 7, 8, 12, 14, 16, 17 I couldn’t have their chaos in my life anymore. 7, 8 AS: Which had continued? 19 WL: Just because I quit drinking doesn’t mean that that stopped. 15, 19 Her gambling and her lying and manipulating. 12 My brother’s meth use and my sister’s—I don’t know. 9, 10, 12, 16, 17 She had several children with different men who were addicts. 7, 9, 13, 15, 18 It was just never a healthy scenario. 13 There were six years where there was no contact whatsoever. 13, 16 Not even a phone call. 12, 14, 17 We lived in the same town, so we would see each other and not say hi. 5, 11, 14, 16 Two years at grad school and then for the three years following that I was at Project Turnabout in an intensive inpatient treatment center there working with gamblers for the first two years and with chemically dependent for a year after that. 7, 11, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18 Nine months after that I was in public mental health at Sioux Trails in New Ulm. 11 Just this last October I gave notice and said I was going to start a treatment center. 6, 7, 13, 14, 18 I had no idea how to do that or if that could ever happen. 5, 13 I prayed about it and quit. 19 I had the gift of gab and we could make this happen. 5, 18 I’ve been talking to people, our policies and procedures have been submitted, the building has been bought, the outpatient building has been bought, furniture has been bought, and the employees have been hired. 6, 7 We are just waiting for two licenses and we are ready to go. 7, 18 AS: In Montevideo?  AS: What kind of a treatment center? 7, 13, 18 Then can you talk about your work with trauma? 6 This is going to be a mixed cohort of men and women. 12 There will be ten in the inpatient center.  AS: There is inpatient and outpatient?  WL: We have an inpatient and an outpatient, two sober homes, and a gambling unit all at the same time. 7, 16, 17, 19 All or none! 12 The inpatient treatment center is a six bedroom, four bath home. 7, 9, 13, 17, 18, 19 It is forty-six hundred square feet. 7 This is in a residential setting. 7, 9 It is a beautiful, big house. 9, 11 Ten folks in that place. 8, 17 We are going to focus on trauma using excelleration therapy. 10, 18 We are going to treat trauma first, and then we are going to treat chemical dependency second. 7, 16 I am very much in belief that chemical dependency is a coping strategy for whatever got you there.  Very seldom do you see the organic alcoholic where they take that first drink and say, I love that and I have a supportive enviornment. 5, 9, 10, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20 My parents loved me, I had everything that I needed—well, that can be a problem too. 7, 8, 9, 12, 17 I firmly belive that trauma is the nucleus of compensatory behavior such as drinking, over eating, shopping, gambling, relationship addictions. 7, 8, 11, 15, 19 In some way I am getting out of dealing with the original issue, which could be in my case the childhood sexual and physical trauma. 5, 7, 9, 15, 19, 20 AS: What do you mean in some way you are getting out of it? 15, 20 WL: You don’t have to deal with it.  I don’t have to deal with the somatic responses that are procured from my amygdala from the trauma. 7 AS: What does ART stand for again?  WL: Accelerated Resolution Therapy.  The God of my understanding works like this: he always shows me things that I need to know first hand. 5, 8, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17, 19 The veteran that I worked with almost a year ago now that was committing an act of suicide caused in me PTSD. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 My symptoms were— AS: This was a man you were treating? 7 WL: I was called to an emergeny situation. 7, 13, 14, 17 I was not treating him. 7 He had put on social media that he was taking the coward’s way out. 18, 19 He was done. 12 He was not happy.  “I will be by the lone tree” was the word we got. 7, 12 I and another therapist and my wife raced across two counties to get to this place. 8, 12, 20 AS: You knew where it was? 6, 12 WL: My colleauge did.  He had a recollection as to where this was. 7 We raced to get there at ninety miles an hour to get there. 20 Behind me is a state trooper with his lights on. 17 He zooms past, so I get right behind him. 8, 14, 20 Another five miles goes by and he pulls over.  I pull over in front of him and he says to me, “What are you doing?” 14, 17 I said, “I’m going to the same place you’re going. 7, 8, 13, 14 I’m going to find so-and-so.” 9 “I’m a mental health professional.  I’m going to the scene.”  “Alright, but you can’t go faster than me.” 8, 14 I said, “Okay.” 13, 14 [laughs] 10 We got up to the spot. 10 He went past the turn off and I took a right and there were squad cars and an ambulance. 8, 14 I thought, Shit, he already did it. 6, 7, 10, 18, 19 We got behind the ambulance and my phone rang. 12, 14 It was him and he was asking me where the fuck I was.  I said I’m behind the ambulance and he told me to go up there. 13, 14, 16 I’ve got to talk to these guys and see if they can let me through the blockade. 5, 6, 8, 15 I went up to the sergeant and said, “Here are my credentials. 7, 13, 14 I’m a veteran.  Let me talk to him.” 6 “He has a weapon.”  “I understand.  I just need to go up there.”  They let me through and I spent three hours at his window. 7, 20 It got to be nighttime. 7, 16, 19 AS: What window? 20 Was he in a car? 14 WL: Sorry, he was in a car. 14 He had a gun. 10 Three hours of trying to negotiate with him.  I shared with him my military experience and his and how can I do this and then live. 7, 11, 15 How can I take that many lives and not be affected. 11, 18, 20 I was like, “Listen. 9, 14 You haven’t had the kind of therapy that I do. 18 I want to work with you and help you to get better.” 14, 17, 18, 20 I’m telling him about Accelerated Resolution Therapy which at the time I had only heard of. 7, 13, 14, 16, 19 I hadn’t needed to. 9 I had heard of other veterans who have. 7, 14 I was just telling him to work with me. 13 Anything just to get him. 20 Finally, we get down to that last minute and he looks at me and says, “I can’t. 14, 17, 20 I’m going home.” 17, 19 He grabs the trigger and I screamed as loud as I could. 7 I said, “By the blood of Christ I bind you.” 13, 14 And he stopped. 15 He cried.  He said, “If I get out of this car they will put me in jail.” 13, 14, 19, 20 I said, “If I go and get a letter that says no charges pending will you get out?” 13, 14, 17, 20 He said, “Yeah, I’ll get out.” 13, 14, 20 By this time the lieutenant is on the scene. 7, 16, 19 He said, “You’re not going back out there.” 7, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 I said, “Just give me the damn letter. 11, 13, 14 He is willing to come out.” 17 I had to negotiate with him and send him a picture to his phone. 7, 12, 14 Finally he did get out. 20 I get in the ambulance with him. 20 I fill in the social workers. 18 I told them he was a vet and these were his experiences. 13, 15, 16 Be cautious.  Just trying to give them some insight. 11 We go home. 17, 19 I’m fired up. 7 My adrenaline is off the charts. 7 I don’t go to bed that night until four in the morning. 9, 19 Three weeks go by and I start to not feel okay. 6, 13, 14, 16, 18 I don’t know what is going on with my. 17 My motivation is low, I don’t want to do much. 14 I come home at night and I just lay around. 17, 18, 19 Pretty soon I had stopped shaving, I called in sick a few days, and I start to get very angry at the drop of a hat. 5, 6, 7, 13, 14, 15, 17, 18, 19, 20 I was suicidal and I’m not telling anybody that I am and I am. 13 By this time my wife started to notice. 6, 7, 12, 15, 16, 19 She said we needed to call somebody. 9, 13, 14, 17 I started my own process of Accelerated Resolution Therapy. 6, 15 I went and got one session and my PTSD was gone. 12 It was lifted.  I walked out of there like I was pre-episode. 7, 20 I’m crying at my wife saying how sorry I was and that I didn’t even know. 12, 14, 17 I tried to explain myself as to why I was being such an asshole before.  She is such a sweetheart she just said, “It’s okay; you’re better now.” 6, 7, 13, 14, 17 I don’t deserve you.  I go back and do five more sessions. 11, 17, 19 We work on things like an old man that used to beat me with a stick and punch me and kick me. 5, 9, 16, 19 I babysitter that used to stick things in me and have sex with me when I’m little. 5, 7, 9, 19, 20 All of the bullshit I did when I left my son. 8, 10, 17, 19 I worked through that with Accelerated Resolution and I rewrote every one. 7, 12 I went and rewrote my first drink, my first cocaine experience, my first marijuana experience. 7, 10, 15, 16, 19 I don’t remember it anymore. 7, 13, 15 Can you give me a quick description of what that means? 11 WL: The reference on this is that this would be Dr. Candell and his work around dendritic spines and the protein synthesis that happens. 5, 7, 20 Images sit on the dendritic spines. 7, 15 It takes protein synthesis to activate the image in the brain. 5, 15, 20 When you recall a traumatic image it renders it unstable. 7, 14, 15, 17, 18 At that point it is maleable and can be manipulated. 5, 10, 18 When we use bilateral stimulation in the way of horizontal eye movements that mimic REM sleep we know that it reduces brain waves from a sedentary eight to thirty hertz to one to four. 5, 7, 9, 14, 16, 17, 19 My theory is that that’s what peels away the emotional response from the traumatic issue because it is like throwing icy cold water on hot trauma. 7, 16, 20 Just like that.  Immediately I went from being unable to talk about the experience to calm. 6, 15, 18 I went through the image in my mind as I was looking at the bilateral stimuation of the eye movements. 5, 6, 14, 15, 16, 19 The first time I went through it I emoted. 7, 16, 19 I emoted around the fact that I saw his chest being blown open. 6, 20 I emoted around I couldn’t save him. 18 I emoted around I’m standing here and nobody is helping me. 7, 17, 18 This colleague that I brought with me went up to the window with me and fell apart. 8, 20 He didn’t make it. 18 He saw that man and he was drunk and had a gun and my colleague couldn’t handle that. 6, 8, 10, 11, 13 He starts to weep. 6 I was like, “Dude, go tell those police officers to go tell those ones over there to shut their fucking lights off. 6, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 17, 18 I sent him away. 20 Abandonment has always been an issue for me. 7, 10 Now my best friend abandoned me to stand at this window by myself to save this guy’s life. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 20 All that tied together I worked through with the eye movements for me because it was very much connected to past stuff. 8, 11, 12, 14, 16, 20 As we rewrite it we use imagination. 7, 9 Positive images. 7, 15 We rewrite it using the same bilateral stimiulation because it is maleable and we can write new images. 5, 6, 7, 10, 15, 16, 18, 19 All we have to do is imagine it.  It is voluntary image replacement. 7, 8, 15 The therapist I’m working with said, “You could replace this now. 7, 8, 13, 14, 17 The first time through the scene is emotion. 7, 16, 19 The second time through is no emotion. 7, 16, 19 The third time through you’re the director. 7, 16, 19, 20 You can make it better. 17, 18 How would you make it better? 17, 18 You can bring angels or a higher power.” 11 My imagination was when I pulled up on the scene I walked around the corner of the ambulance and someone came and walked right in between me and my colleague. 8, 13, 14, 17, 18, 20 He’s got a big right hand. 8, 13, 14 He walks up to the window and the guy that is in the car that sees me there with none other than Jesus looks at him, starts to cry, gives Jesus a big hug, and we walk away and get him treatment. 5, 6, 7, 11, 12, 13, 14, 18, 20 When I think about that story I think about how real it is to see Christ standing there between me and my colleague at the time. 5, 7, 13, 16, 17, 19 It is a new, better image that prevents new triggers and new things. 5, 6, 7, 15, 17, 19 When I say I rewrote my first drink, instead of Derek handing me that Tab I slapped it out of his hand and I watch it roll across the street going all the way down. 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 I never drank. 13, 18 AS: Why would you say that? 14 Why does that make you feel better? 13, 17, 18 WL: Why does that make me feel better? 13, 17, 18 Why does making the right choice make you feel better? 8, 13, 14, 17, 18 AS: Are you saying that is replacing a painful memory in your brain? 5, 7, 14 That you have pushed it away? 20 WL: I’m saying that I’m no longer an addict or an alcoholic. 7, 10, 13, 14, 15, 20 AS: You know your history, clearly. 6, 13, 17 Retelling it doesn’t affect you in the same way anymore because— WL: 7, 13 I’m not ever going to use drugs again because I know today as a professional what drugs do to the body. 5, 9, 10, 13, 17, 19 Since I’ve had ART I’ve had a drink. 19 I don’t drink to get drunk. 8, 11, 19, 20 I don’t drink everyday. 19 I don’t steal from garages. 15 I don’t—right? 8, 14 I say that not to prove a point but because I’m using myself as an experiment. 10, 14 AS: I think there are a growing number of professionals in the field that are thinking the abstinence only and abstinence always attitude towards substances— WL: 9, 10, 14, 20 When I went back and ARTed myself for every first that I had, I then felt comfortable enough to have a glass of wine with my food. 6, 11, 12, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 I still felt guilty the first time. 6, 7, 16, 19 It’s been eleven years. 16 This is okay. 14 AS: Right.  What will I do the next day? 16, 19 This was October.  The first drink I had was in Tampa. 16, 19 It was with my wife in a beautiful restaurant and we had a beautiful night. 7, 12, 16, 19 I drank two glasses of wine and I didn’t think, “We should get a ball of cocaine!” 10, 18, 20 [laughs] 10 I’m not going to advertise what you should do after having ART therapy. 18 What I am going to do is give people the knowledge that the traumatic event and the compensatory behavior to eliminate the somatic response induced by that original trauma—when that trauma goes away you aren’t going to have the need to use. 7, 9, 11, 17, 20 You’re just not. 7 I’m not recommending that someone do that in the first twelve months. 7, 11, 16 I think there is a period of acclimation that needs to happen in the endocrine system because we have acetylcholine, GABA, and glutamate and our transmitters that are very important in regulating my central nervous system. 5, 7, 15 Just making sure that those things return to equilibrium and homeostasis. 5, 7, 17, 19 We know homeostasis can take eighteen months for some people who have used exponentially. 9, 11, 12, 17, 20 Give yourself that time. 7, 16, 19 It has been eleven years for me and I’m not going to revert back to the town drunk in a week. 7, 8, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 I am being very scientific about this.  I am journaling when I drink and how much I drink and what the effects are. 19 In four or five years, or less than that, when ART becomes the go-to modality for the world I’m the first. 12, 16, 17, 18 I am the first addict or alcoholic that has some kind of documentation that says this works. 8, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17 What does that mean for AA and NA?  I don’t care. 7, 14, 20 I don’t think those fellowships will ever go away because it is great to come together beneath one— AS: Yeah. 7, 8, 11, 13, 16, 17, 20 It is the support. 9 Can you talk about the ear thing? 6, 19 I looked it up but I would like to have you describe it. 9, 13, 14 WL: The bridge is a device that was created for the sole purpose of pain relief. 7 It was originally created for people dying of cancer. 7 They had dire pain. 7 A doctor recognized this opiate addict that was having this pain and utilized this machine on the opioid addict. 5, 7, 15, 20 He found out that it attenuated his opioid withdrawal symptomatology. 5, 11 He took it off of him and the symptoms came back. 11, 13, 17, 19 They created this device called the Bridge. 7, 13, 14, 17 I wish we knew we were going to talk about this because it is such a new science and it isn’t my specialty. 6, 12 I don’t have all of the details.  AS: That’s okay. 14 Just that you are considering using it. 9, 10 WL: Yes, we are going to use this. 9 It has been FDA approved, not that that says a lot. 14, 17 AS: Same with Oxy!  [laughs] 10 It does attenuate the withdrawal effects up to 62.8 percent in twenty minutes. 14 AS: It is a medical device? 11 WL: Right.  No drugs are used. 9, 10 It is an electronic device.  It sends an electric signal through the cranium into the amygdad reducing the amygdala’s response by fifty-two percent. 7 The amygdala is the fight or flight, freeze or faint. 7, 13 It is also affecting other areas of the brain such as the hypocampus to reduce symtomology. 5, 7 Imagine if you would jsut for a second offereing to an opiate addict like myslef, “Okay, listen. 7, 15, 16 You can be clean and it won’t cause any pain. 9, 15, 16 Are you interested? 7 Yes or no.”  I would have said yes. 9, 13, 14 No pain whatsoever? 13 Well, you might get the shits. 10, 19, 20 Other than that, no pain.  On day five they are boasting ninety five percent. 19 AS: That is phenomenal.  WL: There are videos.  I will forward you the videos so you can watch these patients prior to and after having this device put in. 15, 19 they wear the device for five days and in that five day period they become biologically clean. 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 At the end of the fifth day we transfer immediately into medication assisted therapy [MAT]. 12, 16, 18, 19 Our treatment center is going to specialize in MAT. 7, 13, 18 We are working with an addiction psychiatrist for prescriptions. 7, 8, 15 We will be doing a lot of telemedicine because of our location.  AS: Are you going to do Suboxone? 12 WL: Suboxone, right. 8, 14 Suboxone is the only thing I am comfortable with. 18, 19 I am not as comfortable with methadone. 18 It just has too long of a half life and has no naloxone in it. 7, 8, 12, 16 I don’t want to take the risk of someone being on that and then using because they will die. 10, 14, 20 It has happened so many times. 5, 7, 16, 18, 19 That is our focus.  The ten inpatient group will come in as a cohort: they will get there together and leave together. 11, 16, 17, 18, 20 It is not going to be the same— AS: You gain a person, you lose a person. 10, 13, 17 WL: Nope.  You come in together and you leave together. 11, 16, 17, 20 AS: What if someone leaves?  WL: We aren’t going to fill another bed.  Tough.  AS: If it is down to three people— WL:  Then it is the three survivors.  That’s right. 8, 14 It is like a platoon.  AS: You will also be using a different financial model, as well. 7, 8, 10, 18 WL: We are using funding from the state. 10, 17 We are going to refund money when it comes down to— AS: You might be using money from the state but if people leave you won’t be getting money anymore. 7, 10, 12, 15, 17, 20 You’re taking a new approach. 6, 7 WL: God is our financer.  Do you think I’m kidding? 15 I’m not kidding at all. 15 Watch him do it.  I want to share something with your listeners. 7, 14 Probably a couple of graduate students that are writing this up for you— AS: Undergrad. 7, 11 WL: Undergrad.  Oh my gosh you are getting them young. 6, 15, 20 AS: They are very smart. 20 Great typers. 7 WL: Smarter than most.  Great typers. 7 Very educated.  Here is something you will be entertained by.  I left the public mental health clinic in October. 8, 11, 19 My mantra was:  I am going to outgive God. 11 I am going to work until God is made to look a little foolish for not giving. 13, 20 AS: Are you challenging God?  [laughs] 10 WL: A little bit. 20 What is the impact on you?  WL: Here is what happens. 5 He’s already blazed away. 6, 7, 18, 20 He introduced us to a donor; the patriarch of this family. 7, 19 He owned a goldmine. 16 When I say goldmine he literally owned a goldmine. 14, 16 He left for the wife, the children, and the grandchildren a trust. 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 19 They decided to spend all the amounts of money they have to spend in order to reduce their taxable responsibilities on recovery in Montevideo. 7, 8, 12, 18 I don’t know how much that is yet because we haven’t been given the check, but she asked us what we needed and we rattled off, “We need a van for this, we need a sprinkler system in the homes, medical devices.” 9, 11, 15, 17, 19 AS: Did they buy the house, too? 9, 11, 20 WL: No, we bought the house. 9, 11 This is what I mean by God has bypassed anything I could do. 9, 17 The house was already zone R4 when we bought it. 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 18 We didn’t know that. 17 WL: Residential 9 Four mean that it is ready for occupancy for the levels we want it to be. 7, 9, 14, 18 Otherwise we would have needed a conditional use permit from the city. 9 I even went to a city planning zoning meeting and one of the people there said, “I’m sure there will be a public hearing on this.” 6, 7, 11, 13, 14 The city manager said, “No, there won’t because it is already zoned R4. 6, 7, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18 We wish Recovery 101 all the best.” 13 [laughs] 10 I was like you’ve got to be kidding me. 15 I walked out of there in five minutes and it was done. 12, 14, 20 There is nothing they can do to stop us.  We have people coming out of the woodwork to help. 7, 18 There has not been one bump.  It has everything to do with the opiate issue that is going on. 7 AS: The people in the area. 7 We’ve got Dr. Willenbring that is doing all of our scripts.  Shelley Alkington is our board president who lost her daughter at age twenty-six to opiate overdose just last year. 5, 7, 9, 14, 15, 16 She has a bill at the House right now that would add a certain percentage to—don’t quote me here—but I think every microgram of opiate that is prescribed. 7, 8, 9, 14, 15, 17 She came up with that. 13, 17 AS: A tax?  WL: It’s a tax.  If that happens that will mean literally millions of dollars, if not close to a billion dollars, in relief for treatment in Minnesota. 5, 6, 7, 13, 18 AS: That’s like cigarettes and the tobacco companies. 7 WL: How many therapy facilities do we have? 18 Less than a handful. 13 AS: We don’t even have enough treatment beds. 7, 13, 16, 18, 20 We don’t have enough sober houses and we don’t have enough—people should not have to wait a second when they say they are willing to go in. 9, 11, 14, 16, 20 Now that we have this bridge device, now th