h you and your therapist, or you and your healers and stuff. 17 It's more private. 5 But when you're running in public view, your traumas come out for everyone to see. 5, 8, 9, 11, 17, 18 And they wanna use those traumas to help push your agenda, right? 8, 9, 14, 15, 18 But what they don't understand is that it's a bare naked feeling. 7, 12, 13, 17, 18 You revealed everything about yourself to the world. 7, 12 And I wasn't ready for that. 7, 18 That was the hard part. 6, 8 I wasn't ready for that. 7, 18 I didn't know that that's what I was signing up for at the time. 7, 16, 17, 19 That I was, I really thought that I could run and not have to tell my story and not have to tell people that I was a user, that I was sexually abused, that I was you know beaten as a child, that I was homeless for four years... you know? 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17, 19 I didn't know that I had to tell everybody that. 13, 17 And, when I was running it all had to come out. 8, 9, 17 And how did you deal with it?  MO: It was extremely hard to deal with [laughs]. 6, 7, 10 It was very... painful?  Because it was a public pain. 11 And it... how I dealt with it was mostly... 5 I tried to remember that all of who I am, those traumas are me. 7, 13, 15, 18 They made me who I am. 13 And I, I needed to use that. 9 I've been using it all this time to help my community. 7, 10, 16, 18, 19 I've been using all my traumas all this time to make a different life for everyone in my community. 7, 8, 10, 16, 18, 19 And I just needed to remember that and continue to remember that whenever people would you know, at the doors some people would, you know like say: ""You don't have no business running."" 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 You know, ""You have no business running. 8, 9, 12, 17 You're just ...all you are, you're just full of all this trauma. 7 You're just one trauma"" [laughs]. 10 But, the thing was, the thing was, I had to fight against that stigma. 13, 19 SP: So it must have been very public. 11 I mean, I can only imagine to the degree that I have been you know, publicly involved working in community, but never in a political sense. 7, 9, 11, 13, 17, 19 And having to share information, and then you get people's response. 7, 20 I mean like, it must have been, I can't imagine. 9, 14 I mean like... like... MO: 9, 14 People thought, there were some people that thought that I was running just for people to feel sorry for me or something. 8, 9, 10, 13, 18 SP: And they would say things like that? 5, 14, 19 MO: Mhm, mhm.  And it was more so, it was more so like, me trying to prove myself to people. 9, 14 That I'm different. 7, 18 I'm not my past. 8 I'm not my traumas. 18 My traumas don't define me. 14, 18 They help push me, but they don't define me. 14, 18 I had to prove that to people time and time again. 7, 16, 19 And it was because of all the interviews.  So I was the first Little Earth resident to ever run for public office. 7, 8, 9, 11, 13, 16, 18 We've never had a Little Earth resident that ever ran. 7, 9, 13 So, for me to be the first I had a lot of interviews. 16 A lot of interviews from different you know radio stations, to reporters, to newspapers. 6, 7, 17, 18 And it was being the ""first,"" that's where my story had gotten out, of who I am. 7, 13, 16 And that's how everybody found out. 11 And that's how everybody saw me. 6 So that's, that's where it all began with the trauma part. 8 And then, that was the hardest part of my campaign. 5, 6, 8 SP: Was that the beginning of the campaign or throughout the whole campaign? 5 MO: It was more so in the middle of the campaign, towards the middle. 5, 14 In the beginning I kept it really hush. 6, 7, 8 I kept my past out of it. 8 It was my campaign team that wanted to have me talk about my issues with a reporter. 5, 6, 7, 14 Talk about my past traumas with a reporter. 7, 8, 18 And it was my campaign team that thought it would be best because that's what made me stand out from all of the other candidates. 5, 10, 13 There were seven candidates running in my race. 8, 9 So, to make me stand out, what made me different from all of them was my life, my life story. 7, 8, 13, 18 That I was the only one, out of all of seven of us, that has lived this life. 7, 8, 11, 12, 16 And that has actually used those traumas to address the issues. 7, 9, 18 So, that's what they wanted to use. 9, 14 And that's what made it come up in public. 11, 13, 17 I just didn't realize how hard it was gonna be afterwards. 6, 7 For me anyway, just for me.  It wasn't, it wasn't hard for everybody else, it was more so hard for me [laughs]. 6, 8, 10 SP: Well I would imagine it was just hard for you! 6 [Ortega laughing]  And so the campaign is recently over. 5, 7 What about two months maybe? 11, 16 Not even that?  MO: Yep, yep.  It's recently over. 7 SP: And so, how did the campaign turn out for you? 5 MO: Well, I got...  no matter what my team is like ""We won!"" 5, 10 Even though we didn't win.  I had the least amount of money out of any campaign, out of all seven. 5, 7, 12 I only had ten thousand dollars throughout my whole campaign. 5, 18 Ten thousand dollars. 18 But I got, I got the most votes on election day. 19 I won primary day, I lost early vote. 6, 19, 20 SP: Wow.  Right on.  MO: Yeah, and they were all running with around 90 to 100 thousand dollars—their campaigns were. 5, 8, 9, 18 SP: How did you go about fundraising?  MO: I didn't wanna.  I fundraised right off of the doors. 5, 8, 14, 17, 19 So when I would talk to people at the doors, they would give me money right at the door. 6, 7, 8, 11, 12, 14, 17, 19 I would ask them if they would vote for me, if they would support me. 9 And then they said yes, and then I would ask them, ""Well would you be able to you know contribute to my campaign. 5, 9, 13, 14, 17, 18 You know for regular costs of printing and everything."" 7, 17 And that's how I raised ten thousand was just off from the doors, off from neighbors. 5, 17, 19 That's what I wanted. 14 I wanted to make sure my campaign was fully ran by the community. 5, 7, 14, 18, 19 I made sure that the money that we got was only from the community. 7, 12, 13, 19 Which I guess was my downfall. 11, 19 I should've accepted money from PACs and everybody else, but I wanted to make a statement. 7, 8, 12, 14, 17, 18 SP: It sounds like you did.  SP: And so, now that the campaign is over, what are you doing now? 5, 17 The two part question...and then, would you run for office again? 8, 15, 18 [Both proceed to laugh].  MO: Right now... 17 I'm gonna go back to school. 11, 17, 19 I still have a lot of contracts that I have to fulfill. 7 So, and I still have Natives Against Heroin that I'm turning into an org. 7 So, there's still a lot of work that I'm doing. 7 And then, I'm just gonna go back to school for a while. 11, 17, 19 Finish up my degree. 7, 19 And I don't think I'll run again. 8 I don't know. 17 Maybe, maybe not. 16 I know I'm, this coming next few months, I'm training other Little Earth residents to run. 7, 8, 9, 11, 16, 17, 19 SP: Fantastic.  MO: So, I got a grant to train other Little Earth residents to sit on neighborhood boards, to sit on commissions, and to also run for public office. 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 18 SP: That is fantastic. 8 MO: I'm a power builder.  I like to make sure I help lift people up. 7, 9, 14, 18 SP: And, what about school? 11 Get a degree in what? 7, 19 MO: Law enforcement is my degree. 7, 19 SP: Really?  So, can you talk a little bit about that. 6, 20 Why did you decide law enforcement? 16 [Ortega laughing].  I just didn't expect that!  A lot of people don't.  [Both laughing].  A lot of people don't!  I wanted to change the criminal justice system. 5, 14 So I started my degree back in, 2013? 6, 7, 11, 15, 17, 19 I went to college.  I started it out but I never finished. 6, 13, 15 I dropped out of college so that way I could you know raise my daughter. 5, 17 She was going through a lot of health problems at the time. 7, 16, 19 So I stopped school to take care of her. 7, 11, 14, 15, 20 And then, from there I went on working and then started on doing all of this community organizing stuff, so that just became a farther priority. 6, 9, 13, 15, 17, 19 But my degree, my major, has always been law enforcement. 7, 10, 16, 19 Only because of the police brutality that was happening in my community, and to a lot of my family members. 5, 7, 17, 19 I wanted to change the criminal justice system from the inside. 5, 9, 14 So I thought I would become a cop to do that. 10, 17, 18 So I will go finish my law enforcement degree. 7, 16, 19 Then go to the U of M for criminal justice.  SP: Right on.  And so, do you think, like at some point working within the criminal justice system somehow other that a cop? 10, 17 Or do you think it's really, or do you wanna be a ""peace officer""? 6, 7, 8, 11, 18 I think that's what they're often... 18 MO: Mhm.  No, I don't wanna be a peace officer. 11, 18 I will do something different within the field. 7, 18, 20 I'm, at first I wanted to be a ""peace officer"" and then reach detective. 11, 14, 16, 18 But then I was like, that's just... 9, 14 I wanna be there before the problems occur. 7 I wanna be able to address it before everything gets to the point of, you know... 7, 9, 10, 17, 18, 20 I don't wanna be there afterwards.  After all is said and done, and everyone is already hurt and families are already destroyed. 6, 7, 13, 14, 15, 18 I wanna be there to help fix families. 15, 18 I wanna be there to help address the traumas that our criminal justice system does to our families. 7, 9, 15, 18 'Cuz there's, not matter what, I get it people make mistakes. 10, 18, 20 We're human beings.  But I also understand that, we also have other human beings that are connected to us.  If we throw someone in prison, when we throw them in prison like that, their children suffer, their families suffer. 7, 8, 9, 15, 17 They are in prison just as much as their family member is in prison. 7, 8, 17, 19 And we need to be addressing, how is it that we keep... how do we minimize the trauma for the families that are going through this system? 7, 9, 15, 17 We do understand that he or she has a price to pay. 18 We understand that.  But we have to minimize the trauma.  How can they still parent? 7 We have to allow them to still be a parent. 7 We have to allow them to still... if it's us providing rides for their kids to go here, to see their parents on a weekly basis. 5, 7, 12, 15, 16, 17 If it's doing live Skypes so they can see their kid's dance recital. 5, 7, 11, 15 You know, like, if something we have to do something to minimize and allow them to still be parents while they're incarcerated. 7, 9, 12, 14, 17 SP: I would agree with you a hundred percent. 7 MO: 'Cuz they should be able, we could do Skype videos, you know? 17, 18 Like have some [laughs] 10 ""It's my kid's first soccer game."" 15, 16 ""Well guess what? 19 You're gonna sit here and watch your kid's soccer game. 7, 15 Like you're still in prison but, here's your kid's soccer game."" 7, 8, 15, 17 You know? 17 You can still be a part of that, in some type of way. 7, 8 We need to be providing something to help minimize this, because we're just, we're creating a generational trauma that is continuing to play out with a lot of our communities. 7, 18 SP: Are you a leader in the broader Native community in Minnesota? 19 MO: Yes.  SP: Well that's fantastic. 8 MO: Yes.  It's not just the Native community. 19 Ever since my campaign it's all over Minneapolis. 5 I wouldn't call myself a leader, I'm more so just an advocate. 14, 17 I just like to help people. 9, 14, 18 It fills my soul.  It's one of those things where you say like, if you don't like a job you're not gonna stay there very long, but this is one thing where helping people, it fulfills me. 5, 7, 9, 14, 18, 19 Where I go home, and I feel like I've done good. 6, 13, 17, 18, 19 I've done what I needed to do for the day. 9, 19 And then I can wake up the next day and do it again, and feel good about it. 6, 13, 16, 18, 19 I've had plenty of jobs where... 15 I worked in a homeless shelter. 12, 17, 19 It was the hardest job I had. 6 I told myself I'll never do it again. 13, 16 I worked in a youth homeless shelter for Native kids. 12, 15, 17, 19 And, the shelter would take children—it would be child protection—would take children away from their parents. 7, 9, 12, 20 And they would put them into this, our shelter. 19 And, having to see them, their little faces crying for their parents. 5, 7, 12, 20 All they want is love. 14, 17 And you can see it, and you can feel it. 5, 13, 18 That's all they're yearning for, is their parents' love. 7, 12, 16, 17 I couldn't be a part of that. 8 I couldn't be a part of holding them from their families. 8, 15, 16 All I wanted was for them to have their parents. 7, 12, 14 And when I had to see that, and deal with it every day, I told myself I needed to do something different. 5, 7, 9, 13, 16, 18, 19 I can't be a part of this. 8 I can't hurt these babies. 14 They didn't deserve it.  They didn't do nothing wrong for them to have to be sitting in a shelter, wondering what's gonna happen to them. 5, 6, 7, 18 They shouldn't be worried about what's happening to them. 5, 7 So that's, it just reminded me of boarding schools all over again. 6, 7, 11 SP: I can understand why.  I suspect that many people see you as a leader despite your protest that you're just an advocate [both laugh]. 5, 13, 18 And especially for women, and for Native women. 8, 12 You know, I think that for me, I think a lot about, well certainly harm reduction is something I believe in. 7, 8, 9, 14, 17 I've worked in for over twenty years. 12, 16 But my focus, and my emphasis has always been around women. 10, 12 Not to exclude men, but women, women identified, and trying to create positive change for the lives of women, and that are pregnant and parenting, and no access to resources, and desperate. 5, 7, 11, 12 So, I'm wondering...  MO: Women that are incarcerated have harsher sentences than men. 14 SP: Yes.  MO: They get longer sentences. 7, 20 And it's, it pissed me off when I was in college.  I argued with a lot of my instructors in college.  I know I'm going back to go argue again [both laugh]. 11, 17, 19 Because it was, it's discriminatory.  It's discrimination.  And we have a protective class against discrimination against sex. 6, 12 But yet, our criminal justice system can blatantly and openly discriminate over and over and over again. 15, 20 And no judge, no one, gets held accountable. 12, 18, 20 Especially when these women have children, or they're giving birth in prison. 7, 8, 9, 12, 17 A lot of children die from giving birth, from their mothers giving birth in prison. 7, 8, 9, 10, 17 The babies, some of 'em don't even survive.  And it's only because of the kind of treatment they get when they're giving birth. 7, 13, 18, 20 They're cuffed to a bed.  How would you like it to give birth, being cuffed to a bed? 9, 11, 14 That's... SP: I can't even imagine.  MO: Right?  It's just...  oh my god... like, the things that I've read. 5, 7, 9, 14, 19 I tend to take up the harsh topics in everything I do. 20 Even in college I did it.  I don't know why it is about me. 17 I take up the topics that nobody wants to talk about. 6, 14, 20 And I tend to write about 'em, and research 'em, and do what I can to figure out well how can we change it? 5, 7, 8, 12 And my instructors were always, me and my instructors were always at each other's necks [laughs]. 10 And it was only because I was always wanting to change a system. 5, 10, 14 Like this can't be happening. 5, 7 Like look at these numbers. 14 And, my instructors are always, you know like... well we'll find out how they feel when they see me come back [laughs]. 5, 8, 9, 10, 11, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19 SP: Well it sounds to me like it's fantastic. 8 Like you are really there to learn. 5, 6, 7, 8 And to create positive change for yourself and for other people. 5, 7 And it sounds like you educate your instructors.  SP: I don't know, in my experience, you know when I would do some education in schools around harm reduction like in the '90s, nobody had ever really heard of it. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 15, 17 And, it's Minnesota so abstinence is expected.  So it was a hard conversation to have, and it was like spending a lot of time explaining to people what harm reduction was. 6, 7, 9, 12, 16, 19 And it was more related to HIV and Hep-C, rather than overdose. 5, 7 So I'm curious now, like, harm reduction seems to be fairly common-place throughout the country, and in Minnesota! 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 14, 17 What is your experience like? 9, 14, 15 You know like in school, or other community places? 8, 11, 17, 19, 20 Do people know and support harm reduction? 7, 9, 17 Do you spend a lot of time explaining to them why it matters? 7, 10, 16, 19 Or what's that like? 9, 14 MO: What I've noticed, harm reduction is much more accepted in the communities of color. 7, 9 In communities of color, it's way more accepted, more looked at like yes we need this. 9, 13, 14 But when you look at the counterparts, like white society for instance. 8, 15, 19 They still believe in abstinence. 7, 9 That's where the hardest part is. 6, 8 The older white folks. 15, 16, 17, 19 It's harder to explain to them. 6 There are still some, you know cuz I, throughout my door knocking when people would ask me about my background in opiates and all of this. 5, 7, 11, 17, 19 It was more so the older white men, that would have the hardest time to accept harm reduction. 6, 7, 9, 15, 16, 19 That I was giving people a way to just continue to use and use and use and use... and to keep the drug stuff going and going. 9, 10, 17, 19 No matter what we do, the drugs will always be there. 10 And that is not because of communities of color.  That is because of our country. 10 Our country is allowing the drugs to be there. 10 They are allowing that to be shipped in.  It's just communities of color, because they deal with a lot of trauma, they deal with a lot of poverty, and poverty creates trauma, that's why drugs are so susceptible in the communities of color. 7, 10 It is not their fault, why it's here.  So, the more I tried to explain that to an older white man, for instance... 15, 16, 19 I think it's because I'm a woman of color.  That gives them sometimes the feeling of ""I don't need to listen to you,"" or ""You're not talking."" 6, 7, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 You know? 17 Being a woman, like you said, you automatically lose some type of respect from some male counterparts. 7, 8, 13, 14, 17 There are a lot of males out there that will automatically lose respect for you just because you're a woman. 7, 13, 14, 17 Being a woman of color you even lose more. 13 So, in this state it's a lot more simpler and easier 'cuz if you go out to like Georgia for instance.... 5, 17 Georgia is so far away from harm reduction. 7, 9, 20 They're still in the criminalization stage where they just wanna criminalize every.... but, I get it, they have a lot of overdoses and stuff going on over there too. 7, 13, 15, 20 But it's, it's gonna take them a while to learn that harm reduction actually helps reduce overdoses. 5, 7, 9, 18, 20 Harm reduction actually helps promote more sobriety, but that takes time to show them that. 7, 9, 16, 18, 19, 20 Because harm reduction is so big in Minnesota, we are the lab rats. 7, 9 We are the ones that will do the data, we'll be the ones to collect all this data, and then we'll start seeing the trickle effects in other states. 5, 6, 12, 17 But we have to be the first. 16 So, right now we will make all the mistakes. 8, 14, 17, 18, 20 But, it's okay to make mistakes, 'cuz we can learn from them. 5, 14, 18, 20 And, we're just fortunate that we have a lot of people in our state that believe in the same thing. 9, 17, 19 That want to be the first to try this. 14, 16 So it will take some time. 7, 16, 19, 20 We'll see it throughout the country, but it'll take time. 5, 7, 10, 16, 19, 20 Am I making sense? 9 SP: You are absolutely making sense. 9 I was just thinking about where I wanted to go with that. 14 I think that, you are such a strong, I'm sorry I'm gonna use the word leader. 9 I can see that in you. 5 Your willingness to stand up.  Your willingness to be heard. 7, 14 Your bravery and your courage just shine through. 15 And, I'm wondering, like just really I guess in many ways excited to see where you will go next [Ortega laughs]. 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 16, 18, 19 You don't strike me as a person that is necessarily content [Ortega laughs]. 10, 17 You've just got to keep moving and keep building with what you're doing, and your passion comes through. 17 I could be so bold, it's like it's grown out of your own experience. 15, 16 MO: Yes, it has.  SP: And that, you share that. 7 And that, you know your face, and how you radiate...like you're infectious [Both laugh]. 17 MO: Well, thank you! 9 [Both laugh].  SP: I would imagine that, really for younger women, for young girls, for your daughters... two of them right? 5, 6, 7, 8, 12, 14, 16 MO: Mhm.  That you are a very strong role model.  I started out mentoring kids, you know? 6, 15, 17 MO: Mhm.  My very first job was a youth mentor. 16 SP: And were they youth using drugs? 10 MO: Mhm.  [Ortega laughs]. 10 I mean like, did they expect, I mean like what was the relationship like? 7, 9, 14, 15 I think oftentimes like youth expect, you know adults to be finger wagging. 7, 16, 17, 18, 19 And, telling them that they shouldn't be using drugs. 10, 13 I mean like, what was that conversation like when you were a mentor of youth, based on your own experience? 9, 14, 15 MO: I was honest. 6, 12 I was very honest with them. 6, 12 That's really where, that's where the trust came in. 6, 7, 8, 13, 17 That's where I was able to build trust. 6, 18 The more honest you are with people, the more trusting a person can be. 6, 10, 12, 17 And then, once a person trusts you the more impact you can make on them. 6, 10, 17, 18 Especially when it comes to kids and teens. 15, 17 I was honest with them! 6, 12 Like yeah, I used. 8, 9 I used and you guys are using. 6, 8, 9, 10, 15 But guess what? 19 We can do something different. 7, 18 The more I showed them, and gave them a part of me, the more they gave me them. 8, 9, 18 So, I was able to change a lot of—I call them my kids cuz 5, 14, 15, 17, 18 I'll always look at them as my kids—I was able to change their lives. 5, 10, 11, 15, 18 There's a lot of my kids that already graduated college. 6, 7, 11, 15, 18 A lot of my kids that are already you know, I have one kid that's already almost a lawyer! 6, 7, 15, 16, 17, 18 She's got one more, like session, or like class bar she was saying. 6, 12, 14 One more test, and she'll be able to be a lawyer. 13, 16, 18 I still keep in contact with a lot of my kids. 7, 15, 17 And they still, wherever they see me they still get super excited to see me. 5, 7, 13, 20 And it's like, they're always so happy to tell me how well they're doing. 8, 9, 10, 13, 14 And how much I've helped them. 18 And it's more so listening and being a part of their story, just as much as they're a part of mine. 8, 13 SP: That's really powerful isn't it? 6, 7, 8 SP: Growing experience. 15 That's one thing that I try to explain to people a lot. 19 Life experience means way more than a textbook experience. 15 I'm gonna go back to school and go get my degree and everything, and show everybody like, yes I can do your textbooks. 7, 9, 11, 14, 17, 19, 20 That's totally fine. 14 I'll do your textbooks.  But one thing they can't do, is live the life that I lived. 7, 8, 11, 16, 19 One thing they can't do is experience what I've experienced. 15, 19 'Cuz there is a lot of lives that I've impacted. 11 A lot of lives that I've helped change. 5, 11, 18 And, I am humbled by how much people have trusted me into their lives. 6, 11 And, I am able to help them have a better life. 7, 8, 17, 18 Give them hope. 13 Cuz there's a lot of addicts out here that don't even have hope. 13, 15 And for me to be able to give them hope for another day, that we can do this another day, and we'll get through it. 11, 13, 18, 19, 20 It means the world to me. 12 It means the world to me to see the light in them come out. 5, 12, 17 SP: Thank you.  I think that's a wonderful place to end the interview [Ortega laughs]. 8, 10 I guess I should ask, is there anything else you want to add? 8, 14, 19 MO: Nope! "
"9","Devich_Stephanie","Dr. Marvin Seppala Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer Interview 2 January 23, 2019 Amy Sullivan’s Home Minneapolis, Minnesota Marvin Seppala-MS Amy Sullivan-AS MS: I'm Marv Seppala and I give you permission to record this interview. 7, 11 AS: This is January 23rd, 2019 and we are at my house in Minneapolis. 9, 11 Alright, let's go! 8, 14 So, when we left off last time, we were talking about how you went to Drake University and then you had just gotten in to medical school and one of your mentors from Mayo, was it Dr. Shepard? 6, 7, 8, 11, 16, 19 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 AS: You were talking about Dr. Shepard and I was making a joke, ""Oh, yeah, of course you got in because he was there..."" 6, 8 Or I made some kind of comment. 13 I was just listening to that.  MS: [laughter] 9 It's true.  AS: Why don't we open there? 20 You guys had been in Iowa and you were going to move back. 6, 8, 11, 14, 15, 17, 19 MS: Yes, and Linda needed to do one more year of college when I started medical school. 6, 9, 11, 15, 16 So, she stayed at Drake one more year and I started medical school in Rochester. 6, 11, 14, 15, 16 And immediately, I told all of my peers, it's a small class, just forty people at Mayo per class. 6, 12, 13, 16 It was really nice and intimate, so you get to know everybody well and all the good and bad with that, I guess. 6, 7, 8, 14, 17, 19, 20 So, I just told all my peers that I am in recovery from addiction, which the first week of class, I am just meeting these people on Monday and Friday night I was living with two other guys. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 15, 16, 19 One, who I had known from freshman year of college at St. Olaf. 7, 12, 16, 17 We both left St. Olaf and we both got into Mayo, so we roomed together and another guy from Minnesota roomed with us as well. 6, 8, 9, 11, 16, 19, 20 We just decided, well, we had a big apartment. 8 A friend of mine owned a house in Rochester and rented it out as apartments, so he let us use it. 7, 8, 9, 11, 13 Well, we threw the party at our place on Friday night and I made sure there was not alcoholic drinks, right? 7, 8, 10, 13, 14, 19 But there were all kinds of alcohol. 10, 12 And I am standing by the drinks and a guy who is now my best friend from medical school, comes up to me and says, ""Here, have a drink."" 6, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 and I say, ""No, thanks."" 9, 14 and he says, ""Have a drink."" 14, 17, 19 And I said, ""No, thanks."" 9, 13, 14 And he said, ""How come?"" 13, 14, 17 and I said, ""I'm an alcoholic, I don't drink."" 10, 13, 14, 19 And he walked away dumbfounded because he'd never met an alcoholic and he finally meets one and it is his medical school classmate and he doesn't even drink. 6, 10, 11, 12, 13, 19, 20 [laughter] 9 So, it turns out that he now works... 8, 17 he is an anesthesiologist, but he does the whole drug diversion program for the Mayo system because he took a real interest in addiction over time and was really involved. 6, 7, 8, 10, 15, 16, 19 AS: Interesting. 7 MS: And then right before Christmas, that first fall, I decided to tell the dean that I am in recovery. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 16 AS: What made you do that? 13 MS: Well, all of my peers knew, and I was really open about it and I thought I might as well just tell him, you know? 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 13, 17, 20 In case anything comes up about it, which was... 17 And I knew... 6, 12 MS: I'll tell you the story. 13 It was really problematic in an odd way. 6, 7, 8 So, I thought that they would hear so I might as well just get it out there. 8, 10, 14, 20 So, I went to his office. 18 I told him I'm in recovery from addiction. 7, 8, 13, 15, 16 I was told not to let anyone know when I applied to medical school, that I was in recovery. 7, 8, 11, 13, 16, 17 I'd never get into Mayo. 13, 20 And I didn't tell anyone, and it was a little hard in one interview, and only one. 6, 12, 13, 20 All of my volunteer activities from college were addiction related. 5, 7, 8, 15 And the family practice doc who I knew, actually, asked me how that came to be? 6, 7, 12, 13, 17, 18, 19 And because these two docs I knew at Mayo told me, they said don't mention a thing or you just will not get in. 6, 12, 13, 14, 16, 19, 20 I lied to this guy and said, something like ""Oh, we had a family issue."" 6, 7, 13, 14, 19 Which wasn't a total lie, I was the family issue. 7, 19 [laughter] 9 And he let it go at that.  So, I got through the interviews.  So, that was one of the reasons I thought I should tell the dean. 7, 10, 13, 17 AS: So, that was your conscious that was like, ""I better tell."" 9, 13, 14, 17 MS: Yeah, better to just get it out there and let him know that I am in recovery. 7, 8, 17, 20 So, he was this really gregarious Irish guy and I told him, and he just didn't say a word and he had this terrible grimace on his face. 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 16 He just kind of said, ""If we had known that, we would have never let you in here."" 12, 13, 14, 17 Really?  MS: And he never talked to me again. 6, 13 MS: There was just this tremendous bias against it. 7 AS: That you would someday be a doctor with an addiction problem? 7, 8, 15, 19, 20 MS: I guess so, that I could be an embarrassment to the school. 11, 12, 19 That someone would find out or that I would relapse or have some sort of... 7, 8, 9 AS: Did you ever hear of that book called, this is a little off topic, but called ""Thirty Rooms to Hide In""? 13, 14, 17, 20 AS: About a doctor with really severe alcoholism. 6, 7, 8, 10, 13, 20 Okay, it's by one of his children. 7, 9 MS: No, I don't know that book. 17 Really?  AS: We'll just move on and I will give you a reference for that, because that makes me really curious about why Mayo, in particular, would have that stigma? 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 18, 20 He was a pretty famous surgeon. 5, 7, 14 He was pretty well known. 5, 7, 8, 12, 14, 17 MS: It's interesting because during medical school, the Chairman of the Surgical Department was a known alcoholic. 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 17 And when I was on a surgical rotation, so I am around all of the surgeons. 18 We're going down the hall on Monday morning and there he is, and he's got this bandage across the whole side of his face. 9, 15, 19 And I am with a whole group of residents and we are with our attendant, who was a peer of the Chair of Surgeries in that department. 7, 8, 9, 18 And he says hi to him, and the chair says, ""Hi."" 14, 17 And he says, ""Wow, what happened?"", you know because he's got this huge bandage. 5, 14, 15, 17 ""Ah, the garage door was going down and I just had to run and jump under it and I just kind of fell and scraped my face."" 8, 15, 17 It made no sense at all, you know? 9, 13, 17 I mean who scrapes their face jumping under the garage door? 15, 17 AS: Yeah, that was quite a leap.  And it was known as a really angry guy. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17 AS: What was his name? 11 MS: I am blocking out his name, maybe it will come to me. 11, 16, 17 But anyway, he was well known as an alcoholic and I knew of other situations like that, and I was told that one of chairs of the board of Mayo at one time, went into treatment at Mayo for his alcoholism. 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 When he walked in, the whole staff lined up and shook his hand as he walks into treatment. 7, 13, 18, 20 Which didn't really set up a good situation for him or with his peers. 6, 7, 8, 19 AS: Because everybody knew? 6, 12 So, it was just really odd some of the stuff that went on there. 6, 7, 8 But, nonetheless, that was my introduction to my dean and he never talked to me again. 6, 12, 13 But, other than that, school went really well. 6, 7, 8, 11 And the second year, I am planning on being a cardiac surgeon, because of that lab and because of my experience with that. 14, 15, 16 You know, the guy who influenced me most was a Brazilian (?) surgeon and I wanted to be like him. 6, 14, 17 And, so that was the plan.  AS: So, you enjoyed surgery?  MS: I loved it and I was really good at it because of my experience in the lab. 6, 7, 8, 15, 17, 19 And they let me do things that they never let students do, because I could do it! 5, 11, 13, 19 [laughter] 9 Yeah, it was really neat. 6, 7, 8 So, I was just psyched about it, but I noticed on clinical rotations, all of these people with alcohol and drug addiction underlying the reason that they were in the hospital. 7, 8, 10, 12, 15, 17 Or, coincidental to it, but often underlying their hospitalization. 8, 12, 18 And we weren't diagnosing it, we weren't writing it down even.  We were not giving referrals, we were not giving consultations. 7, 20 Nothing that you would normally do for an illness, did we do. 18 So, I was going to this AA meeting in town and the same two doctors who told me not to say anything about being an alcoholic or addicted were at this meeting, they were in my home group. 6, 10, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 And that's why I asked them, because I knew them from AA. 6, 12 And they said, do not say a word. 13, 14 So, I'm going to the meeting and every weekend complaining about this situation on clinical rotations all over the hospital. 6, 7, 8, 16 There are people with addiction and alcoholism, and we do nothing about it. 8, 10, 15 It is awful. 7 And one night those two took me aside and they said, ""Marv, you've got to quit bitching about this and do something about it."" 9, 13, 14, 19, 20 And it was at that point where I kind of opened my eyes to the possibility that I didn't have to be a cardiac surgeon. 9, 10, 14, 20 As much as I liked doing it, I could do this instead. 9, 14, 18 And shortly after I had a psychiatry rotation, and they are all like one-month rotations, I enjoyed it, a lot. 8 I found an attraction to it that I didn't expect, and it was a gate way to work in addiction. 8, 11, 15 So, that's what I did and that is why I changed my mind. 5, 6 All because of that statement and that experience. 15, 17 So, then I needed a place to do that and I wanted to do an addiction fellowship. 8, 9, 14, 15 There were only a few around the country at the time. 7, 10, 16, 19 AS: A few as in only for a few people or a few different programs that were larger? \ 7, 8, 18 Yeah, only a few where you could do fellowships, that you could do an addiction training fellowship. 8, 15 So, I wanted to do a psychiatry residency and then an addiction fellowship. 7, 8, 9, 14, 15 So, I wanted to, ideally in the same place for whatever reason I thought I would want to stay in the same place. 5, 7, 8, 10, 14, 17 This is a funny part, but I applied to program on both the West Coast and East Coast for psychiatry because I didn't want to stay in the Midwest. 8, 14 [laughter] 9 For whatever reason, I thought that I might as well go to one of the coasts and Linda agreed. 7, 8, 10, 17 I made all of the applications and got rejections from every West Coast school and acceptance from every East Coast school. 7, 11, 13 And I didn't have enough money to go to both coasts to interview in both places, so I was kind of seeking direction and I got it. 5, 7, 8, 12, 16, 20 I went to the East Coast to look at all of these programs. 8 And they either had nothing going about addiction, and or, when I said I was in recovery from addiction and that's what allowed me to go down this path, they were like psychoanalytic programs. 7, 8, 13, 14, 15 So, they just couldn't even tolerate this idea that I would be... 5 AS: That someone in recovery would want to be in addiction medicine? 7, 8, 14, 15 MS: Yeah, one guy actually started to do psychotherapy with me in the interview when I mentioned that. 6, 12, 15, 18 It was just bizarre. 7 AS: Okay, so let's put a time on this. 7, 16, 19 What year is this? 16 Do you remember? 7, 13, 15 For my history of medicine pursuits. 8, 13 MS: [laughter] 9 It would have been 1984.  I graduated from medical school in 1984 and it was that winter and spring leading up to that, that I was doing those interviews. 11 AS: Would that happen today? 5, 19 MS: No, not to that degree. 7, 19 But also, this is the basic understanding. 17 I told all of the attendants on the rotation that I was on, I can't remember if it was internal medicine or neurology, but I said ""Hey, I'm going to go into psychiatry and specialize in addiction."" 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, 16 And he said, ""You're throwing away a good career in medicine."" 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 19, 20 And that was the basic feeling about psychiatry in general, but also, even more so about addiction, which nobody did. 8, 13, 15, 17, 18 Like, who would do that, Marv?  Why would you even consider it? 9 So, it was like really... 6, 7, 8 AS: I've heard that story before, from doctors that I have interviewed. 7, 13, 14, 20 MS: Okay, so it was like really going against the grain. 6, 7, 8 Yeah, it's like, why would you want to do that? 9, 14 Like, think of who your patients are going to be, was the underlying message. 12, 15 MS: Exactly.  ""It isn't even an illness"", you know? 17 AS: Oh right, you had that even. 8, 14 MS: Yeah, so I get back from the East Coast and I am just perplexed and disappointed because there wasn't a single place that I wanted to go. 7, 8, 10, 11, 14, 17, 19, 20 And I applied to the best programs in the country, you know? 8, 10, 13, 17 It was awful. 7 So, I am walking past the secretarial pool in the medical school... 6, 7, 11 AS: At Mayo?  MS: Yeah, and I knew a lot of these women because I had worked there and I grew up in the area, right? 6, 7, 8, 12, 14, 19 So, I always talked to them and one of them says, ""Marv! 6, 10, 13, 14, 17 Are you going to finish your application to the University of Minnesota?"" 7 And I said, ""I haven't started one."" 6, 13, 14, 15 And she said, ""Well I think you have."" 13, 14 So, I said, ""Sure."", because they helped us with it because we didn't have to do our own applications. 7, 13, 14, 18 Which was really wonderful. 6, 7, 8 AS: Are you kidding me? 15 I mean why as a secretary? 7 Oh my gosh, you guys were so spoiled back then. 6, 8, 11, 15, 17, 19 MS: So, spoiled.  [laughter] 9 We were just treated really well. 6, 7, 8 So, she said, ""You want to?"" and I said, ""Yes."" and she sends it off. 13, 14 And they call me, and I get an appointment for interviews and I am driving up to Minneapolis and I am half way here and it hits me. 10, 14, 17, 18, 19, 20 And I don't know what this is, or what happened, but I'm like, ""This is where I belong."" 5, 7, 9, 14, 17 It is just overwhelming.  And I get to the University and I have to park at the Medical Center and my parking spot overlooks the Mississippi there and eagle flew down below me, because you are on the cliffs, right? 7, 8, 10, 14, 20 This eagle goes by.  And I'm like, ""Wow, this is amazing."" 9, 14 It was funny because I get this sense that this is where I belong, and then I got anxious like, man, now I really got to perform this interview. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 17, 20 But then, I realize that this is where I belong, so it doesn't matter! 7, 10 [laughter] 9 However, it was just like, this is where I belong. 7, 9, 13, 14 And then the eagle.  And I go in, and the interviews go fantastic, they've got an addiction fellowship program. 8, 15 If I perform well in the residency, I can do that in my fourth year rather than adding a fifth year. 7, 8, 9, 16 Because the whole fourth year they have are electives at the U. Which is like, oh my god, that is amazing. 9, 14, 16 I can get done in four instead of five years. 16, 18 So, it was where I belonged and it's where I went. 7 And they had great people at the time, and a really robust program and a lot going on. 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 I mean, it was fantastic. 8 So, I had a great experience. 7, 8, 15 AS: So, who were your mentors there?  MS: Joe Westermier was one.  He oversaw the whole addiction department at the U, at the time and later became the Chair of Psychology at the University of Oklahoma and then came back and was Chair of the VA here in Minneapolis. 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19 And he was a true academic and over three hundred publications and books and stuff. 11 We had a Southeast Asian Mental Health Clinic and a Southeast Asian Opium Clinic at the time, because the church sponsored a lot of refugees after the Vietnam War and that included a lot of Hmong, and with those folks, a lot of opium addiction. 7, 8, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19 And they basically brought it here and there were opium dens all over the Twin Cities. 14, 17, 20 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 There probably still are. 7, 12, 13 AS: In the Seventies?  And Eighties?  MS: Yeah, Eighties now, but starting after the Vietnam War, so late Seventies into the Eighties. 5, 6, 17 And so, he set up programs during the Vietnam War. 8 He was a family practice doc and later went into psychiatry. 5, 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 He spent a lot of time over in Southeast Asia during the war. 7, 16, 19 And he actually spoke Hmong, Vietnamese, Thai, and Cambodian. 11, 18 I mean, he was an amazing guy. 6 And so, he was a true mentor and really knew addiction and really Twelve Steps stuff and had a really great program at the U. AS: I suppose he's passed? 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 15, 17 MS: No, he is still around, here in town. 7, 18 AS: Oh, my goodness, wow. 6, 14, 19 MS: He'd be worth talking to. 6 He still does some stuff at the VA, so that would be a place you could easily get a hold of him if his number isn't available. 7, 8, 10, 14, 16, 18, 20 I don't have a home phone number, I just call the VA to talk to him. 6, 12, 14, 17, 19 So, he was tremendous. 7 And then, Mark Willenbring.  Do you know Mark? 17 AS: I've interviewed him.  Twice!  I had to interview him twice, too! 16 [laughter] 9 I was going to ask if you knew him. 6, 12 MS: Yeah, Mark was at the VA.  Yeah, we're good friends. 6, 7, 13, 19 We get together a couple times a year and have supper to talk over stuff. 6, 7, 11, 16, 19, 20 But he was closer to my age than Joe. 6, 13, 15 Mark was early in his career and at the VA and was my attending when I did my addiction rotation. 6, 7, 8, 14, 15, 20 And for just a couple weeks oversaw some of my work during psychiatry rotation, too. 6, 7, 8, 16 AS: That is fantastic. 8 I love that... for my storytelling. 13, 17 To have that connection is really incredible. 6, 7, 8, 18 MS: So, it was those two, primarily, who really mentored me in remarkable ways, really beneficial. 6, 7, 8, 18 And John Brantner was a psychologist at the U who did die some time ago. 7, 16, 19 But he was part of the group that developed the MMPI. 8, 18 And John was in recovery but also just this really brilliant, eccentric psychologist and his main focus was thanatology, so death and suicide. 6, 7, 8 AS: Wow.  It's called thanatology? 13, 14, 17 And he, because he was in recovery, but also a really well-known therapist. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17 I mean, really, really well respected. 6, 7, 8 Joe Westermier was one of my psychotherapy supervisors. 18 You would do that for a year. 16 Every hour of therapy, I had to have an hour of supervision, which never happens anymore. 5, 7, 13, 18 And one year, I had John. 16 AS: So, what are you saying? 14 Repeat that again, what you had to do with the program. 8 MS: If I did an hour of psychotherapy with someone where I was providing the psychotherapy, I'd have to go do an hour of supervision about that hour of psychotherapy. 18 AS: You mean, you would have to go and talk to one of your supervisors about what had happened in that session? 5, 6 Hour to hour?  MS: Yeah, and some of them required that I record the sessions. 7, 11 Some required that I write every single word down during the session. 7 Just writing away and trying to talk at the same time. 6, 7, 16, 19, 20 I learned how to do that really well, because it was so frequent that I had to do that. 5, 6, 7, 8 That's hard. 6 [laughter] 9 AS: That's really hard. 6, 7, 8 You can see, I'm not doing that. 5 MS: No, the recording is a lot easier. 7, 11 Yeah, so those two both did that for me for a year. 16 The addiction fellowship, more than anything else, well first... 8, 15, 16 I was in my training during a time when psychoanalyses were still really a major aspect of psychiatry, but the biologic psychiatrists who were coming in, and the University had hired a biologic psychiatrist as a chair, Paula Clayton, and she was trying to change the department. 5, 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 So, they were both still there though, and they were waring with each other basically. 7, 14, 17 Which seems like that kind of conflict could be a difficult time to train, but it was wonderful because you got to hear everything. 5, 7, 10, 14, 16, 19 I got both sides of this whole issue and training from both sides, and the understanding of things from both sides. 5, 7, 8, 9, 17, 19 And there was still an emphasis on psychotherapy and biology. 7, 18 So, I thought it was awesome. 10 Some people didn't and they thought it was difficult that way, but I just loved it. 10, 17 And, I got both, which is what I wanted. 14 I wanted to be a therapist more than handing out medications, anyway. 13, 14, 16 AS: So that is also just on the cusp of when medications took over psychiatry? 8, 16 MS: Yeah, oh yeah. 8 AS: So, that's the mid-Eighties?  MS: Yup. '84 to '88 I am in my training and while I was there... 8 While I was in medical school, just to kind of put this historically, I guess, someone in infection disease came to give us a lecture one day down at Mayo. 7, 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 He said there that there is a new illness that we had just been informed about, and it was HIV. 6, 13, 14 It didn't even have a name when he told us about it. 11, 13, 16 It didn't have a name, we didn't know anything about it, not sure what is going on. 7, 11, 17 AS: This is when you were in med school? 11 MS: Med school. 11 Then in my residency, I saw the second patient with HIV at the University because the first patient attacked a nurse and just got psychotic and took her pin off her shirt and tried to puncture her with it and infect her basically. 6, 7, 9, 14, 16, 17 He was just psychotic.  So, they decided every person with this disease, again, I think they were calling it AIDS by then, but I'm not sure. 7, 8, 10, 14, 17 I can't remember when it kind of transitioned. 7, 12, 13, 15 So, they said that they had to have a psychiatric consult before anything else happens, because of this first episode. 5, 8, 13, 14, 16 Because no one knew this disease. 6, 12 Well, they made us wear space suits basically, because no one knew what this disease was or how it was transmitted. 6, 12, 13, 14, 17 So, I had to cover myself with, you know, protective garments and gloves and a helmet type thing. 12, 17, 19 I mean, everything.  Not a breathing apparatus, but you know... 7, 17, 19 I'm a psychiatrist walking in like that. 6, 8 And after a couple times of that, I just said screw it, because no one was getting sick that I saw. 6, 7, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19, 20 But still, no one knew, but it was so disruptive. 6, 7, 12 But at the same time, the pathology department at the University of Minnesota, refused to take the blood samples from these people. 7, 8, 9, 16, 19, 20 Refused to study the blood samples because they didn't know if they were at risk or not. 5, 9, 17 And so, in medicine, isn't that your job? 8 I mean the essence of risk... shouldn't you be the ones wanting to figure this out? 6, 7, 12, 14 They didn't want anything to do with it. 14 They refused. 7, 9 So, there was so much controversy going on about this.  AS: That is such a powerful story. 13 It is really bizarre that that went on. 6, 7, 8 All kinds of weird things like that. 5, 12, 19 And so, what else? 8 I was mentioning something else. 8 AS: We were talking about... 6 I was asking you about when the shift to medications in bio-medical psychiatry? 8, 11, 16 I was going to ask you, when did Prozac enter your story? 13 MS: During my residency. 7, 9 It was released for use. 7, 9 So, it was the same kind of story. 13 All of the sudden, there is a new... all we had were the old tri-cyclic antidepressants basically and the old anti-psychotics. 6, 7, 14, 16, 17 They all had a lot of side effects and people hated taking them. 9 And they worked, in fact, even now, sometimes those old antidepressants are used as the backup in nothing else works. 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 16, 17, 19 And then suddenly, there was this new medication, Prozac. 6, 16, 17 So, I just happened to be on a rotation working with the psycho-pharmacologist in the department at the time when Prozac was released. 5, 7, 8, 9, 16, 19 So, I'm like right on top of it and get to learn all about this new medication and stuff and its potential. 5, 6, 8, 10, 14, 16, 20 AS: But you were at the same time also being trained in therapy? 7, 16, 18, 19 MS: Yeah, so it was wonderful.  Because to me, that is still what a psychiatrist should do, both. 7, 8 And yet, a lot of training programs have put psychotherapy behind. 8, 15, 18, 19 It is really weird. 6, 7, 8 AS: Or completely separated them. 14 MS: Yeah, or just biological.  Just let the psychologist do it or something, I don't get it. 20 They want to just do psychopharmacology which... 9, 14 It is really a wonderful and useful tool, and necessary. 6, 7, 8, 9 And I suspect...  The brain is a new organ of study, right? 5, 6, 8, 14 There was taboo against even opening the skull and studying the brain, and yet, the rest of the body, you can open and look at and study and do whatever you wanted. 5, 7, 14, 15, 20 And so, it' been only recent that we've really had that opportunity. 6, 7, 8 It is really complex. 6, 7, 8 And so, we are way behind in a way, but it is also a brand-new field, which is one of the things that did attract me to psychiatry, it's like wow, this is... there is nothing known about this whole field. 5, 6, 8, 12, 14, 17, 19, 20 It is really wide open, and I had thoughts about academics at the time. 6, 7, 8, 10, 16, 19, 20 Which, because my parents didn't pay for any of my education, I had so much school debt that I couldn't go into academics. 7, 11, 12, 18 AS: You thought about academia for a minute and then realized that you had to be more practical? 7, 10, 14 [laughter] 9 That was a good decision probably. 6, 7, 12, 13, 19 MS: Yes!  I just couldn't do it.  Well yeah, the school debt was enough that I had to make decisions in terms of income to pay that off. 7, 8, 11, 16, 17, 18, 20 [laughter] 9 AS: So, at this point, do you have any children while you are in residency? 7, 9, 10 Or what's happening? 5, 7 MS: Yeah, well, during my internship, I had to do a rotating internship in St. Paul Ramsey to start with. 6, 8 So, my first year was at St. Paul Ramsey with all of the internal medicine and family practice people doing internal medicine feeds, ER, all of that stuff, just in case you'd decide to bad psychiatry and... but it also gave you a really solid foundation in medicine. 6, 7, 8, 11, 16, 18, 19 It gave me that. 18 And, during that, I was on all every other night in the hospital and our daughter was born. 5, 8, 19 [laughter] 9 AS: Oh, that is so much.  MS: I know, and she didn't sleep well. 8, 17 So, I'd be up all night and get home and be woken up regularly. 7, 17, 19, 20 I think I was just...  AS: And then Linda on the nights that you were gone, not sleeping, she was really not sleeping either. 6, 7, 8, 12, 19 MS: I know. 17 It was probably tougher than I noticed at the time. 7, 9, 12, 13, 16, 19 AS: Yeah, you were both sleep deprived.  MS: Yes, terribly.  And then later, Adam was born in my third year of residency. 5, 7, 9, 16, 20 It was down to every third night then. 19, 20 But it all worked out, you know? 12, 17 You just do what you have to do.  AS: It's true.  You look back on it and you can't believe that you did it. 9, 11, 17, 19 It's good that when you're in it, you just have to keep on moving forward. 6, 17, 19 [laughter] 9 Okay, so your residency is over. 7, 9 MS: So that's my background. 11, 17, 19 My background is in... 11, 17, 19 AS: It's also on the cusp.  MS: Yeah, it is on the cusp of all these new medications, all of this promise, but you know, from my own bias and my own recovery, I think psychotherapy is really important. 6, 7, 8, 16, 17, 18 AS: Right.  MS: So that's my background. 11, 17, 19 My background is in... 11, 17, 19 AS: It's also on the cusp.  MS: Yeah, it is on the cusp of all these new medications, all of this promise, but you know, from my own bias and my own recovery, I think psychotherapy is really important. 6, 7, 8, 16, 17, 18 AS: Right.  MS: And I've got this experience when I got sober of the spirituality of the Twelve Steps and the science of working in that lab, and then my college and medical school experience and residency. 7, 9, 11, 15 So, there's these somewhat diverse influences going on.  But I think they left me in a remarkable position because I was open to all of that, and not, in a single lane, kind of. 7, 8, 18, 19, 20 And I think that allowed me to do a lot in my career, that I would have maybe not otherwise been able to do, like Core Twelve, actually. 7, 14, 16, 18, 20 And when I finished training, I was looking for a job and had hoped to work for Hazelden and they didn't have any openings for a psychiatrist... 6, 8, 13, 20 AS: Because they didn't have a psychiatrist? 8 MS: No, they did have a psychiatrist. 8 They used consultants, just like a few hours in the evening and they were guys from the VA that I knew. 6, 8, 9, 12, 15 AS: So, the preeminent addiction treatment center in the state did not have a psychiatrist on staff? 7, 8, 13, 15, 17, 18 MS: No, not on staff.  Yeah, they were using these consultants. 10 AS: Can you explain why that is?  Just for people reading this? 7 MS: Oh, sure. 7 So, they had a pretty big psychology department and a lot of full-time psychologists. 5, 7, 8, 14, 16, 19 So, it was still a psychotherapy oriented mental health program. 7, 8, 18 But there were still plenty of folks coming in that had medication. 7, 16, 17 So, they had these psychiatrists come in the evening, you know, it was a consulting job, so you work all day at the VA and you head up to Hazelden for a few hours in the evening, see a bunch of patients and make sure they are okay on their medications or look at the psychotic books or someone that is suicidal and do what is necessary. 5, 7, 8, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 So, that was the bulk of the job.  Then, I knew that the guy who was running the addiction program at the VA was Dick Heilman 6, 8, 9, 12, 15 And, I don't know if Dick is still in St. Paul or not. 7, 17 I don't know if he is alive. 11, 17 I think so.  But Dick was long term recovery guy, really committed to the VA and to Hazelden. 6, 7, 8 So, I worked under him during my fellowship. 8, 12 So, he was actually a mentor too. 18 I should have mentioned him earlier. 12 And he was a mentor in that... really about recovery itself and what people needed spiritually and interpersonally to get there, you know? 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 17, 20 I remember telling me that group therapy was just as important as surgery and you cannot interrupt it. 7, 13, 15, 18 AS: Wow.  MS: Yeah, which I thought was a really nice way of describing just how important the work was, that you are doing with people. 6, 7, 8, 10, 14 That is profound. 11 MS: It is, yeah. 8 And he was always really interested in my life beyond medicine. 6, 7, 8, 10 Like, how was I leading my life and that sort of thing. 7, 8, 19 AS: Like who you were as a person? 10, 17 MS: Yeah, yeah. 8 Exactly.  AS: That's a good mentor. 6, 19 [laughter] 9 AS: I agree. 7 MS: So, I couldn't get a job here, and being born in Seattle, I somehow must have somehow imprinted on the Northwest. 5, 17, 20 And I thought, let's move to the Northwest, it would be fun to go out there. 10, 14 And Linda was game [laughter] and so I was looking for jobs in these psychiatric throw away journal things and there was a little ad for Portland. 5, 6, 9, 15, 19, 20 This little hospital there that was a dual diagnosis hospital, which was unheard of at the time in 1988. 7, 8, 14, 16, 19, 20 But they had a program and they needed a psychiatrist and when I went out and interviewed and everything and they not only wanted me to do in-patient work there, they would set me up in an office right next to the hospital to have a private practice and they could be, like the medical director had this little adolescent program about twenty minutes away. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 16, 18, 19, 20 So, I had all of these, like three different positions in one job, basically. 7, 14, 17, 18 I didn't understand...  I had to bill you know? 17 To get paid for all of this stuff in the hospital which was all new to me. 6, 8 It all worked out fine because the other guys told me how to do it and who to use if I wanted to or do it myself. 6, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16 AS: So, were you... was the adolescent part of the job a surprise to you? 8 Or had you been drawn to it because of that?  But that wasn't described until I got out there for the interview.  It was the dual diagnosis, but the dual diagnosis hospital had both an adolescent and an adult program. 8 So, it was right up my alley. 8, 14 That's how I was trained.  I knew psychiatry, I knew addiction and I got the job. 6, 8, 12, 15 AS: What was that little hospital called? 8, 13, 14, 17, 20 MS: It was Pacific Gateway.  It no longer exists. 7, 20 AS: It got eaten up?  MS: Yeah, by a bunch of condos. 19 AS: Oh, the hospital is even gone? 8, 12 MS: Yeah, it's gone. 12 It was this great program when I was there, run by people who really recognized the necessity of treating both the mental illness and the addiction in concert, you know? 6, 7, 8, 15, 17 In an integrated manner, way back then before people were doing that and they were like writing about it and stuff and teaching all about it all over. 11, 17, 19 And doing some great stuff. 7, 8 So, I just had a ball there, but the hospital was for profit, which I didn't understand at that time. 7, 8, 16, 19 I just wanted a job and didn't know the difference, really. 6, 7, 8, 14, 17 AS: So, what did that mean?  MS: Well, it got purchased by another hospital system and then they started to change what was going on, and then was purchased by another on and it got even.... and the program kind of slowly deteriorated, and people started leaving as a result. 5, 6, 7, 8, 15 Staffing diminished and then it got purchased by another.  And I had left, to do other things. 5, 8, 19 First, we were only there a year and a half, and we came back here for three years and we lived in Hopkins because I got a job at Hazelden as one of those consultants, but at the adolescent program. 8, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 So, that was my first job in the system, but it was like twice a week for three hours maybe. 16 AS: And you moved back for that? 11, 14, 17, 19 MS: I know! 17 For a six-hour a week job? 16 MS: It was crazy because I had this great situation going, I moved back to this and I had to pull all of these other jobs together. 7, 8, 11, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19, 20 So, I had a job out in Waverley, a treatment center called Waverley. 7, 13, 14, 17, 18 It was Hubert Humphrey's old home. 7, 16, 17, 19 AS: Yeah, I think there is still one out there. 7 MS: Oh, yeah, yeah, there is. 8 I got a job doing consultation there and at Wayside Women's, I was doing consultation for them. 9 A couple half way houses and a bunch of programs. 7, 8, 9, 11, 19 I was just doing like five or six different consulting jobs a week to get forty hours. 7, 15, 16, 18, 20 You were like a traveling salesman.  I would go and I would do my psychiatric evals for them and help them out and provide medications and therapy.... and I was the only one doing it in a lot of these places, you know? 8, 12, 16, 17, 18, 20 Because there are no mental health services at a lot of them, and I was it.  So, I got... the good news is as a result, I got a really broad experience, really fast. 6, 7, 8, 15, 19 And I went back to Oregon and just kept doing that kind of thing. 7, 11, 17, 19 I failed to mention, one of the jobs that I got. 15 I moved to Oregon in summer of '88 when I finished training. 7, 8, 11, 14, 17 January '89 a treatment center opened there, called Springbrook. 7, 13, 14, 17, 18, 20 Which is now Hazelden's Springbrook. 17 AS: Right, I was going to say, is that the same place? 8, 14 MS: [laughter] 9 So, it opened and they tried to just treat physicians. 7, 20 And within a year and a half went bankrupt doing so. 16 They didn't treat anyone else, only physicians, right. 7, 8, 14 And the doc who was running it was just spending all of this money and not getting enough patience. 7, 8, 9, 12, 15, 16, 20 And so, went bankrupt and one of the businessmen who had invested initially, owns the biggest dental supply company in the world, in New Borg, Oregon, right next to Springbrook. 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 16, 19 He was involved from the start. 6 Then, he bought everybody else out and reopened it and had it as a treatment center for anyone, with a specialty for physicians. 7, 8, 13, 18, 20 AS: Oh, right. 8, 14 MS: And it did much better. 17 I finally realized that I'm not getting anywhere with Hazelden, it's just this six hour a week at most. 7, 10, 15, 16, 20 So, we decide that we love Oregon and that we were going to go back, and we went back. 7, 11, 17, 19 And then I did the same thing there, multiple jobs. 15, 19 Springbrook was one of them, I did Pacific Gateway for a little while, I worked at that adolescent place for a little while, then I worked at a women's program, I worked at a Native American program. 8, 12, 20 I did consulting for the Board of Medical Examiners and you know, on docs who have addiction and stuff like that. 8, 15, 17 And then I did some for the nursing board, too.  Just throwing all of this stuff together, again, trying to get a forty-hour week or whatever. 11, 16, 20 And, [laughter] there still really weren't full time jobs in addiction for docs. 6, 7, 8, 9, 15, 16, 19 Hazelden still didn't have any and even Springbrook. 7 Springbrook and a couple of full-time docs. 7, 16, 19 They had a detox area and they liked more of a medical model, because it was started by a doc, you know. 6, 7, 9, 11, 14, 15, 17 So, they had a couple, but not psychiatrists. 7, 8 AS: Did they also focus on other professionals like pilots or? 15 People who need like licensing?  Yes.  And it was really kind of a natural that way, because all of the stuff in medicine with licensure issues was similar in the other professions. 6, 7, 8 It worked out really well. 6, 7, 8, 12 And those groups got along well too. 7, 8, 11, 15, 18 There were a lot of similarities.  A bunch of attorneys. 19 AS: Yeah, I had another doctor say that pilots and doctors, like they would rather die than lose their license. 13, 14, 15, 18, 20 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 Man, absolutely.  AS: That it is so meaningful to their identity...  that threatening that, usually gets people into treatment. 7, 13, 18, 20 MS: It does, it really does. 6, 7, 8 AS: Or that the idea of losing... 5 MS: Both are so highly trained in one thing, that... 11, 19 AS: Right, what would you do?  I know docs who have been working in restaurants and all kinds of stuff, because they have no other skills, really. 6, 7, 8, 12, 16, 17 Although, I also know some who did do, that were like techy guys on the side and they had been able to, during a period without a medical license go work for, you know, a tech industry doing something. 6, 8, 9, 11, 15, 17, 18 AS: Right.  MS: But, there's not much.  AS: Okay, so are we in the Nineties now? 17 MS: Yup, early to mid-Nineties. 6 AS: And you're still on the West Coast? 7 MS: I moved back here, this is a horrible tale, in some respects. 7, 11, 14, 17, 19 Hazelden, right after we moved back to Oregon, six months later I get a call from one of my friends at Hazelden and he says, ""Marv, we finally decided that we want a medical director for the company."" 5, 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20 And, I said that I would be interested. 7, 13, 14 I foolishly said that. 13, 14 I just had this struggle with myself and with Linda, you know... 17 AS: Because meanwhile, how old are your children at this point? 7, 9, 10, 16 You have two daughters? 5 MS: A daughter and a son. 5, 17 AS: A daughter and a son, okay. 5, 14, 17 MS: And so, they are in grade school. 11, 19 Second and fourth grade, maybe. 16, 19 And, so '95 I move back. 11, 14, 17, 19 It took nine months for them to decide after I interviewed, and they finally gave me the job. 11, 18 Then we moved back, I only moved back for nine months. 11, 14, 17, 19 The job was so undefined, and I just hardly did anything. 6, 14 I had no oversight of anything and no responsibility for anything. 7 AS: So, you just sat around? 18 [laughter] 9 MS: I saw patients a lot, like a psychiatrist, but nothing else of use to them. 6, 8, 9 It wasn't what I had in mind, and so, I just left and took the family back. 6, 7, 8, 11, 17, 19 They came for just four months. 11, 13, 17 Luckily, the four months was a fall from the start of school to Christmas, and we were back. 6, 11, 17, 19 They were both in grade school at the time and they both just finished the first year of a two year with the same teacher, same classmates. 6, 7, 11, 12, 16, 19 So, they missed just one part of that, and they came back to the same classmates, the same teacher and everything just fell right into place. 6, 8, 11, 12, 13, 14, 17, 19 It was really a tough time. 6, 7, 8, 9, 16, 19 AS: So, would you say that Hazelden wasn't really ready at that point? 6, 7, 8, 10, 14, 18 MS: Yeah, I never... the president at the time, Terry Spicer, I think he talked to me once. 6, 7, 9, 13, 16, 19 AS: So, they didn't really understand why they should have a medical director? 6, 7, 8, 11 MS: So, I was the first full-time doc hired and I left because they didn't have anything really going. 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 And it was really hard to do, to leave. 6, 7, 8 Because I had given up so much to get there and drag my family around the country for a second time. 7, 10, 11, 16, 19, 20 And all because, probably because... and there is still some of this. 7, 12, 13 I'm sure that, because of my own treatment at that place, there was a commitment to it, you know, that otherwise I probably wouldn't have. 7, 8, 12, 13, 17, 18 And a connection to it. 18 And some, perhaps, even a feeling that I owe them somehow. 13, 17, 18 AS: Interesting. 7 AS: And you were still feeling that twenty years later. 5, 7, 13, 16, 17, 18 Right?  Oh, yeah, absolutely. 8 AS: That is pretty powerful. 5, 7, 14 MS: I mean I didn't get sober right after treatment, but they opened my eyes... and they kind of gave me my life. 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 18, 20 right, right, the place. 8, 14 MS: So, yeah it is really powerful. 6, 7, 8 And so now I get to live in Oregon and work for Hazelden. 7, 11, 17, 20 AS: So, how did that happen? 5 MS: So, in '95, nine months in that job. 11 I am the medical director of Hazelden. 7, 11 And at the time, just a couple sites. 7, 16, 19 Minnesota, Center City and Plymouth, and St. Paul, and then we had a place in Florida at the time, as well. 7, 8, 16, 19 And I was the medical director of all of that. 7, 11 So, basically the same job that I have now... 14, 17 AS: Wait, that was the job you left that was so.... unfulfilling? 8, 19 MS: Yeah, yeah. 8 Cause they had no idea what they were doing, at the time. 5, 7, 16, 19 With a doc, you know? 17 So, we go back to Oregon, same situation. 7, 11, 17, 19 AS: You go back to doing all of the consulting, piecing... 11, 17, 19 MS: Yeah, piecing all of this together, and the private practice that kept growing. 5, 6, 11, 16, 20 It got really big which was kind of neat. 6, 7, 8 AS: Yeah, well I bet by that point you were also a special kind of psychiatrist, if people weren’t able to get... 8, 10, 18, 20 That's true.  People started to recognize their needs, yeah. 6, 7, 8, 15 AS: But did you continue that model of talking, spending more time talking with your patients, than just prescribing them medicine. 6, 7, 8, 12, 15, 16, 19 MS: Yeah, so, about half of my time I was spending doing psychotherapy and the other half doing medications and still, talking more than my peers were, with patients on medication, so it was really nice. 6, 7, 8, 12, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19 AS: Right, right. 8, 14 So, I can see why that would make you popular. 5, 18 MS: Yeah, yeah, and people come to me and say ""I go to my doc and he sees me for five minutes and just gives me a prescription, and you talk to me. 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, 14, 17 So, I'm coming back."" 7, 11, 17, 19 I heard that repeatedly. 7, 14 AS: Oh, I'm sure. 7 I'm sure. 7 MS: And I also did psychotherapy for real, you know. 7, 17, 18 AS: Right, it wasn't just trying to be nice and listen patiently for a few minutes. 14 MS: So that went well and then, I was kind of involved behind the scenes, telling folks at Hazelden, that same guy who asked me to come back for that job, he became like a COO at Hazelden. 6, 8, 11, 13, 17, 19 They didn't call him that. 14, 17 And he and I were talking, and I said, ""You know, the guy who owns Spring Brook is kind of interesting in selling it."" 6, 7, 9, 13, 14, 17, 19 It was that guy who owns this big dental company, and he just kind of lost interest. 6, 7 He was in recovery, that's why he did it, but now he just wanted to get rid of it. 7, 8, 14, 17, 20 And no one was buying it. 12, 20 So, I said, ""You guys outta consider it. 6, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15 It's a great program."" 7, 8 So, he came out and looked and then they never did anything about it. 13, 17 And then a new president came in, who was just there a year. 6, 7, 9, 13, 16, 17 It didn't work out well, and the board, you know, kind of got rid of him. 8, 17 I don't know the details, but he came out to visit. 7, 13, 17 I talked to him a lot about it and he thought it was a good idea. 5, 6, 10, 13, 19 So, he decided to buy it. 8, 20 And we're a non-profit and they were a for-profit, so it required all of this juggling about that, legally. 7 But, while he was there, he brought Linda and I out for supper with he and his wife and he asked me if I'd consider coming back as the medical director. 7, 9, 11, 12, 17, 19, 20 I said that I will if I can stay here and do it from here. 13, 14 And he said sure. 7, 13, 14 And he came out of hospital administration, so he really knew docs and medicine and he had a whole different perspective on how to run Hazelden and we had never had a person like that. 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 13, 17, 18 AS: And you said he only lasted for a year at Hazelden? 13, 14, 16 MS: Yeah, only a year. 16 But it was mostly interpersonal stuff that didn't work out. 5, 10, 17 It was problematic stuff, not because of his perspective. 7 Yeah, unfortunate stuff, but sometimes it happens that I can't mention. 5, 7, 12, 16, 19 AS: That's fine, I understand. 14 MS: But so, he asked me one day if I would be interested, and the next day, I have the job. 7, 16, 19 So, it went from nine months that first time, to overnight and I had the job. 7, 11, 16, 19 MS: And they didn't replace me when I left in 1995. 7, 8, 19 This is 2001 when they purchased Spring Brook and they get me. 20 AS: And they hadn't replaced you in that whole time from 1995... 7, 8, 16, 19 they didn't have a medical director? 7, 11 AS: Marv, that is just a crazy story. 13 So, I become the medical director, well now I am the chief medical officer. 7, 8, 11, 17, 18 They changed the title, but it is the same job, it is just bigger now. 5, 6, 17 So, I'm going back and forth. 5, 11, 17, 19 The day I start my job, they invited me out to a board meeting, and that was my start day. 6, 19 And I get to Center City and walking toward the board meeting I run into a board member, Ellen Brier, and we're just talking, and I've never met her, we're walking to the meeting, and the guy who hired me is not there. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 20 And they announced that he is no longer at the organization. 7, 20 This is my first day on the job. 16, 19 And Ellen Brier, the woman who I just met walking in, is the interim CEO. 6, 12 Ellen Brier has never been a CEO of anything, has no health care experience, comes from Godiva Chocolate. 5, 7, 13, 14, 15, 17, 20 AS: [laughter] 9 Oh my gosh.  MS: So, I start when she starts. 6 So, this goes on and she is... one of my neighbors in Oregon, I did a lot as a neighbor and then we did a lot of fishing together, and he was a CEO of an international computer firm out of LA and then they had moved to Phoenix. 7, 11, 14, 16, 19, 20 He was doing basically what I was doing, working elsewhere. 7, 8, 14, 17 I asked him if he would help me out as a business mentor and he did, and after a couple of years, probably three years, he told me that I needed to get out of there because she was going to run the company into the ground. 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 16, 18, 20 And I couldn't do it, I just held on until 2007, really trying to emphasize quality of care and outcome measures of our patients. 6, 7, 8, 14, 15, 17, 20 We gotta know that what we are doing work and we gotta prove that it works and be able to stand on that. 8, 17, 18 AS: How was that received? 7 MS: It was well received by the clinical people, you know? 7, 8, 17 But, not necessarily by her and her ideas for the organization. 5 She was more focused on the money and didn't really want to put money into doing something like that. 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 19 AS: She didn't want to put money into you all proving or trying to study whether what you were doing was working? 5, 7, 12, 14, 19 MS: And we were already doing some outcome studies, but I wanted to really enhance that... 6, 7, 8, 14, 17, 18 AS: You wanted to do that because you were trained in science. 14 MS: Yeah, yeah. 8 AS: But you're saying that it was the leadership at the time, not the culture of the 12-Step Minnesota Model? 7, 14, 16, 19 MS: Correct. 7 Yeah, and I will admit, the councilors in general...  I'm blocking out the word for it...  It was like an apprenticeship program. 7, 8 AS: Right, the peer training. 8 Alcohol and drug counselors, that's their whole history. 10, 13, 20 MS: Yeah, they had a whole certification program at the time and you just kind of come and become an apprentice for a year and then you could be a counselor and get licensed and everything. 7, 8, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 It was an oral tradition.  AS: Right, like a peer coach.  MS: But there wasn't much in the way of academics associated with it.  Nothing like the grad school now, but the training program started in the mid, I think '64. 6, 8, 11, 15, 17 It's old and established. 16 But, without the academics, there was not a learning culture at Hazelden. 5, 7 Coming out of Mayo and the University of Minnesota, I mean, there are lectures every day, all day long you could go to on all of these different specialties, diseases, all this stuff. 7, 18, 19 And that sort of culture wasn't in place, and they were kind of just resting on their morals and starting this Minnesota Model and all these remarkable things that they had done, but they weren't really pushing anything that was new. 5, 6, 7, 8, 18, 19 I was wanting to do that. 14 I thought about... 10 I left in 2007, and before I left, I was thinking to myself that we really outta consider this medicine, the only one for opioid use disorder. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 19 AS: You mean methadone?  MS: Suboxone. 12 Methadone was available, but that is so highly regulated and [not-audible] and Suboxone was just coming around and I thought maybe we should consider it. 5, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 18 I had already been involved in really driving medicine for alcohol use disorders, only Naltrexone and Antabuse and then Acamprosate were used. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 18 AS: Acamprosate?  MS: Yeah, it is another medicine for alcohol. 8, 10 It hardly ever works, maybe ten percent of people? 6, 8, 13, 16 When I say that, just today we had a lecture by video by one of the leading researchers down at Mayo. 5, 7, 12, 14, 19 A cancer researcher who now is a genetics researcher actually, really an internal medicine doc. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17, 18 For cancer research, he started using genomic and metabolomics to try and figure out responses to medications and who would respond to what. 6, 7, 10, 12, 15, 16 So, he did that for antidepressants and now he is helping out in the psychiatry and addiction department. 7, 8, 15, 17, 18 And we applied with them to [inaudible 58:33] alcohol abuse and alcoholism for a grant to study Acamprosate for alcoholics to see if we can define biologic markers that would predict response. 5, 7, 9, 10, 13, 14 AS: Wow, that is so interesting. 7, 9 MS: Because if ten percent respond, and they respond well of those that respond, it works. 7, 8 But, say you were an alcoholic.... 10, 13, 14 Here try this, you have a ten percent chance.  MS: It probably won't work, but if it works it will work great. 7, 8, 12, 13 Who wants to do that? 6, 14 It's expensive and you gotta take it three times a day, well that's not going to happen. 5, 7, 8, 16, 19, 20 AS: No. MS: But, if we could define who it works for, and you could just do a blood test and you can go, ""Hey, this will work for you."", that's a big deal. 8, 13, 14 It'll take four or five or six years. 16, 20 We just started... 6, 15 AS: Wow, that's great. 7, 8 MS: Yeah, it's really neat. 6, 7, 8 AS: Okay, so 2007 you leave.  You were already thinking about why don't we use these... because at that time, we're already seeing the consequences of overprescribing of opioid pain pills. 5, 6, 7, 9, 16, 18, 19 And you were on the West Coast.  MS: I was doing lectures about it. 7 AS: Right.  MS: And ASAM even, the American Society of Addiction Medicine, I described the stuff that was going on.  And no one was listening. 12 Cause you could see in the national data trends, we were starting to see it within Hazelden with the number of people with opioid use disorders is increasing. 5, 6, 7, 9, 14 People at Hazelden and people on the ground, they were recognizing it. 7 We're talking about it. 6 I'm trying to bring attention to it and give them lectures about it and writing, not articles for research or anything, but just writing about it and doing interviews about it. 6, 7, 11, 12 People were not paying any attention. 6, 18 So, I go out to Portland.  I needed a job, and a couple of nurse-practitioners I knew had just started to work with a woman who ran a home health service and they were going to do detox in people's homes. 6, 7, 9, 12, 15, 17, 19 Which is done in the UK and in Australia, it's really common. 6, 7, 8 And so, I thought that'd be really interesting. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 I'll work with them and we can also start an out-patient program, because those people will need treatment. 6, 7, 8, 13, 18 You can't just detox them.  So, we'll do out patient, help with the detox, figure out how to do this and see if we can prove it useful and convince insurers to use it. 5, 7, 9, 18 It'll be cheaper in the home, if we do it right. 8, 14, 17, 19 So, we got all of that going, but I decided in the out-patient program that we would do Suboxone, Vivitrol wasn't available, Naltrexone hadn't been approved for opioid use disorders yet, it had for alcoholism, so I started prescribing that, and convincing the councilors who were all from Spring Brook, basically. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, 15, 17, 18 AS: They were your councilors that you had worked with at Hazelden? 12 MS: Yeah, we stole them kind of.  And they came to work for us. 13, 17 They decided it would be more fun to try and get a new program off the ground and I convinced them that we should do this thing where we provide a real 12-Step, abstinence-based treatment programming, just like you normally would, just like background in treatment is, with the use of suboxone, this new medication for opioid use disorders because it looks really promising. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 I think we should try this.  And initially, they were just aghast that anyone would want to give that medication to patients, but after a few patients, and the whole excitement of getting it going, they just got totally supported. 9, 11, 14, 15, 16, 20 AS: Because they were seeing really good results? 5, 6, 7, 8, 19 Yeah, people kind of settled down...  I mean it wasn't all good. 6, 19 There were problems and people didn't keep coming and abused their Suboxone or whatever. 7, 9, 12, 17 There was a whole gamut of things happening, but most people did well. 5, 7, 8, 19 And so, we established that program and I did it for two years. 8, 16 And unfortunately, the woman who had that in-home health company that owned this whole thing, basically was going bankrupt. 14, 17, 19 And not telling us and trying to just... she was just a mess kind of. 13 All of the sudden, it was in dire straits. 7, 17 At the same time, Mark Mishuck had been hired at Hazelden. 7, 16, 19 MS: He is our CEO.  AS: Oh, okay. 14 MS: Yeah, sorry.  [laughter] 9 It's okay! 14 You shouldn't know. 17 AS: Sorry, I didn't study up on that! 5 [laughter] 9 You never know what I remembered and might have picked up. 5, 7, 13, 15, 17 MS: So, I get a call from his assistant, Karen Colander. 7, 14, 17, 20 Karen is an old friend, I've known her for fifteen years or something. 7, 12, 13, 16, 17 And she says, ""Marv, Mark is coming out to the northwest and he wants to meet with you. 6, 7, 14, 17 So, he and his wife want to take you and Linda out for supper."" 12, 14, 20 AS: Here it comes. 17 MS: And I'm thinking, why does he want to talk to me? 6, 14 And she doesn't know. 17 She says, ""I don't know."" 14, 17 And I'm thinking well maybe he just wants to know the history or something that I know. 6, 8, 13, 14, 16, 17 Honestly, that's what went through my head. 6, 12 And cause when I left, I forgot to tell you this, when I left, the woman who was CEO, Ellen, was absolutely furious with me for leaving. 8, 13, 19 And, I also told the board why I was leaving, I wrote them a letter that, she's doing this, and my thoughts are quality. 10, 13, 16 If we're going to make money, we have to, but we gotta have a quality program. 7, 8, 12, 18 AS: 