y out here, and the house is worth even less than before we did that. 6, 7, 9, 11, 18, 19, 20 So, we say the heck with this, this is okay, it's not that bad living apart, we'll just do it a little longer and see what happens. 5, 6, 7, 8, 14, 20 So, she stays in Oregon and I was here in Minnesota first living in Center City and then in White Bear, just renting. 6, 7, 14, 16, 19 First, I was living in a friend's house, they just let me stay there because they moved to the Southwest. 6, 9, 11, 13, 14 Whenever they visited, I would just get out for a week or whatever. 7, 13, 16, 20 And then, it went on for almost four years living like that. 6, 15, 16 AS: That's hard. 6 MS: And finally, I just told Mark, my boss and CEO, this is just too much. 13, 16 I have to do something different. 7, 18 And about at the same time we were starting to negotiate with Betty Ford, so we would have a bigger presence on the West Coast, and he agreed that I should just be able to work out there and work out of the office there and come here regularly. 5, 6, 7, 16, 17, 18, 19 And that's what I've done since.  Before I left in 2000... 8, 19 yeah, before I left, we hired our first full-time psychiatrist. 7, 8, 16, 19 For here in Minnesota.  MS: Yeah, Steve.  Here in Center City.  Springbrook had full time people. 7, 16, 19 And I had worked there full time for a period of time before I was hired by Hazelden that first time, or that second time. 7, 12, 16, 19 [laughter] 9 AS: That's okay. 14 We'll try to make a timeline or something. 7, 16, 18, 19 I'll get your CV. 20 MS: [laughter] 9 So, basically, when I was talking with Mark about coming back, I said that I have been doing this in-home detox stuff which is exciting, but more exciting is that I have been dealing with opioids and I think we ought to consider this and go down this path with Suboxone. 5, 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 13, 14, 17, 19 And he says, ""That makes sense to me."" 9, 14, 17, 18 And he comes out of hospital administration. 8, 17 Of course, it makes sense, a doctor tells me, ""Here is the research and here is my experience."" 7, 9, 12, 13, 15, 18, 20 AS: And here's what we need to do!  MS: And it was still not getting attention nationally. 6, 7, 15, 20 I mean it was, but it wasn't.  I come back and finally, it's kind of exploding, and I am still talking about it. 6, 7, 11, 17, 19 And we haven't done anything yet, I gotta do all kinds of other stuff as well, getting back involved there and getting some things taken care of. 5, 7, 8, 11, 12, 14, 15, 17, 19, 20 And then, I decided let's do it. 8 And I had to convince the board because it is really controversial for our group. 6, 7, 8, 18 AS: I'm sure. 7 MS: I would bet about half of the board or more were older alcoholics in recovery and had biases about medicines, like buprenorphine. 7, 8, 10, 13, 15, 16 AS: Right, any medicine. 8 MS: Yeah, oh yeah. 8 But we already had full mental health services with full-time psychiatrists now. 6, 7, 8, 16, 17, 18, 19 AS: So, people understood that there was a need for psychiatric-based medications. 16 MS: Yeah, and they'd already gotten the medicines for alcoholism in place before I had left. 6, 7, 8, 10, 18, 19 AS: At Hazelden?  AS: Oh, I didn't know that you guys were doing that. 6, 8, 15, 17 MS: Yeah, so the foundation... 11 Yeah, we did that around 2003 maybe. 16 So, Naltrexone came along, we decided to do that, with rare use of... 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 15, 17 Oh god, what's the stuff that makes you puke if you drink. 9, 18, 19 AS: Anifuse. 9 MS: Anifuse, yeah. 8, 9 We hardly ever use it because it is so dangerous in a way, and then Acamprosate came later, so we added that. 5, 6, 9, 13, 16, 17 We had already established that. 6, 7, 18 I came back and started to talk about this. 6, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19 The board chair at the time was a catholic priest from inner-city Minneapolis. 7, 16, 19 He had been a really high-level administrative priest and then kind of got that out of the way in his career and then kind of went to real street level type work. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 20 A lot with the homeless and with other organizations like that. 17, 19 Father Michael Connell.  And he was wonderful.  Because of his experience with all of that, he had seen the opioid crisis. 5, 13, 15 He was also in recovery, but he had seen it for what it was in inner city Minneapolis. 5, 7, 8, 13 He thought that we should do this too and was really supportive. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 So, I had the support of the CEO and the support of the board chair, spent a bunch of time educating the board, and then they voted unanimously to support doing this and going down this path. 7, 9, 16, 19 MS: It was probably 2011 when they actually supported doing it. 9, 12, 13, 18 So, I started my plan in January of 2012 and pulled that team together and we took people from all parts of clinical from all sites on that team to kind of get this figured out for the organization. 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 Initially, one of the councilors who I asked to be on this team, he said to me when I asked him, ""Is this a good career move, Marv?"" 5, 6, 7, 13, 14, 19, 20 Because no one knew. 6, 12 Yeah, should I even be on this team if I am going to be suggesting that we use this medicine in this organization, what's going to happen to me? 5, 8, 9 And others, I got a four-page, single-spaced email from one of our councilors in St. Paul. 7, 15 Because it had leaked out, this was about a month and a half project with the team. 5, 16 We we're communicating about it, we were just planning to figure it out. 7 We were actually just reading the literature. 7, 18 AS: Right.  MS: Right, and I had already done it in that outpatient program. 6, 7, 8, 18 Basically, the whole model was already established in the outpatient program and we're just going to put it into Hazelden, kinda. 6, 7, 8, 14, 17, 18, 19 And yet, I had to convince people of it's worth, so I thought I would just use the literature. 7, 9, 10, 15 It made a huge difference, because I had everybody read a couple of papers about the early research on Suboxone and how it was working for people and they came back and had to present their two papers and everybody did their two papers, or three or whatever. 6, 7, 11, 12, 13, 17, 19 And they were all like, wow, this is kind of hard to refute when you read this stuff and you hear all of this. 6, 7, 9, 14 So, it made it huge difference. 7, 13 AS: What was the four-page email? 15 MS: Oh, sorry.  It was why we should not do this and about, maybe two and a half years ago now the woman who wrote it came up to me at one of our leadership meetings, basically the one we are having tomorrow and gave me a big hug and actually, with a tear in her eye, said ""Thank god that you had us do this. 6, 9, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18 It works so well."" 8 [laughter] 9 Yeah, so it was wonderful because I didn't pick people that I thought would support it, I picked people I thought could get it done and decided that the research itself and my experience should help, you know win the day of whether we should do it or not. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 15, 17, 18, 19, 20 We already had the board approval, so we were going to do it. 6, 7, 18 AS: Right, and... it's happening. 5, 7 MS: Are you going to get on board or not? 20 And I had one of our main kind of national speakers, Fred Ulmquist, ran the renewal center at the lodge at the time and Fred is like an AA, Twelve-Step professor. 6, 7, 16, 19 AS: [laughter] 9 MS: Also, his parents were professors and he wore bowties and he teaches like a professor, you know, he just does. 7, 12, 17 And he's wonderful and really bright. 6, 7, 8, 14 I've known him a long time, we're old friends and we've worked together on the alcohol medication thing. 7, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 19, 20 I asked him if he would help because I wanted to have his AA-cred for the staff, of course we're doing the right thing. 8, 14, 18, 19 So, Fred comes along, and he get on the team too, for the Suboxone, and Fred's wife, I'd known this but forgotten, Fred's wife Paige was in recovery from heroin use. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 15, 17, 20 And Fred was also in recovery, not from heroin. 7, 8, 10 So, he knew that whole side of heroin and he said ""Absolutely, I want to be involved in this. 6, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14 I want to help."" 14, 18 And Fred, there's a book ""The Twelve Steps and Twelve Traditions"" and the third tradition, there is a description, a full paragraph, of all of the people who really early kind of established when they went to AA who should not come to these meetings. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17, 20 And there is a whole list, includes ""fallen women"", whatever that is. 11, 12 AS: Yeah, that's classic. 6, 12 MS: And then on the next page or two, it says we realize that to limit anyone from coming, could possibly sentence them to death and they decided against any limitations. 7, 8, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 And Fred had brought that to our team, which we used throughout anything we did. 5, 7, 9, 20 AS: When people would start to push back? 6, 11, 17, 19 MS: Even before, we just had Fred get up and describe that and say, ""Hey, we are going to do this, and we need to. 7, 14, 20 This is a precedent set by the founders of AA."" 7, 11 [laughter] 9 And there's no limitations to medication that are described in AA. 16 AS: Why do you think that that myth persists?  Because I hear so many stories of people who've struggled with whether they tell their sponsor that they are on Suboxone or on Methadone, because there is still this idea that... 5, 7, 12, 13, 14, 18 Why does this myth persist if it is in the traditions?  MS: There's even a pamphlet from AA about medical care and the use of medication and it says that it is between you and your doctor. 7, 9, 11, 14, 16, 17, 20 MS: I think it's because historically, the medical profession has addicted a lot of people to a lot of different medications and sold a lot of medications as if they were not addicting. 7, 11, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18 AS: So, there is basically a distrust of the medical profession, which I understand in the history of medicine very well. 6, 8, 11, 13, 14, 17 MS: Okay, that's it.  That's the main reason, that's why it has nothing to do with the treatment of addiction and alcoholism. 7, 8, 10, 13, 15, 17, 18 AS: Not for a long time. 7, 16, 19 MS: Yeah, and finally they start to. 6 But during my residency training, one of the other faculty members in psychiatry was studying Xanax for alcoholism and saying it was a safe mediation. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 14 MS: Yeah, and people back then thought so. 10, 11, 17, 19 Not that long before that, TIME Magazine's cover was ""Cocaine is not addictive"". 7, 15 And I knew it was, I used cocaine. 6, 9, 10, 12 AS: Right, it's like smoking cigarettes isn't bad for you. 7, 10 MS: My god! 9 It was really addictive. 6, 7, 8, 15 And, you know, all of us within recovery knew this stuff was so terrible. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17 So, I think that that was what it was.  A distrust. 6 And there was a real distrust in Methadone, even though it was remarkably useful. 6, 7, 9, 12 Well, because it got associated with crime and inner-cities and people of color.  But also, most of that was because of the for-profit methadone maintenance programs that were established and still are all over the place. 7, 8 Because once you get someone on methadone, they keep coming back and you get money from them. 7, 10, 11, 12, 17, 19, 20 And they are for profit?  There are some that are not-for-profit, most of them are for-profit.  And they don't provide all of the services that are supposed to be done in methadone. 14 Yeah, so all of these wrap around services, well not in those programs. 8 They hand out methadone all day long and that's it. 7, 13, 19 AS: Well, that's another extreme that is just as, I think, just as problematic as just saying ""Twelve Steps are going to heal you."" 7, 14 ... from opioids. 5 Absolutely.  And every time they have looked at people that are on long-term methadone and they stop, they relapse. 7, 10, 12, 13, 16, 19 Well, if you've got nothing else but methadone, of course you are going to relapse! 7, 8, 10, 12 AS: Right, right. 8, 14 If your life still is horrible... things are the same. 5, 7, 8, 19 So, I've always... 10 that was the beauty of suboxone.  Is that, it's not under the same regulatory requirements as methadone, so you can do it right from your office, which was fantastic. 7, 8, 14, 18 AS: Right.  MS: You don't have to have all of the licensure for methadone either, which is really onerous. 6, 7, 8, 12 And our board, there was still bias about methadone and I had had experience in a couple of different methadone maintenance programs. 7, 8, 10, 12, 15, 18 One, my training at the VA and one, I consulted at and did psychiatric work for in downtown Portland. 8 So, I knew that there was a real utility to methadone, and I had seen the research. 5, 6, 7, 10, 12, 13 It was kind of like... but I also knew a lot of people who had a history of heroin, who were sober in NA and either had used methadone for a period of time and stopped or had never done it and now were sober. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 So, I had that experience too, that it is not absolutely necessary. 15 But in our setting, there was no way that we would have done methadone.  AS: Right, I totally understand that.  MS: Partially, because of the onerous nature of the regulatory system. 7, 12 And we do this in people's offices, and we knew that they could get the care later, easily. 5, 6, 7, 12, 14, 16, 18, 20 So, vivitrol had been approved so we said we were going to do both medications. 13, 14, 16 I didn't have experience with vivitrol from that practice, because it wasn't approved when I was there, so this is new, but it makes so much sense to use both. 6, 9, 15, 18 So, we decide that's what we're going to do right from the beginning. 8, 14 AS: You mean to offer both?  AS: Yeah, so people could have a choice.  It is always nice to have a choice among medications, for any illn