0, 17 MS: Right, three quarters of the room. 9 And you could hear a pin drop. 14 It made our whole argument, in one question. 13, 15 Then Fred talks, and we open it up for discussion and I'm thinking, okay, here it comes. 6, 7, 14, 17, 20 We get softball question after softball question and support for this program and that we need to change that people are dying. 5, 8, 9, 15, 20 You know, ""This makes so much sense."" 9, 17, 18 Somehow, we're going to do it, type questions. 15 And then, we're ten or fifteen minutes into the questions and one of our most conservative councilors raised their hand and I am thinking, now it's going to start, this is the flapjack. 5, 6, 13, 14, 15, 17 And she stands up and she says, ""My daughter,"" she was twenty-eight or something, ""went to residential treatment three times for heroin, relapsed after each treatment right away, could not get sober until she started taking suboxone. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 And now she has been sober three years, she's part of my family again, she now takes of her children and I don't have to anymore, she has a job, and she is doing wonderfully."" 7, 8, 9, 16, 17, 19, 20 And no one knew. 6, 12 She hadn't told anyone. 13, 16 And she just got up and gave this testimonial and it was like, we couldn't have asked for anything better to say and it was just from the most unlikely person in the room, just this big book thumping woman who, who no one ever thought would ever support this. 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19 And it was the most incredible description of the utility of this medication that you could ever hear. 7, 13, 14, 16 And her daughter went to AA, right? 5, 8, 14 And took the medicine. 8 It turned the entire conversation... there wasn't any griping, let alone absolutely anarchy. 7, 12, 18 There were certainly pockets of people who didn't agree, but they didn't talk in that meeting and they kind of got silent as we went down this path and just silently just tried to disrupt things. 5, 6, 7, 14, 19 It was amazing.  It was the absolute opposite of what we were expecting. 7 AS: That's incredible. 7 MS: Yeah, and it told me, once again, the passion of our counseling staff, our clinical staff-- our docs and nurses as well and councilors --- is so tremendous. 7, 8, 13, 16, 17 They just want to do what is right for our patients. 8, 14, 15 And we finally said, here's what we should do for this particular group of patients, and... [aside conversation about incoming phone call]. 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17, 18 AS: So, what would you say... 14 So, I know that you did, just in the interest of time, you did a webinar, this is how I started to reach out to you, because you did a webinar about what has happened in the few years since you started. 5, 6, 7, 15, 16, 17, 19 Okay, so I could watch that and then get a lot of your answers. 15, 20 MS: Okay, yeah, that would tell you how we did and what our early results were. 6, 7, 8, 13 AS: Okay, that is good to know. 6, 17, 19 What would you say...? 14 I have a couple things. 5, 7, 19 What would you say to people who still say, ""Hazelden is a dinosaur.""? 7, 14 MS: [laughter] 9 I laugh, nowadays because man... 17, 18, 19 AS: You must have heard that. 7, 14 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 AS: And this is in the context of the opioid epidemic. 5 MS: We were talking about it this morning actually, because a couple of our folks who are out on the East Coast, I don't know if they are in Rhode Island or in Connecticut, and they are talking with the executive director of the AAA, the American Association of Addiction Psychiatrists. 6, 7, 9, 14, 17, 18 And this person in this group that we are talking to, they think that we are a dinosaur, that we're just living in the past. 6, 8, 10, 17, 18 They have no idea what we were doing. 5 They had no idea about Core Twelve, they know nothing about our treatment, they just made all of these assumptions based on twenty years ago and what we were like. 5, 7, 9, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18 As if somehow, we had never changed. 5, 6, 13, 17 You know? 17 And they were able to tell them all of this stuff, and when they left, they said, ""Oh my God. 8, 13, 14, 18, 19 We had no idea."" 5 Thanks for coming. 7 AS: Yeah, thanks for showing up. 9 MS: [laughter] 9 Yeah, so now I tell them about Core Twelve, about the research project that we have completed that we are trying to get published. 7, 12, 13, 17 We still haven't heard from the publisher. 7, 14 We submitted the paper and asked for the edits, we submitted the edits.  AS: To which publisher?  To a scientific journal?  MS: Yeah, Journal of Substance Abuse Treatment. 7, 9 The right one, right? 8, 12, 14 [laughter] 9 AS: Yeah, you picked the right one there. 5, 8, 12, 14 MS: Yeah, so we're hopeful. 13 It was a naturalistic study, so it didn't have double-blind controls with the medications, which it a bit unfortunate for a study because you don't have the controls that you might want. 5, 10, 14, 16, 20 But we were told when talking to several researchers that both medicines have been adequately approved to be effective, we just need to see what they are like in practice. 5, 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 16 AS: So, what does that mean, naturalistic?  MS: That the patients get to choose which medicine, we don't force that on them. 8, 15, 20 AS: You don't demand that?  Because that's what I... reading that short piece from 2013, that patients can continue to choose, if they want just abstinence or if they want one of these drugs. 7, 10, 14, 15, 19 MS: And that's still the case. 7 And we recommend that they take one of the two medications. 7, 16, 20 AS: But how much... okay, okay. 14 MS: Every single person with an opioid use disorder, we recommend the medication. 5, 7, 9, 10, 16, 17 They can refuse it. 7, 9 That's the deal.  MS: You can't force it on them, we can, and we do continue to try and convince them, because this conversation is right when they get into treatment during detox it starts. 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 18, 19, 20 And we're continuing to try and tell them to try the medicines. 8, 13 We will their family, not necessarily successfully because a lot of the times, family are not involved at all and they don't want anything to do with the person anymore, or, they just... 7, 10, 14, 16, 17, 19 ""We didn't bring them there for that.""  Especially that suboxone stuff, because there are real biases about it. 7, 12 And we have to do a lot of education about it there, and even then, they might say that we're not going to support that. 9, 14 ""We just want them sober."" 14 AS: Have you noticed a difference between what happens at Plymouth versus Center City, in terms of opioid addiction? 5, 7, 8, 15 MS: To a degree. 7, 19 One of the main things, the one big difference we noticed right of the bat, is that some of the younger people especially misused suboxone on the street. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 16, 19, 20 And some of them, to me that's not a big deal, if it's just that they are using suboxone... 10 AS: But they are trying to use it between? 9 MS: Yeah, detoxing themselves...  But if they are injecting it or something, that would suggest that we're not going to give it to them. 11 Because people certainly do that. 14 AS: How do you inject suboxone?  It's a liquid?  It is a liquid, well you can turn it into a liquid really easily. 6, 7, 8 AS: Because it's the little sublingual... 20 MS: Yeah, it's either a tablet or a film. 18 You just put some warm water on it, and it goes right into a solution. 8, 14, 19 But also, you're not supposed to be able to inject it because it's got Naloxone in it, it's supposed to block your receptors and put you into withdrawal. 7, 14, 18, 19 Suboxone is really tightly bound to those receptors and might not let that happen. 5, 6, 7, 8 It's really a weird thing. 6, 7, 8, 19 Yeah, so some people actually do inject it and get high off of it. 11, 18, 20 Most people don't try for that reason. 7, 10, 17 AS: What are you guys doing with Naloxone and Narcan? 6, 8, 12, 15 MS: We give that to every patient that has an opioid use disorder. 5, 9, 11 AS: When they leave?  AS: When did you start doing that? 6 MS: At the latter part of installing this whole system. 8 So, it's been going on for quite a while now. 17 What else? 8 Shoot.  AS: Sorry, I interrupted you.  MS: I can't remember what I was going to say, that's okay. 7, 13, 14, 15 AS: That's bad oral history. 13 It's a violation.  MS: [laughter] 9 AS: I'm in trouble now. 17 [Aside, moving cat away from interview] 9, 20 MS: I can't remember what I was going to say, but when we went public about this, we got just lambasted by other treatment programs and, especially, Twelve 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 15, 18 Step program type treatment. 7, 8, 13, 18 AS: By saying that you were going to use medication? 9, 14, 16 They said we were... 13, 14 We heard form a real kind of prominent AA person in the Twin Cities that were ruining AA. 7, 10, 14, 17 We were told we were turning our back on our entire heritage and ruining the treatment field, that we were, and me in particular, were ruining Hazelden. 7, 8, 11, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 AS: Is this a public document? 11 MS: There was some in the media, but I don't know. 17 You would have to ask Jeramiah.  He might be able to dig some of that stuff up. 18 AS: Who is Jeramiah?  MS: Jeramiah Gardner is our PR person. 10, 17 AS: Oh, okay. 14 Well because that is kind of the opposite of what I was... 7 That's the opposite of some of the things that I have heard. 5, 7, 14, 19 MS: And now it's changed. 5, 6, 17 Now it's really switched. 6, 7, 8 AS: No, but I mean that you weren't doing enough. 16, 20 MS: Oh, sure. 7 AS: And when you do it, you're criticized by people for not doing enough. 16, 20 MS: It was both, we were getting both. 15, 20 AS: But, let's talk about that for a second... 6, 16 Oh, go ahead. 12 MS: In the same month, I was told that we were ruining addiction treatment of this type, you know Twelve Step, abstinence-based treatment, and it's not going to work what we are doing, by one person from a different treatment program. 7, 8, 10, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18 And a couple weeks later, told by a doc in St. Paul that we weren't giving enough people Buprenorphine and we shouldn't even be giving Vivitrol to anybody. 5, 7, 13, 16, 20 And neither were true at the time, he just was making assumptions and of course, the other one wasn't true either. 7, 12, 16, 19 It was ridiculous.  And that was just constant for a while, that sort of stuff. 8 In spite of the fact that we were doing...  We were the first of the major addiction treatment programs to do this. 7, 8, 13, 15, 16, 18 We weren't this first program to do it, but we were the first to write about it and the first to get it out there in the media, to really bring attention to that issue. 6, 7, 8, 16, 20 I have trained all kinds of people who were from other treatment programs, some of whom couldn't even tell their treatment program when they were coming to visit us and learn about this. 5, 7, 8, 12, 13, 18 Yeah, they didn't dare. 7 Some who were trying to convince their board that we should do this, but you know, they couldn't and still wanted to learn how we were doing it and stuff like that. 5, 7, 14, 17 It was really weird. 6, 7, 8 I didn't really care, because we were doing what we needed to do, and it was so exciting. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 20 AS: For your patients. 15 MS: Yeah, and patients were getting better, and it was really useful and wonderful. 6, 7, 8, 9, 15, 17, 20 AS: Does your program support people staying on Suboxone for some amount of time or are they encouraged to get off before they leave? 5, 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 15, 16, 19, 20 MS: Well, initially we said we only wanted to use it for some period of time, like a year and a half, two years or something. 7, 9, 13, 14, 16, 19 Until you get into good solid recovery, and then if you want to get of the medicine, just fine. 6, 7, 8, 14, 19, 20 I still think that is a useful tool for most people probably. 7, 9, 12, 13 Not all by any means.  And yet, the Federal Government doesn't agree, and a lot of researchers say, ""I can't take people off of their medication."" 7, 12, 14, 15, 16, 20 But the truth is, medication adherence study shows us that two weeks of an antibiotic, less than half of people do that without stopping it early. 5, 6, 7, 9, 16 It's terrible.  And all of the suboxone studies, those early studies we used in that literature review, show that less than fifty percent of people were staying on it. 5, 6, 7, 9, 12, 14 And they were really quitting early. 6, 7, 8, 19 So, our goal became... 13, 17 We want to keep people on it, keep them engaged in treatment, and that's where we shifted our model because we wanted people to stay engaged with us long term who had opioid use disorder. 5, 7, 9, 13, 14, 15, 17, 18 Not in residential, we wanted residential to get into out-patient in St. Paul and stick around in this program, getting the medicine there, living in a sober house, you know, stick with this long term. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 15, 17, 18, 20 And, we will help you figure out if you should stop the medicine or not, and we will support you all along the way. 7, 8, 9, 18 So, Core Twelve became this really kind of long term out-patient program. 6, 7, 8, 13, 17 Now there are over two hundred people in St. Paul in this program. 8 AS: Oh, wow. 14 MS: Yeah, it's great. 7, 8 And that's where we ultimately resulted in... in our whole model. 7, 19 We saw the utility of a residential stay for stabilization, followed by long term out patient, during which the people could transition from professional care to self-care over months and years, if it was necessary. 5, 6, 7, 9, 11, 14, 16, 20 And it gave us the opportunity to maintain involvement and support ongoing use of medications, and ultimately, if they wanted to get off, we could be there to help them with that and insure continued support. 7, 9, 14, 16, 18, 19, 20 Because so many people stopped anyway, to me, that was just an essential feature of this. 7, 15, 18 And I knew that the craving of opioids goes on so long, I didn't want to say, ""We're just going to do four weeks of treatment,"" or whatever, now our average is about three, and then say... 5, 6, 7, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18 AS: Oh, really? 6, 7, 8 MS: Yeah, in residential. 7, 9 Our average in out-patient after that is now like several months. 11, 13, 15, 17 And for our Core Twelve folks, our initial Core Twelve group was going two years later with all of the same people still there. 5, 7, 16, 17, 18 I mean, they didn't want to stop. 14 And they were all going to Twelve  Step meetings and doing all of this other stuff, but they still really appreciated what they were getting there. 6, 7, 8, 12, 15, 20 And so, my bias was...  There's literature on physicians with addiction and a lot of them are opioid addicts, and a lot of those are fentanyl addicts, so even more powerful drugs that what they have on the street. 5, 7, 8, 10, 13, 15, 20 They are taking pure fentanyl. 7 And a high death rate for those folks as well. 8, 11, 17 But, in most states, they were not allowed to use Suboxone and go back to practice medicine. 6, 8, 9, 11, 12, 17, 19 But also, they had the highest recovery rates recorded in any literature because of all of the long-term monitoring. 7, 8, 11 AS: Oh right, so you could use that monitoring model... 8, 9, 14 MS: It was two-fold. 16 I must be getting tired, I can't remember anything. 7, 13, 15, 20 AS: That's okay, I understand. 14 You have been talking for two hours. 6 You should be running out of words. 8, 9 MS: [laughter] 9 So, contingency management is an evidence-based practice for addiction. 6, 8, 15 The biggest contingency, the easiest to understand what this means, is if a physician or a nurse or anyone that requires a license, like a driver, a semi-driver or a pilot, if you're going to go back to your work, you can do that as long as you do this, this, this, and this, too, and we'll let you maintain your license. 7, 9, 11, 14, 17, 18, 19 If you don't do any of these things, we are taking your license away. 5, 18, 19, 20 If you relapse, we are taking your license away. 7, 18, 20 So, that's a contingency management, that's an evidence-based practice. 6, 15 Sometimes, a different type of contingency, and when we used this at St. Paul, if everybody shows up for group today, we'll have a pizza party next time we meet, and we'll supply the pizza. 5, 7, 8, 9, 12, 16, 18, 19 And the thing is, when we did that, they were all supporting each other. 9, 19 ""You gotta go to group we want that pizza party."" 8, 14, 18, 19 Right?  They are calling each other and texting, ""Get to group!"". 14, 17, 18 So, it supports abstinence, it supports continued involvement. 9, 19 So, we were using that. 10 So, for the docs, its contingency management, they could lose their license to practice medicine, as well as that long-term monitoring that I think results in the really high outcome rates. 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 15, 17, 18 And even for those with opioid use disorders, although a lot of the data is a little skewed because some people drop out, ones with opioid use disorders and they weren't used in the final analysis, but still, they've got seventy-five or eighty percent abstinent in five years. 5, 6, 7, 9, 12, 16, 20 AS: Really?  Wow.  That's great. 7, 8 MS: It's incredible. 7 Yeah, but most of them can't use suboxone and go back to work. 9, 11, 12, 17, 19 There are a couple of states that allow it, but most states won't. 7, 17 AS: You mean for doctors? 20 MS: Yeah, these doctors cannot go back to work on Suboxone. 11, 12, 17, 19, 20 So, I knew of that literature and I knew all kinds of people in NA, who, like I said earlier, have either never used methadone, or used methadone and stopped and now are sober. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 13, 14, 15, 17 So, I know that people with opioid use disorder can stay sober without medication. 5, 9, 14, 16, 17 And I don't know who is who, so that's one of the reasons that we recommend everyone take one of the two medications, but it also is one of the reasons, initially, that I thought we should support people who want to stop medication, at some point. 7, 9, 10, 14, 16, 17, 20 That only after their really good recovery, because the risk of relapse is associated with the risk of overdose and death. 6, 7, 8, 19 So, it can't, we can't, be undisciplined about this.  We've got to really make sure that we are only supporting that, if they are in solid recovery, and even then, there is still a risk. 6, 7, 8, 9, 18 We've had all kinds of people stop the medications and we've had some stay on the medications. 12, 14, 16 AS: Right, it is just so personal. 10, 17 MS: Right.  We don't know who is who. 17 AS: And you haven't been able to test that. 13, 18 MS: No, and I would like to. 9, 14 That would be a great research project, but it would be really hard to do and take a really long time. 6, 7, 8, 12, 16, 19, 20 It would still be worth it. 7 AS: Okay, just one more question. 15 Do you need to go?  AS: So, if you could change something for the better right now, if you could change something right now regarding addiction treatment, what would it be? 5, 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, 17, 18 MS: If I could just suddenly change something? 5, 17 MS: I guess the main thing would be to allow access to anybody to have addiction treatment and as long as they needed addiction treatment. 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 18, 19 AS: To have it for as long as they need it? 7 MS: Yeah, and in a system like our own, where they start with residential if they need it, they go to day treatment, they go to out-patient, intensive out-patient and have long term follow up. 6, 7, 9, 13, 18, 19 AS: And that's if they have the insurance or the funds.  MS: Well, if I get to change anything the funding is somehow provided so anyone can access treatment and they can have the treatment they need. 5, 7, 13, 17, 18, 20 AS: Okay, that's what I knew you were getting at. 6, 12, 15, 20 MS: Which is hard to g