ion and in overwhelming numbers that we have never seen before, and we have an obligation to do everything we can to help and that's what convinced me more than anything, and what convinced our staff more than anything. 5, 8, 13, 14, 15, 18 And the medicines work, and they work well, and that helped a lot in convincing. 8, 18 But the Betty  Ford folks, their board actually agreed and still went through with the merger. 7, 17, 18 It took over a year before their staff would even consider it. 9, 16 And it required a lot of them coming to visit to see what it was like in action and to meet our patients. 5, 7, 15 AS: So, they're very new to the Core Twelve Program? 6, 7 Within a couple years. 7, 16 It might be three now or so for them, but it took a while. 17 And they were really biased initially, but now they just love it too. 6, 7, 8, 17 AS: So, what was the impact, and you might not know this, but what was the impact on staff at Hazelden when these deaths started happening and how were you finding out about them? 5, 6, 7, 9, 15, 17 Were you finding out through the grapevine or how was it? 9 MS: Well, it depended on how long they had been out of treatment and probably circumstances with their families. 7, 12, 13, 15, 18 If they were still involved with us, we were absolutely finding out. 7, 9 If they weren't involved and patients who were still in our system were involved with them, we would find out through the patient once and a while. 7, 9, 15 The family would tell us regularly. 7, 13, 19 We have a quality review committee, which is like a peer review committee in a hospital that has to review every sentinel event. 7, 8 It would be like a death, a very bad outcome, an injury, a medication error, stuff like that. 16, 17 And so, I oversee that, and I am the liaison to our quality committee to the board, and so I was seeing everyone we were aware of, we reviewed. 5, 6, 7, 17 Which is really hard. 6, 7, 8 AS: Was there a time when there were a lot of them? 7, 16, 19 MS: It didn't suddenly peak, it just kind of slowly got to become more and then it kind of leveled off, but it's been... before that, before this opioid crisis, we hardly had any deaths. 5, 6, 9, 17, 18 I mean there would be a suicide now and then, I mean we were not reviewing regularly deaths all the time, no, and now we are, which is horrible. 7, 16, 17, 19 But I can't prove this.  But the numbers are so much more now, in terms of the numbers of people with opioid use disorder than it was at the start of all of this. 5, 6, 9, 14, 17 And although we have more death, I think we would have way, way more without the use of the medication. 9, 16 I can't prove it, I suppose I could try.  AS: Well, hasn't evidence-based medicine already proved it? 6, 7, 8, 18 I mean, do you have to prove that it is you?  MS: It has, there is proof.  There is proof in the literature. 7 However, in our research study of Core Twelve, there were two-hundred and fifty-nine participants and they basically, almost a third in each group, a third on Naltrexone, mostly vivitrol, a third on Suboxone, and a third who refused medications. 5, 7, 8, 9, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 20 There were three deaths over the 2013 to 2017, in that two-hundred and fifty-nine people.  One used buprenorphine and two used naltrexone, nobody with no meds. 7, 9, 12 It goes against anything that we would have thought would have thought would have happened. 5, 10 AS: Nobody with no meds?  MS: Nobody.  We don't have all of the deaths because somebody could have died and not told us. 13, 16, 17 I am intending to do... we lost a couple of people in our research department, so I haven't been able to carry this out, but I want to study like a thousand of our patients with opioid use disorder and look at all of their deaths through the social security death index, because they have gotten really much better by defining death by overdose. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 12, 14, 15, 17, 18 And then I could look back and see who was on no meds, who was on Suboxone, who was on vivitrol. 5, 11, 12, 17, 19 I won't have the detail of how long they took it after treatment or anything, so I am not sure how much it will be helpful, but I will at least... 7, 13, 18 No one has published anything like that, looking at death following addiction treatment, and that is so important. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 15, 18 Because every single treatment program in the country is experiencing this. 7, 8, 10, 13, 18 When we first started talking about this, I was talking about death and overdose at every single discussion that I had about it, because it is so necessary to the discussion if you are going to change your whole model, you have to have a good reason. 5, 6, 7, 10, 15, 16, 17, 19 There is no better reason. 7, 10, 17 And nobody would engage in a conversation about that. 15 No other treatment program, no other providers. 7, 8, 13, 18 They wouldn't even bring it up with me.  And I would ask sometimes. 7, 12, 16, 19 AS: And when you say treatment programs, you mean those usually based on Twelve Step programs? 7, 8, 13, 14, 18 You weren't talking to addiction medicine doctors who were already using it. 6, 7, 8, 10, 15, 18, 20 AS: They didn't even want to talk about the death rates. 6, 14 AS: Why do you think that is?  MS: At ASAM there was more and more discussion about that over the years, but I think people were so used to a field that barely ever had deaths that they just didn’t know what to do about it. 7, 9, 12, 13, 16, 17, 20 And the other thing is that most treatment centers do no outcome studies. 7, 13, 17, 18, 19 They do no follow up of their patients. 15 AS: Well, that's what really shocks me in my whole process of what I have been studying for this. 5, 6, 7, 8 MS: Yeah, it's horrible.  AS: I don't even understand how that is possible.  MS: It's amazing.  It's ridiculous.  And so, if you assume that everyone is doing great and put on your website that ninety-percent are abstinent at one year, you can't look and see who died. 5, 7, 8, 16, 17, 19 Man. AS: Right.  Well and how can you even prove that people were abstinent.  Yeah, you can just call them and ask them... 14, 17 [laughter] or don't even. 9 Or just take that, say it's ninety-percent. 14, 20 AS: Just say it, right. 8, 14 MS: Because you can't know and there's no group that is ninety-percent, ever. 13, 17, 18 [laughter] 9 Even in treatment it might not be ninety-percent. 7, 13, 18 AS: Right, exactly!  MS: [laughter] 9 AS: Even when they are in the building.  MS: Yeah, yeah. 8 AS: Anything else that you want to say? 8, 14 MS: Ah, man.  Oh, just a little bit more about... you know, so I was talking about how we switched from basically a programmatic model and it wasn't all Core Twelve, there was other influences going on, but Core Twelve was the major influence in switching this through-out the whole organization. 6, 7, 8, 14, 17, 20 Part of it was going down a path of insurance, you know, and trying to work with insurers. 7, 17 AS: Oh, okay. 14 MS: So, changing from, you're coming into treatment for four weeks whether you need it or not, right? 5, 7, 8, 13, 14, 16, 18 Four weeks is it. 16 Maybe you can stay for six, but four weeks of treatment and then you are leaving and there won't be any follow up. 7, 13, 14, 16, 18 Betty Ford was still doing that when we merged. 7 Yeah, and there are some longer-term programs for the people that could afford it, because it was purely private pay, but hardly anyone could afford that. 5, 6, 7, 8, 18, 20 And there are still all kinds of programs doing that nowadays, private pay and long-term treatment. 5, 7, 8, 12, 13, 17, 18, 19 And some of that probably gets better outcomes because it is long term treatment. 7, 12, 13, 17, 18, 20 AS: Because it is long term, right. 7, 8, 14 MS: It's just that no one can afford to do that, or like the one-percent can, I guess. 12, 19 And so, so now our model is that residential is for diagnosis and stabilization, and not just diagnosis if your substance use disorder, it's all the mental health too. 5, 7, 9, 17 AS: It's about all of the mental health, right, right. 8, 14 MS: And then, we want you to go to day treatment with sober housing in IOP, intensive out patient, prior to sober housing and then we want you seeing a counselor or somebody once a week, or every couple of weeks for a while. 5, 6, 7, 10, 13, 14, 16, 18, 19, 20 It's a chronic illness, let's be sure that you are really stable and that you've got a foot hold in recovery. 6, 7, 8, 16, 18 So, that's how we started and how, because of the long-standing nature of the craving, like I said earlier, and other factors, and the high relapse rate with opioids, I wanted long term involvement. 5, 6, 7, 11, 13, 14, 15, 17 And insurance of course doesn't want to pay for that. 14, 18 AS: Right.  MS: Shortening residential reduces the cost dramatically and allows for longer out patient. 7, 9, 14, 17, 20 Right, right. 8, 14 MS: Yeah, cause then you can shift your cost to the out-patient and get it really long. 6, 7, 8, 9, 20 AS: So, you were part of that, that thinking? 8 MS: Oh yeah, that's Core Twelve, that's was our thinking. 7, 8 We've got to keep people... 17 AS: Oh, that came out of Core Twelve? 7, 13, 17 That has now been applied... you've seen the benefits for people who don't have opioid issues. 5, 7, 13, 17 MS: Yeah, yeah, it's become our model as a whole now. 8, 17, 18 Long term care for people. 7, 14, 20 And there were other influences.  It wasn't just me, but I was doing it both for Core Twelve and suggesting we do it because it is a chronic illness. 7 [laughter] 9 AS: I know, yeah. 8, 17 MS: I mean my own experience was four weeks of treatment in 1974 and relapse in five days, no care of any kind, told to go to AA... 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19, 20 AS: No support groups, right. 8, 9, 11, 14, 18 AS: And you were also a teenager. 15 MS: Yeah, yeah. 8 AS: You think of all of the risk factors.  MS: There was no professional...  No, there wasn't anything available. 10, 18 AS: So, what would you say your most proud of in your work? 14 MS: I would say Core Twelve itself. 7, 14 I am most proud of that for my entire career. 7, 14, 20 Although, one thing I am doing right now comes as a close second. 6, 8, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 MS: And over the long run, may be more important, I don't know but I've instituted a program that we can FIT. 7, 8, 17 It's Feedback Informed Treatment and it is in our electronic health record where we have a portal for our patients. 7, 11, 15, 17, 19 And they can go into that portal and we want them every week to fill out these objective tools about how they are doing. 14, 16 And they are in the literature, the research literature, all of these tools, well, not all of them. 7, 8, 12 Three of them are in the research literature and are associated with positive outcomes from treatment. 7, 12, 13, 17, 18 They've been used individually, never in combination. 9, 13 And then we added two tools that are used in primary-care. 7, 9, 14, 20 One for anxiety and one for depression and the new understanding of addiction as a disease is one of... initially it is all about positive reinforcement, ""it feels good, I am going to do it again"". 6, 7, 8, 13, 15, 17, 18, 19 Then it becomes negative reinforcement, ""I feel so bad but when I get high, it's relieved"". 7, 11, 13, 17, 18, 20 And that negative reinforcement is a release of negative stimuli. 7, 19 And so, the whole kind of new neurobiological theory of addiction is that it is negatively reinforcement associated with a combination of depression and anxiety and angst that is sort of driving continued use and driving relapse. 6, 7, 8, 9, 15, 18, 19 And so, no one has ever measured to see if anxiety and depression are high... do people have more relapses? 5, 7, 11, 12, 13 Or if they are low, do they have less?  AS: Right.  MS: And it is not necessarily anxiety and depression that are true anxiety disorders or mood disorders, it's just that negative affective state that is associated with addiction. 5, 7, 8, 15, 17 And so, we added those two so we can do that and see, but also to see if they are predictive by themselves. 5, 7 So, now we have all five of these, we're asking our patients to fill out weekly. 15, 16, 17 AS: Woah.  MS: And they fill it out online, it goes into their chart and we're working with our electronic health record provider so it'll come up as a graph so you can see it over time, but then the next thing is we'll be figuring out interventions based on certain scoring. 5, 7, 11, 16, 17, 19 AS: Things that they say? 14 That they report? 7 MS: Yeah, to see if they are doing great, not going to change much, if they aren't then we better do some changing and what exactly that we change and what makes a difference. 5, 7, 8, 9, 17, 18 It is going to take a decade or more. 20 AS: That might overshadow.  [laughter] 9 MS: So those two I am very proud of.  AS: What's interesting about that though is that also has a really hopeful... 6, 7, 8, 9, 13 [laughter] 9 AS: That's a very positive... 7 I don't know how to say it. 14, 17 It has a positive overlay to it, versus the intensity of the opioid epidemic which is that you are trying to prevent death. 5, 7 MS: Exactly.  AS: This is a program where you are trying to like, keep people supported and feeling loved and cared about, right? 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 17, 18, 20 Whereas with Core and with the opioid epidemic, we're just trying to keep people alive so that they might get better at some point. 5, 7, 10, 11, 17, 20 MS: True.  In fact, one of the medicines... 8 AS: It makes sense to me why would you excited about this. 9, 18 Sorry, you were going to say? 14 MS: But still, Core Twelve is currently the best thing I have done in my career. 7, 13, 14, 19, 20 [laughter] 9 AS: Yeah, that's really good. 6, 7, 8, 19 MS: Although, I did really like individual work with patients. 6, 7, 8, 15 This is probably more important in an overall scheme of things and probably has already effected more people 