"10","Eden_Frank_Rae","Marvin Seppala Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer November 6, 2018 Minneapolis, Minnesota Marvin Seppala -MS Amy Sullivan -AS AS: This is Amy Sullivan interviewing Dr. Marv Seppala.  It is November 6, 2018.  We are at Hazelden Betty Ford Foundation in Center City.  Dr. Seppala, do you give me permission to record this? 7, 11 MS: Yes, I do.  AS: Alright, thank you. 8, 9, 14 So tell me—you might state your name, your birthday, where you grew up. 7, 11, 13, 17, 19 MS: Okay, my name is Marvin Seppala. 11 I go by Marv. My birthday is July 22nd, 1956. 19 Born in Seattle, Washington to Finnish parents. 7, 12 I am 100% Finnish.  My mom immigrated from Finland with her brother to Tacoma, where a second-cousin sponsored him after World War II. 7, 13, 16, 17 My dad, his parents were both born in Finland and he grew up in Northern Minnesota in Virginian after it got logged out. 5, 7, 12, 19 My grandfather was a lumberjack.  He moved out to Tacoma with the family to the other Finnish community. 7, 11, 14, 19 AS: Oh wow, so you had roots in Minnesota too. 14 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 So ultimately, we moved back here and I grew up in Stewartville, Minnesota. 7, 11, 14, 17, 19 AS: Stewartville.  How old were you when you moved back here? 11, 14, 16, 17, 19 MS: So, I would have been eight when we moved to Minnesota, but we lived in Eden Prairie for just a few years. 11, 14, 16 Before the start of sixth grade I moved to Stewartville. 6, 11, 14, 19 AS: And what do your folks do? 17 MS: My dad was a chemical engineer at IBM and my mom was a housewife. 9, 11, 12, 17 AS: Mmhmm.  And you’re, are you… 7 tell me about your siblings, or... MS: Sure. 7, 13 I am the oldest of five and I have three brothers and the last sibling is a sister. 15, 16 She is ten years younger than me. 6, 16 AS: Oh lucky girl [laughter] 9, 12 MS: [laughter] 9 So, that ten-year gap was big because it was at seventeen when I was kicked out of the house for my addiction. 8, 9, 11, 15, 16 She was just seven years old, so we never really bonded very much. 6, 7, 8, 13, 16 AS: Oh, right, right. 8, 14 Right, you wanna talk about that? 6 [laughter] 9 You kind of jumped to it.  MS: [laughter] 9 I know, I did jump to something AS: Seventeen, being kicked out, it seems like an important place. 5, 8, 11, 17 You want to go a few years before that? 14, 16 What happened in Stewartville, you got there in sixth grade? 5, 19 MS: Yeah, just before the start of sixth grade. 6, 19 AS: What was that like? 9, 14 MS: You know, it was funny because I think about it... 8, 17 Seattle, San Jose, Bloomington, Eden Prairie... and then Stewartville.  For me, as a kid, at that age, I didn't notice the difference really, in terms of being in a big city and then being in a really small town. 6, 7, 8, 12, 15 My focus, this was the fourth move already, and every four years, which is kind of funny when I start college and medical school.... training is every four years! 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 16, 18 AS: Oh yeah, your life is in four years, that’s interesting MS: [laughter] 7, 8, 9, 16 Which seemed kind of nice is a way, it was weird. 5, 14 AS: So, every four years you’re like hmm… 7, 16 is it time to go somewhere now? 7, 16, 17, 19 MS: [laughter] 9 So, what my difficulty was being a somewhat self-conscious, anxious kid and now I've got to make new friends and start a new class, and I don't know anybody. 5, 6, 7, 10, 12, 13, 15, 17, 18 AS: Yeah, and in sixth grade that’s starting to be awkward. 5, 6, 19 MS: Yeah, it was really awkward. 6, 7, 8 But also, in a small town, I think it may have been easier. 12 I don't know that. 17 I met people pretty readily, in class of course, in the only school [laughter]. 5, 6, 7, 9, 11, 12, 14 AS: One school, where all the kids are in the whole town [laughter]. 9, 11, 15 MS: Everyone in sixth grade is there, so it worked out that way [laughter]. 9, 12, 19 AS: So, who’d you meet?  How’d you start getting in trouble? 6, 15, 20 MS: Sixth grade was nothing like that. 19 It was that summer though, after sixth grade, so twelve-years-old.... 16, 17, 19 I'm just trying to get this right. 8, 14, 20 Yeah, so twelve years old, it must have been the start of seventh grade and I am at a farm with two friends, Kim and Rick, both guys, at Rick's family farm, right outside of Stewartville. 6, 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 19 And, I don't know how this idea comes up but all the older guys that we looked up to, are like the athletes and the sports teams. 5, 6, 8, 13, 15, 16, 17 You know everybody. 17 So seventh grade we were in the high school. 11, 19 There was no junior high. 11, 16 It was seventh grade through twelfth. 19 So sixth grade I was in grade school and seventh grade I'm with everybody. 11, 19 All the older guys are drinking and they're all the really popular guys and the guys on the athletic teams. 5, 6, 7, 8, 15, 16, 19 My mother was a cross-country skier in Finland growing up and was on the Olympic team but broke a leg and never got to compete. 5, 10, 13 Her dad, my grandfather, was a world-champion cross country skier. 10, 12 So I grew up with athletics being a really big deal. 6, 7, 8, 19 So was academics.  But in my mind as a kid, athletics was certainly more important. 6, 14, 15 So, these athletes are all doing something that we're not supposed to but it seems like fun so I am attracted to it. 5, 14 So the three of us are at the farm, we steal some whiskey out of the kitchen and we go out to the barn, which we had to clean [laughter]. 9, 12, 15, 16, 19 It was just part of the deal. 8 It was a little dairy farm. 9, 19, 20 And we drank. 18 I can still remember it. 7, 13, 15 At one point in my training, I was at the VA hospital and the councilor there, this ex-chief-petty-officer in the Navy, six-five, big guy. 6, 8, 10, 11, 18 Chief Petty Officers are known for being very deliberate, really strong minded. 6, 7, 8, 12, 17 So he was this incredible guy, remarkably passionate about what he did for these veterans. 6, 7, 17 He had them all describe their first drink. 16, 19 And they almost to a person, they could. 10, 15, 17 AS: Really?  MS: It really captured them somehow. 6, 7, 8, 17 As if something really important had happened. 5, 6, 7, 8 AS: What is that called, in addiction medicine? 8, 13, 14, 15, 17 There’s a name for that. 11 MS: I can't remember that. 7, 13, 15 So I'm not sure if I should do it really, but I'm all in. 6, 7, 8 AS: But you remember it feeling good? 6, 7, 13, 15, 17, 18, 19 MS: I remember I just could hardly understand why anyone would swallow this stuff. 6, 7, 13, 15 It tasted so bad.  It burnt my throat and then all of the sudden, feeling like I belonged. 7, 13, 17, 18 Like I was part of these other two guys who had grown up together and I no longer had these worries or fears about that or anything else really. 6, 7, 8, 11, 15, 16, 20 It was like I was suddenly part of the world or something. 8, 12, 17 I don’t know, it was like my whole life changed. 5, 6, 7, 8, 17 It was really remarkable. 6, 7, 8, 18 And I knew I was going to do it again. 6, 12 That's for sure. 7 I didn't get to for months, but it was like a goal. 11, 20 I wanted to feel that way again. 13, 14, 18 So, ultimately, the following summer, I did again. 17, 19 Then I started doing it more frequently that summer. 6, 7, 15, 17 AS: Do you remember if you got drunk the first time you tried it, or you just got the buzz? 7, 8, 11, 13, 15, 16, 19 MS: I didn't get sick or anything. 20 We just took a few sips each, you know, because we had to replace the bottle. 7, 8, 17 [laughter] 9 So it was mostly just this remarkable feeling. 5, 7, 13, 17, 18 AS: Yeah, that warmth, and... MS: Yeah, and there was more to it.  It felt like I was part of something for the first time, and that is a strange thing to describe. 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 In the midst of my addiction, it seemed like it was almost a quest to feel that way. 5, 8, 13, 15, 18 It was almost like this spiritual quest because it felt like that almost, at the onset. 6, 15 And almost every new drug I took was that same sensation of ""Wow. 6, 10, 15 This is what life should be like."" 7, 8, 9, 14 It never would last. 13 I never really could get back to it. 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 17, 19, 20 There was a sense that I am missing something and I am looking for it, and seeking it, and never finding it. 5, 6, 9, 13 Except for those first couple of times with each particular substance. 7, 8, 9, 16, 19 Other people have told me that as well over the years of my work. 8, 13, 16 And even I've heard some speakers describe the same thing in regard to their substance use. 7, 9, 14, 19 It certainly was for me. 14 It was just like, ""Man. 9, 14 This is what I thought life would be like."" 7, 8, 9, 10, 14 AS: Yeah, and to be twelve or thirteen... how old were you? 16 MS: Yeah, twelve the first time. 7, 16, 19 So a year later, drinking again with some friends and then an older brother of one of my friends that was a year ahead of me in school had just returned from the University of Minnesota after his freshman year. 5, 7, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 19 He was a guy I really looked up to, both an athlete and a really good student. 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 19 He was on the honor roll and everything.  Also went to the same church as I did, and overall, just a really good guy. 6, 7, 8, 19 So, he comes back and tells the two of us that he is smoking pot at the University and describes the importance of it and how fun it was. 7, 10, 11, 13, 17, 19 And I remember saying, ""I would never do that."" 7, 13, 14, 15 That was my initial response. 7 I am really young, and then, a week later, I'm doing that. 5, 6, 7, 8, 16 [laughter] 9 AS: That was short [laughter]. 9 MS: [laughter]. 9 It's funny because I have certainly read about peer pressure and thought about peer pressure in regard to its influence on people. 7, 8, 10, 14 When I look back on my own life in regard to substance use, I was always pushing the envelope and seeking more substance use and I needed to find people who were doing the same, so that I wouldn't stick out. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 17, 19 There might have been some peer pressure to start something… 6, 7 once I got going, I didn't want people to know how often I was using, how much I was using, all of the different drugs I was using. 7, 10, 14, 17, 18 AS: Right.  So you looked for those people… 13 MS: I had to hang out with people who were doing the same so I wouldn't feel as bad. 5, 13, 18 AS: Right.  So it was more like peer support. 9, 14 All of this shame and guilt about doing it at all.  At least I wouldn't have to be around people who would elicit that in me.  [laughter]. 9 AS: Right, right. 8, 14 That’s really powerful, that’s a really interesting take on it. 6, 7, 8, 9, 20 Because other people get blamed a lot—the “bad kids.” 15 And I was probably one of those bad kids because I did try and convince my friends. 7, 12, 13, 15 You know, ""You gotta try this now! 17 I smoked pot and it is so much fun. 10 It was only a couple of people, less than a handful of people that I would do that with. 7, 13 It was the late Sixties, early Seventies. 5, 6 It was one thing to do it quietly, it was another to get other people involved. 19, 20 There were a few friends that every time I tried something new, I would go tell them just how great this was too. 6, 7, 8, 13, 16, 19 You know, ""You gotta try this."" 17 [laughter] 9 So I was probably pressuring other people for sure. 7, 12, 13 AS: So you’re smoking pot, at this point you’re thirteen, fourteen… 7, 10, 16 MS: Yeah, thirteen or fourteen and once I kind of broke through smoking pot when other drugs became available, I didn't have that same resistance or hesitance. 7, 10, 13, 17, 18 I just tried it.  So speed was available, and not that much else. 8, 10, 18 There was LSD.  Sometimes. 7, 12, 16, 19 AS: Who were you getting it from? 15, 20 These college kids, when they came home? 13, 15, 17, 19 MS: You know, there would always be someone in town, usually an older guy. 6, 10, 15, 16, 17 [laught