17, 18, 20 But it was usually still within this same, well-known group that that occurred. 7, 8, 12, 17, 18 And with that, I had summer jobs, but until I was over sixteen I really couldn't drive. 6, 7, 8, 14, 15, 17 So I couldn't really get a job. 6, 7, 8, 20 We had a minor allowance.  I had to start finding a way to get drugs or get money, so illegal stuff fairly early on to do so. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 20 AS: What would you do, like steal stuff?  MS: Yeah, steal stuff or sell it. 19 The first time we took the whiskey from the parents' supply in the kitchen. 7, 12, 16, 19 That next summer I had gotten a job loading trap at the local gun club. 7, 10, 16, 17, 19 The guy who picked us up to go to the gun club had this really old rusted out station wagon and he always brought the booze out to the gun club. 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 16, 20 So he would carry in the cases of beer and cases of whiskey, whatever, into the gun club. 10, 12, 13, 14, 20 It was part of the job. 8 It didn't occur to me at the time because I was younger, it was like the seventh or eighth grade. 6, 7, 16, 19 At this later point when I started drinking, thirteen or fourteen, was when I realized that.... 5, 6, 7, 10, 15, 16, 19 No, so this is what happened. 5 I was hiking... this would be early spring, late winter. 5, 6 I am in boy scouts and there are three of us out on a hike.  We're out on the root river and we've got one 22-caliber rifle, a single shot. 7, 9, 20 Once in a while we were shooting something.  We're just hiking along the riverbed and it was a really unusual day. 6, 7, 8, 9, 19 The river ice was breaking up. 7, 9, 10 There were these giant chunks of ice floating down the river. 9 This is the same Rick that I drank with the first time. 7, 16, 18, 19 So he and I tell my brother Brian, who is also with us, we give him the 22 and we hang out from this oak branch that’s out over the river waiting for a big chunk to come off and we dropped on top of it. 5, 9, 11, 13, 16, 17 The two of us-- Brian stayed on shore. 7, 14, 16 Brian then threw us a big stick so we could control it. 7, 10 [laughter] 9 This is a big chunk of ice, probably not quite as wide as this room but pretty close. 5, 6, 7, 9, 12, 13, 14, 19 At least how I remembered it. 7, 13, 15 We picked it because it was so big. 5 The river of course was swelling because of the melt-off and I had never seen this before. 5, 8, 9, 13 I haven't seen it since. 5, 13 It was really a remarkable day. 6, 7, 8, 18, 19 We're going down the stream, not fast, but we're moving decent. 7 We realize that every time we move the ice chunk with our stick to try and control it, we just go slower than in the current. 7, 10, 14, 16, 19 So we toss our stick, so we eliminate the only control we have for navigating this thing. 10, 19 We're going along... it was a long straight section where we started, so we're just thinking, ""This is great."" 6, 7, 8, 15 We come around a bend and there is this chunk of ice, a dam of ice chunks across the river. 9, 17, 18 They look kind of smaller than ours. 12 Ours is just big so we thought that we'll just hit this and we'll go right through that dam. 8, 10, 14, 19 That was our discussion.  It was limited to that.  We're right in the middle of the river at this point, the river is wider than this room. 8, 9, 10, 14 We hit that dam of ice chunks and ours starts to go under. 6, 19 I can still remember these little ice chunks going out from under our feet as we're trying to run across them to get to shore. 7, 8, 13, 15, 20 We went towards the shore that Brian was on, I think it was just closer, it wasn't that far. 6, 7, 9, 13 Maybe here to that wall, ten feet at most.  All of the sudden it all breaks through, just as we're reaching a four foot bank of mud. 7, 10, 17 Luckily, there were tree roots in that bank of mud and both of us managed to grab those roots. 15 We're soaking wet, we crawl up the mud, we get out, and it doesn't even occur to us that we almost died. 15, 17, 20 We're just like, ""Wow, that was exciting!"" 9, 14 [laughter]. 9 The reason for this story is that we get up... 7, 10, 13, 17, 20 We were meeting my mom, who dropped us off, and we were meeting her at Low Water Bridge to start the hike at the Gun Club. 6, 17 That's a nice spot for pick up. 5, 10, 14 We were just going to go down the river, but we're on the wrong side now. 6, 9, 17 Usually there is a place where we could cross near the gun club. 8, 10 It's maybe a third of a mile across a field from the gun club. 10, 16, 20 It is usually really shallow. 6, 7, 8 But because of the swelling it was much deeper. 8 Brian is up above his knees, we're all really cold. 6, 7, 8, 16 It is melting.  It is not warm out.  So we're probably close to hypothermia, soaking wet. 6, 10, 12, 13 It is getting towards late afternoon, so we're briskly getting up to the gun club. 5, 10, 15, 20 Because I'm freezing and we're there early... 6, 7 My mom wasn't going to be there for some time. 7, 16, 17, 19 We didn't have cell phones or anything. 6, 12, 14 We were just counting on a specific time. 7, 16, 19 I remembered that when I worked there, the back window by the backdoor, this tiny little window, little tiny back porch, a few steps up to this 3 x 5 back porch where the kitchen was, this window was unlocked. 7, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 17, 19, 20 It was broken.  I remembered that for some reason when I worked there. 7, 10, 12, 13, 15, 17 So I say, ""Let's see if that thing opens."" 5, 14, 19, 20 We can go in and get heated up, we can warm up.  So I try the window, which is up above and it was open. 20 So I crawl through, open the door for those guys, we all go in and we turn the heat on and the ovens on. 6, 8, 15, 17, 20 Everything we could to get heat and warmed up. 20 We took our clothes off and hung them over the deep fat fryer.  I realized I can break into the gun club, but this is meaningless to me at that time besides that we got warmed up and my mom comes and we're all dry, basically. 7, 10, 14, 16, 17, 19 She didn