apers, we're all going to meet in court and you will be forced in here."" 13, 14, 17 I don't believe that it could have happened, cause when I got into training later, that wasn't even possible in the Eighties. 5, 8, 9, 16 No, but I'm thinking when he said that, the last thing I want is to be in any legal situation, in court. 7, 13, 14, 19 You've got to be kidding! 15 I'm a drug addict! 10, 15 AS: Right.  What else could they find out about you? 8, 9 MS: Right.  I can't admit to this.  So, I can't go to court.  So, I say ""Okay."" and I sign the papers and I stay. 14 And I am put on the men's unit, in the original farm house that Hazelden started in, in 1949. 6, 9, 11, 15, 19 AS: That little white house? 9, 11, 15, 19, 20 That was a unit.  This building wasn't here, but the parts that were left of the other buildings were built in 1969. 8, 19 So, I am here in 1974, but they were still using the original farm house as a men's unit. 7, 9, 10, 11, 19 That's where they put me. 19 And I find out later that, that unit, called ""The Old Lodge"" was for people who had multiple treatments and really hardcore addicts. 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18 And they put me there because they didn't know what to do with a seventeen-year-old. 16, 17, 19 Because, five years later, I find out I was the first adolescent to ever be treated here. 5, 7, 9, 13, 16 And that's where they put me. 19 So, I am with all of these older guys, I am the youngest by a long shot. 6, 7, 8, 15, 16, 20 And I argue that I don't belong there at all. 7 AS: You spent time doing that? 7, 16, 19 MS: Yeah, well, two weeks. 8, 16 It wasn't a lot of time. 7, 16, 19 AS: Oh, you were only here for two weeks? 16 MS: I was here for four weeks, but the first two I argued. 16 You know, ""I do not belong here, I don’t have this chemical dependency."" 7, 17 I still have the Big Book of Alcoholics Anonymous that they gave me, and the Twelve by Twelve, the twelve steps and twelve traditions. 7, 12, 16, 18 In the margin of the first step in the Twelve Steps and Twelve Traditions, I have these little cryptic notes about why I don't belong here, why I'm not an alcoholic. 7, 10, 13, 16, 20 AS: That’s incredible. 7 [laughter]. 9 [laughter] 9 So, every day we would have to fill out something called a significant events sheet, just something we learned today or something we had experienced today. 5, 13, 14, 15, 17, 19 And every day, mine was why I don't belong here. 7, 19 I am making my argument day in and day out, based on the books and my experience and what people say. 14, 15, 19 And I am fairly bright guy, and I am writing this up every day. 6, 8, 14, 19 And every morning, there was an intercom system that would say, ""Marvin Seppala, please come to the unit office."" 9, 14, 17, 18 [laughter] 9 It's my councilor, who sits me down to talk over my argument with me. 6, 7 It was never a bullying thing or us butting heads, he is just suggesting that my argument is not right. 8, 12, 13, 14, 19 And he is doing it in a way that makes sense, but I just don't care and I don't belong here anyways, so I'm not going to listen. 7, 9, 14, 18, 20 This is the wonderful thing about group therapy for addiction, actually, is that in the midst of this resistance on my part that I might be an addict, that I can't even see, I can absolutely see it in everyone else in the group. 5, 7, 8, 15, 18, 19 I mean they are describing it.  Even if they believe it or not, I can see it. 5, 9 I mean, they have given all of these examples, you know? 11, 17 They've described their life and they should be here because of what they have been doing. 7, 8 And they're a lot older, but they have lost their jobs, they have lost families, and all of these things. 5, 15, 16, 19 And I can see it in them. 5 And then it finally starts to dawn on me that all of these examples that I am using about them are the same examples in my life, you know. 6, 7, 8, 10, 17 Whether they have pointed it out or my councilors have pointed it out, or that I have thought it through, which was not much. 10 It is exactly the same.  It finally occurred to me. 7 I go to my councilor and tell him that I finally believe that I have this chemical dependency, whatever that is, and that I have to do something about it, and he kicked me out of his office. 9, 11, 13, 18 He said, ""You finally realized the only way out of here."" 7, 10, 13, 14 [Laughter]  Which truly wasn’t the case.  AS: But he thought you were pulling one over on him, he didn’t believe you at that point because you had been arguing so, so smartly. 9, 10, 20 MS: Oh, yeah. 8 Yeah, it was like that one day and then the next day it was like, ""Wait a minute."" 9, 14, 16, 19 So, I talked to my peers and they were like, ""Well it does seem like you kind of changed your tune about this."" 5, 6, 9, 13, 14 So, they just took me in, and they had all along. 7, 15 Which was the most amazing thing about being here, is that they accepted me, which wasn't happening much in my life. 5, 7, 8, 19 They understood what I was going through, which I wasn't telling anybody. 13 Not even my closest friends understood me. 6, 7, 13 And they valued what I said, which wasn't happening with anyone I knew. 5, 6, 7, 12, 13, 14 And they validated my experience, which I couldn't even understand because I didn't know what I was doing or why. 15, 17 They understood that and validated that for me.  They cared about me. 7, 14, 20 That is what got my attention. 6 In addition to that, the other counselor on the unit was Ed Jergins. 20 He was this really big, bald, Scandinavian. 6, 7, 8 And my dad and my grandfather are both bald Scandinavians, so I wanted nothing to do with Ed. 14 He scared me. 7, 14, 20 My father and my grandfather were pretty mean, stoic, Finns, right? 5, 7, 8, 14 So, I assume he is exactly the same.  He is bigger than those two.  So, I stay away from him. 14, 20 Then, I'm in group, and this was before that I even figured out that I had this. 7, 18, 19 Ed is sitting there and his eyes are closed and I assume this old guy is sleeping. 6, 7, 9, 13, 14, 16, 18 He was all drooped.  He is supposed to be the councilor and he looks like he is fast asleep. 11, 14 This guy is talking about his marriage and how he wants to get a divorce, and all of the sudden, Ed starts talking from this position. 6, 7, 14, 15, 17, 20 He raises his head and starts to open his eyes and he has heard every single bit of this. 6, 7, 9, 12, 14, 20 He wasn't sleeping at all. 7 And he expresses this most incredible statement about this guy. 6, 7, 17 Just this really supportive statement and then talks to the whole group in this incredibly loving manner and then he starts talking about love, which I have never heard a male talk about in my life. 6, 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 17, 18 And that got my attention. 6 It was unbelievable. 18 Then after witnessing him do this a few times, and I realize that he talks about spirituality and love all the time, and that, I wanted that. 6, 7, 14, 16, 17, 19 I didn't want to get sober, but I wanted that. 14, 20 Then I wanted that and I wanted to get sober. 14, 20 And I was also starting to experience whatever that was from those guys who were really serious about getting sober too, at least the small group of guys I would stay up at night with and talk about things with. 5, 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 19, 20 Which was just amazing.  We’d talk about life, really, for the first time in my life. 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 I had a few friends that I could do that with on occasion, but it almost wasn't even real. 7, 13, 15 It was during this period in my life where I was just getting high all the time, so I'm just a mess anyways. 7, 8, 11, 15, 16, 19, 20 I don't know what I was saying or thinking. 14, 17 Sometimes I felt like there was really a bond there with Ed and with this group. 6, 7, 8, 12, 16, 18, 19 So, I really decided that I've got to do something. 6, 7, 8 But that wasn't enough. 16, 20 I was scared to leave, because four weeks really isn't enough. 6, 7, 8, 14, 16, 20 It goes by quick.  And it was four weeks, whether you needed it or not. 9, 16 It was twenty-eight days back then, and that was it. 11, 17, 18, 19 There was no follow up of any kind for a seventeen-year-old in Rochester, Minnesota. 16 They told me to go to AA. 13, 16 This is the only thing, this is it. 19 There wasn't anything else. 8 There really wasn't anything else in 1974. 6, 7, 8 So, they told me to go to AA, and they would have anyway, but that was the only thing. 13, 16, 19 And there is no AA in Stewartville.  So, I get back. 11, 17, 19, 20 They get me back into high school and back into my house with my family. 7, 9, 11, 17, 19, 20 I wasn't really out of the house, that was part of the deal, I would live at home. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 17, 19 I went back to school and they told me not to hang out with my old friends because they are all using. 5, 7, 10, 11, 13, 16, 17, 19 So, this is a long time in the early part of my life... 6, 7, 8, 16, 19 That’s okay. 14 We’re good if you’re good. 6, 7, 19 MS: Good deal, okay. 14 So, I go to school and it's a small town and a small school. 11, 12 One hundred in my graduating class. 6, 12 The people who I am not supposed to hang out with, I just stay away from. 5, 14, 20 I am trying to do it.  And the people who don't use drugs, especially, they want nothing to do with me. 8, 9, 10, 14 And there were all of these rumors about where I had gone and what I had done.  Just wild rumors.  People had told their kids to stay away from me. 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 You know, it was a small town. 12, 17 So, I am kind of ostracized.  AS: You are alone. 12 MS: Yeah, I was alone. 12 And it hit me rather quickly. 5, 19 I was already sensitive to such things anyway, and I never really felt like I had belonged that much. 5, 6, 7, 8, 13, 18, 19 I had some friends that were kind of close, but very few and they were all using, so I couldn't hang out with them anyway. 5, 6, 7, 10, 13 But on the weekend before I left, that prior week before I left treatment, I really worried about going home. 6, 7, 8, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 I don't know that I am ready. 7, 17, 18 I am just really scared but I just really want to leave. 6, 7, 8, 14, 20 Both are going through my head. 12 And I see an ad for a Marshall Tucker Band concert in the Twin Cities. 5 So, I decide, that is a great idea, which is really the last thing I should be doing because I had never gone to a concert without being wasted. 5, 6, 7, 8, 13, 19 Somehow, I don't know how it happened, I think it was after I got home, I convinced my best friend using Dave, that we should go see Marshall Tucker. 5, 10, 13, 17, 19 And this is after these few days of trying to be alone, I decide I am going to go to something with Dave and go see Marshall Tucker. 5, 12, 18, 19 So, we get tickets. 20 As we are driving to Minneapolis/St Paul, he is driving, and smoking pot and drinking. 10, 15, 18, 19 And I am sitting there and telling him all about treatment and why I can never use again. 7, 9, 13, 18 I am like lecturing the whole way to Minneapolis/St.  Paul and  I tried also to convince him, because he is my best friend who is doing exactly what I do, that he has to stop as well, right? 8, 13, 14 So, he doesn't buy that at all. 20 He doesn't argue with me because most of what I am saying seems to make sense to him, just not for him. 5, 9, 14, 18 So, we get to the concert, we meet some other people there. 20 And there's pot being passed up and down the row and a joint comes by and I took it and smoked it. 9, 10, 17 I took some, and then more, and then had some beer, and I don't know what else. 8, 17, 20 I was just right back to where I was, just like that. 8, 11, 14, 17, 19 Not any thought about it. 10 Didn't even feel bad about it until later. 5, 13, 16, 18 When we get in the car and we're going back, I finally realize what I have done. 7, 11, 14, 17, 19, 20 I think I was trying to convince myself in telling Dave not to let anybody know that this has happened. 5, 13, 17 That was how I was all along anyway. 7, 15 I tried so hard to not let anyone know about this, so I could live this double life of getting good grades, at least when I was in school, until I quit, and getting still high. 6, 7, 8, 11, 15, 17, 19, 20 So, I'm telling him that he can't tell anybody. 13 And I am kind of thinking that I won't keep doing this. 17 I was right back at it the next day with him. 8, 11, 14, 16, 17, 19 And everything I had told him on the way up was like a distant memory. 13, 16 I was just off and running. 8, 9 I got to go through the graduation ceremony with my class but I didn't get a diploma. 6, 7, 12, 20 I did go to school until graduation. 11 I showed up. 9 They even let me on the track team and I was pretending to.... 5, 7 I was smoking cigarettes and pot and drinking. 7, 10, 15, 19 I was a mess.  AS: Did your parents ever clue in that you were using again? 7, 10, 12, 13 MS: They really figured it out and they disowned me and kicked me out. 6, 7, 8, 11, 19 They told me they wouldn't pay for my education. 13, 16, 18 MS: Just a few weeks after the graduation ceremony. 7, 16 So, in June.  They got me a job with our next-door neighbor who was a contractor and I quit going. 16, 17, 19 I never quit a job and I never got fired, I just never showed up. 7, 9, 13, 19 So, I had some other job after they booted me out at Crenlo that built tractor cabs in Rochester. 7 When they kicked me out, I took my Volkswagen, threw my stuff in it and moved to Rochester. 7, 11, 14, 15 You can call that a move when you drive eleven miles without a place to land and just bum from friend to friend and live out of the car. 8, 11, 13, 14, 17 I got this job at Crenlo and then I quit going there. 7, 19 Every time I would just some money and get high and not go back. 7, 11, 12, 16, 17, 19, 20 I had no thoughts about a future, really. 6, 7, 8, 10 I just assumed I was going to die really young. 6, 7, 8 I didn't think I would survive.  Not graduating from high school was kind of meaningless, in spite of the fact that I had been to treatment. 7, 11, 13, 18 That was the only thing-- like I said, I hated lying in bed without being able to fall asleep. 11, 12, 13, 14, 18, 19 Well, it was even worse now, because I knew there was another way for me. 6, 12, 17 Morning and evening were really bad. 6, 7, 8 I failed to mention that my girlfriend at the time, Linda, came to treatment and visited me. 7, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 And so did Wayne, the guy in that car accident. 6, 14 They were the only two people.  She was the only girl who came to visit, besides my family. 7, 12, 13, 17, 19 And she and I were dating afterwards as well. 8 She didn't know what to make of all of this. 17, 18 She thought I shouldn't use because of what I had been told, but she didn't know anything about it either, except what I told her, basically. 9, 10, 13, 14, 16, 17 Which when I was in treatment, was pretty accurate. 5, 7, 13, 14, 18 So, I'm kind of living with her more than the other people at the time. 6, 7, 16, 19 My dad was at IBM, so I knew they wouldn't give me a job. 6, 11, 12 Mayo and IBM were the two primary employers. 20 So, I go to Mayo and I apply to be a janitor and they sent me away. 20 They didn't have a job.  I lied and said I graduated from high school. 11, 13, 14 Two weeks later, they called my mom and got a hold of Linda who found me, and they said to go back in for an interview. 5, 11, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19 They sent me over to a cardiovascular research lab where I am hired by David Donald, who is this world-famous physiologist, as a lab technician. 7, 12, 14 So, the way I look at this, I said I was attracted to Ed and his discussions of love and spirituality, and the same discussions I had with people in treatment. 7, 13, 14, 17, 18 I look at it as even before I started to care for myself, I was being cared for in really miraculous ways. 6, 7, 8, 14, 15, 20 I get into treatment when I was seventeen, when I shouldn't even be there. 7, 13, 18, 20 Then, I get this job. 20 I stayed sober for five days after treatment. 7, 13, 14, 16, 18, 19 I get this job and I stayed sober for two weeks. 14, 16, 20 And my intent was just to stay sober. 14 I tried as hard as I could and it lasted two weeks. 6, 16 On the first day on the job, it was an animal surgery lab, so we were studying a lot about hypertension and its causes and cardiac function and stuff. 5, 9, 14, 16, 19 People from all over the world came to work under Dr. Donald and John Shepard, who were the two leaders of the lab that I was assigned to. 12, 13, 17 Dr. Donald is this eccentric old physiologist. 16 He was trained as a veterinarian, but he became a physiologist and helped invent the heart-lung machine. 6, 13, 14, 17, 18 John  Shepard was the president of the American Heart Association at the time and he was on the board of governors and the board of trustees at the Mayo Clinic. 6, 7, 9, 16, 19 He was really one of the top administrators, the top docs in the whole place, and famous world-wide for research. 6, 7, 8, 12 So, suddenly, there is this drug addict working in their lab. 10, 15, 17 On the first day that I was there... 16, 19 AS: Who’s eighteen?  At this time I had turned eighteen. 7, 16, 18, 19 At the end of the day when they were orienting me to the job, it wasn't them, it was the other technicians, one of the technicians said, ""And there's the drug cabinet and you have to make sure that it is locked at the end of the day."" 7, 10, 13, 14, 18, 19 [laughter] 9 AS: That was your job to make sure it was locked? 7, 18 MS: Yeah, it was one of my jobs. 15 Yeah, and I'm thinking, there's no one that is going to pay more attention to that cabinet. 6, 12, 18 So, I last two weeks and we were studying cocaine. 5, 10, 16 I was weighing out cocaine for experiments. 10 Cocaine is a vasoconstrictor and it does it in a very specific manner.  We were studying how veins and arteries constricted and cocaine helped us to understand that process, physiologically to figure it out. 5, 7, 14, 17, 18 So, I took some.  Then I just took more and more, and over a few-weeks-period, I am just addicted to cocaine, in a way that I have never been addicted to anything. 10, 13, 15, 16 I am using a lot of it because I can just grab it out of the cupboard. 10 It's right back to something that isn't being paid for. 8, 11, 14, 17, 19 AS: And it’s not being monitored? 7 MS: No one is monitoring it. 12 I am the only one monitoring it. 12 There is no monitoring of any kind.  AS: Did you ever find out how you got this job? 9, 13 I have no idea. 5 Dr. Shepard was out of the country when Dr. Donald hired me. 7, 10 So, he hired me. 7 AS: But you had applied to be a janitor?  MS: I did, I applied to be a janitor.  So, actually, the day I started is when they told me about the drug cabinet. 6, 10, 13, 15, 16, 18, 19 The next day, second day at work, I realize that I have got to tell them that I haven't graduated from high school. 7, 11, 13, 16, 19 I didn't tell Dr. Donald, I went to the HR department and said, ""I haven't graduated from high school."" 7, 8, 11, 13, 14 I didn't say that I lied, but I did. 14 I made up another lie about why I didn't, this big family problem of some sort of why I missed half of my senior year. 7, 8, 11, 13, 16, 19 I don't mention that I went to addiction treatment or anything. 7, 8, 13, 15, 18 They still give me the job. 7, 11 They didn't even balk.  They we're just like, ""It's okay."" 9, 14 I don't have a clue how this happened. 5 I knew no one who worked at Mayo, no one in my family. 6, 7, 12, 19 I can only say again that I think I was being taken care of. 7, 14, 20 So, I just plummet with my addiction and I miss a week of work. 8, 12, 15, 16 Which doesn't seem like a lot, but I knew they warned me that I had a three-month probationary period. 5, 6, 12 They could fire me or I could just leave, no questions asked. 7, 15 Which I kind of liked, because that is how I left jobs anyways, but I didn't know that I was going to like this job. 8, 9, 14, 15, 17, 19 It turns out from the first moment I walked into that lab, I loved this job. 15, 16, 17, 20 It was like unbelievable to me. 18 I was stimulated in a way that I hadn't ever been in my whole life. 5, 7, 8, 13, 19 AS: And you were just mostly cleaning things up, and helping? 5, 7, 15, 16, 18, 19 But around things you were interested in. 5, 7, 19 MS: Well, yeah. 8 I had to assist in surgery on animals, mostly dogs but sometimes cats. 5, 7, 12, 16, 19 I would stand right across from the doctor or some fellows from all over the world. 8, 12, 14, 20 I was either assisting a fellow or Dr. Donald.  And they would tell me about the experiments and they would tell me what we were doing and why. 13 It was just fascinating to me.  I wanted to learn about it. 5, 14 Physiology, I found really interesting. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11 It explains things, right? 5, 8, 14, 19 I just found it incredible and I really liked these people too. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14 They cared about me. 7, 14, 20 It was somewhat similar to my experience in treatment, but remarkably, there wasn't really anything at an interpersonal level, but it was in a way because it was more about knowledge. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 15, 17, 18 But they also cared about me in other ways, like how come I'm not seeking college? 5, 7, 14, 17, 20 And what do you think about going on to school someday? 11, 19 Even at the very beginning.  Dr. Donald in the interview asked me how long I would commit to the lab. 7 I remember this question because that prior summer, I had gone to a recruiting thing in the Twin Cities with a friend to join the army. 7, 13, 15, 17, 19 I was so desperate.  The Vietnam War was over, but it was still a mess. 7 They put us up in a hotel and of course we just drank and goofed off. 18, 19 I had a physical the next day and in the physical, my hearing was inadequate. 14, 16, 19 I had hearing loss that I didn't know about until that moment. 14, 15, 17 So, they told me that I would have to sign a release if I wanted to be in the army because they didn't want to cover my hearing. 7, 13, 14, 16 So, I just couldn't imagine that.  For some reason, that stopped me. 7, 10, 15, 17 I didn't want to sign this release. 7, 14 But Dave went into the army.  My best friend. 13 So, I tell Dr. Donald that I just recently looked into going into the army for two years, so I'll stay two years. 7, 13, 14, 16 That was as far as I could think about my life. 7, 8, 9 You've gotta be kidding me, how long am I going to stay here?? 7, 14, 15 Two years. 16 I told him the story even, I just looked into going into the army but I couldn't because I have a hearing loss and I couldn't do it without a release and I didn't think that was wise. 7, 13, 14, 16 So, it turns out that he was in the Royal Airforce.  He didn't tell me that then, I learned it later. 5, 13, 16 Way later, at that talk that you said you were watching, after I gave that talk and I walked behind the stage, and a woman from Mayo's development department, a young woman, came up to me. 5, 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 20 I had just seen Saturday Night for the second time ever. 5, 7, 13, 16, 19 And she tells me that my father and I have just bought Dr. Donald's old house, that he had died and had donated his house to Oxbow Park in Biren, Minnesota, just outside of Rochester, because it was right adjacent from the park. 7, 8, 9, 11, 13, 14, 16, 17 He is a really eccentric guy. 6, 7, 8 He just lived out in the woods and he was really odd that way. 6, 7, 8, 11, 16 She said that we're going to turn it into a halfway house. 9, 11, 13, 14, 16, 20 She said because my father is in recovery and he wants to do that and I am going to help him with this because it is really important to me as well. 6, 7, 8, 13, 14, 18 And Dr. Donald was in recovery from alcoholism. 7, 8, 10 Well, he wasn't in recovery when I met him because on rare occasion, he had a terrible tremor in the morning doing surgery. 7, 8, 9, 12 I noticed it just a few times, but somehow, we connected. 7, 16, 17, 19 Most of these fellows came there to work under him and John Shepard, but none of them could really get along with him. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 15, 17, 20 And I got along with him fantastic. 7, 8, 15 Somehow, he hires me. 7 I have no clue.  I always tell people that I think he was playing a joke on John Shepard because Shepard was out of the country. 10, 13 I never saw him out of three-piece suit. 6, 13 He's like Mr. Clean.  Dr. Donald wore a white lab coat and had white athletic tape around his shoes holding them together. 7, 11, 15, 16, 19, 20 He is just this eccentric, brilliant guy. 6 So, I always thought, ""What the hell, he just hired me so he could give Shepard a hard time with this hippy drug-addict kid."", that he didn't know was a drug addict at the time. 6, 7, 10, 11, 14, 15, 16, 17, 19 I had long hair, I didn't look like anyone else in the lab. 7, 8 [laughter] 9 AS: So, you miss a week of work? 16 MS: Yes, I miss a week of work and I am so scared to lose the job, I am getting desperate. 7, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 AS: Were you taking cocaine home with you? 10, 17, 19 MS: Yeah, I had a big supply that I grabbed.  So, I was gone but I still had a supply. 7, 12 My folks had disowned me. 17 I didn't get back into the house for two years. 9, 11, 16, 17, 19, 20 AS: Really?  That’s hardcore. 6, 7 After a while, it was both parties’ kind of contributing. 8 Like, I wasn't going to go back there either. 11, 17, 19 There was no invitation either.  AS: That’s hard. 6 It was also probably good for my siblings because I was stealing from them too. 6, 12, 13, 19 I was just a disaster.  And I was certainly not being the role model of the kind that they needed. 9, 14 I never talked to my father, but in this desperation, I called him, which still kind of surprises me when I say it even. 6, 7, 13, 14, 17 I tell him exactly what is going on. 13 I am stealing cocaine from the Mayo Clinic, I am scared 7, 10, 14, 20 I am going to lose this great job and I don't want to lose it, and I don't know what to do. 7, 8, 13, 14, 17 He had, in the meantime since I had last seen him when he kicked me out, helped start this adolescent counseling center in Rochester and he was on the board of it. 5, 6, 7, 11, 13, 16, 18, 19 It was for kids with drug and alcohol problems. 7, 10, 15 AS: Really?  It was called Sunrise. 13, 14, 17 He says, ""I'll meet you tonight and we'll talk about this."" 6, 14, 17, 19 I tried to put it off because I didn't want to talk to him. 6, 14, 19 I would call, but that was as far as I was going to go. 9, 14, 17 And I am thinking, if I meet him tonight, then... 19 I can't use. 9 So, I don't want to meet him tonight. 14, 19 Somehow, I agreed. 7 We meet and then he brings me to Sunrise and he says that I can talk to somebody there about this. 6, 14, 17 And he knows that he is not the right person, too. 8, 10, 14, 17 I meet Jane, a counselor, who talks to me and I go back the next night and I don't do any cocaine. 6, 10, 11, 16, 17, 19, 20 And I go back the next night, and I don’t do any cocaine, and I realize that this place just opened and that she was a social worker. 7, 8, 10, 11, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 I learned that later when she worked at Hazelden and so did I. 5, 12, 16 [laughter] 9 But I realized that I know more about she does about addiction. 7, 8, 10, 15, 17 More than anyone there does, just from my one month of treatment, I know way more than they know. 7, 13, 17, 18 And, in treatment, they told me the only thing that is going to work is going to AA and I have not done that. 7, 13, 16, 18, 19 So, I go there one night that first week and I tell them that this is not going to work for me. 13, 16, 19 I don’t think this is going to work for me.  I didn't tell them that I think I know more about it than they do… 13, 17 I felt like I did. 6 I think I actually did, honestly. 6, 12, 18 I am going to go to AA like they told me to when I was in treatment. 7, 13, 16, 18 [End of Part I, beginning of Part II]  MS: So, I say that I am going to go to AA. 14 And I am sure they are thinking that this guy is not going to AA, right? 6, 7, 8, 14 They think that I am just going to go get high again and then he is gone. 11, 12, 20 And I didn't go back, so they never found out actually, until I met her much later. 5, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 AS: So, did you start going to AA? 6 I went to an AA meeting that Sunday morning in this club house, the only one that I was aware of at the time in Rochester. 6, 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 19 I don't think there was another one. 12 It was on Third Avenue.  There were three guys there over seventy. 6, 8, 15 That was their group? 18 MS: That was the group I walked into. 18, 20 Yeah, and I don't know what they said, I cannot remember. 7, 13, 14, 15, 17 But I went back the next Sunday. 11, 16, 17, 19 AS: There was only one a week? 16 MS: That's all that was recommended. 7 Once a week. 16 That’s what people did back then. 11, 17, 19 AS: So, we're in the state of Minnesota in 1974... MS: 1974... 17 MS: No, it was '74 still. 7 AS: Okay, still. 7 MS: And people went to one AA meeting a week. 6, 16 That is what they did and that is what they told me. 13, 16 Come on back next week. 11, 16, 17, 19 AS: Interesting, that is a new thing for me to know. 6, 7, 17, 19 MS: That was reinforced over time too. 7, 16, 19 If things are really, really bad, maybe you go to another one. 5, 6, 7, 8, 12, 16, 19 Maybe you call your sponsor and talk to people. 6, 13, 14, 17 But you couldn't really go to another one. 6, 7, 8, 12 AS: This is something that I will have to look up again, to understand when did it become that you should go every day. 17, 18, 19 MS: Because I moved around with school, you know, so all the sudden I was in places where people went a lot. 8, 11, 14, 17, 18, 20 I didn't know about that transition. 7, 17 I'll let you know when I find out. 9, 17 [laughter] 9 MS: So, I go back and these guys... 6, 8, 11, 15, 17, 19 I mean, I felt really connected with these guys. 6, 7, 8, 15 It was that same description in treatment. 7, 13, 18 They understood me, they accepted me, they validated me, they valued what I had to say. 14 I hardly talked, but they listened. 6, 13 They supported me and cared for me in ways that I was completely lacking. 7, 9, 14, 20 I hadn't had experience with it, so I went back. 11, 15, 17, 19 And whatever I wasn't getting at Sunrise, I got at AA that morning. 9, 15, 20 I know I got it. 17 I got there out of pure desperation. 7 I called my dad, I went to this Sunrise place. 8, 13, 14, 17 I walk into AA, which I was supposed to do after treatment months before. 7, 11, 13, 14, 18 AS: Right, but how would you have been able to do that given where you were? 11, 18 You went right back home. 8, 11, 14, 17, 19 You were set up to fail.  MS: Right.  Right back to the home where everything went on and school where everything went on. 11, 17, 19 So, AA was like an oasis or something for me.  These people really understood me and really cared for me. 6, 7, 8, 14, 20 The meeting grew rather quickly, so it came to be men and women. 5, 6, 7, 12, 13, 17, 19 There were several women in this meeting. 6, 12, 13 It never got big, twelve or fourteen people maybe. 13, 16 But there was a police officer, a real-estate agent, and a teacher. 7, 11, 15, 17, 18 A couple of docs started showing up, a nurse was there. 6, 7, 9, 15 There was nobody my age. 15 Nobody even close. 6, 13 So, I was going to AA, staying sober, working in the lab, and then trying to figure out what to do with myself. 5, 7, 14 I was living with Linda by this time. 6, 7, 16, 19 I learned how to fly-fish with a guy who worked in a different lab. 5, 6, 7, 12, 18 I always wanted to fly-fish for some reason. 7, 10, 14, 17 I was doing that a lot in the spring and summer, because I could. 17 I did it by myself because I had no other friends my age, really. 6, 7, 8, 13, 15 There were two other guys, one worked in the lab and one worked with the animals in the kennels and stuff that were close to my age. 6, 8, 12, 13, 15 One was about my age and the other was a little bit older. 15, 16, 20 So, they kind of became friends, but beyond that, I was mostly by myself and with Linda, trying to stay sober, going fishing or whatever. 5, 7, 13, 14, 17 And the meeting grew and because I was so young, there was a lot of parenting in addition to everything else that goes on in AA. 6, 7, 8, 19 MS: Yeah, just because... because, I was a kid. 15 AS: Group parenting. 7 It was great. 7, 8 I know in a lot of treatment now, it is important to separate adolescents from adults, but there's something to it. 7, 13, 17, 18 I really got a lot out of it. 6, 7, 8 So, I am going weekly and I am going on six months. 11, 16 I am feeling better than I have in my life. 7, 8, 13, 17, 18 My job is great. 7, 8 I am just having a ball at work, in a lot of ways.  I am getting close to a couple of these fellows and I really enjoy my work and I really got it down. 6, 7, 8, 13, 15, 20 I am able to learn some stuff too. 5, 18 One thing that Dr. Donald did, two things: 5, 19 At the end of an experiment, after animal surgery, you know it is just a mess. 17 So, my job is to clean it all up, right? 8, 14, 15, 16 And wash all of the instruments and prepare for the next day, for the next surgery. 7, 16, 19 But, if he did the experiment or if it was in his lab, he stayed and did all of that with me or with the other technician. 14, 16 If he stayed, the fellows stayed. 14, 16 So, it was this whole group of people gets done really quick and everybody goes to their offices except us and we stay in the lab to go do other things, because there is a lot to do. 5, 6, 7, 8, 14, 18, 19, 20 And when he didn't stay, the fellows all disappeared too. 7, 14 There were no rules about this of any kind, but it was absolute. 13 If he wasn't there, they didn't stay. 14 He was remarkable that way. 7, 18 And then we had a Monday morning lab meeting, every Monday morning. 6, 9, 19 And they would present their research and they would present their speeches they were about to give at conferences. 7, 11, 12 They would just talk, have these remarkable discussions about physiology and about what they were doing and ideas. 5, 6, 7, 18 What else we can do? 8 How can we solve this problem? 7 For me, it was just fantastic. 8 It was just fascinating.  In one of the early meetings that I attended, Dr. Donald presented a talk he was about to give at a major medical conference. 6, 7, 11, 12 It was something about cardiac physiology. 14 So, he presents the whole thing and usually when they presented, then everyone there, the six or seven people in the room, would start asking questions and commenting about the topic. 6, 7, 9, 15, 19 He immediately stopped and then said, ""Marvin, what did you get out of my talk?"" 6, 12, 13, 14, 15, 20 And I'm like, ""What?"" 9, 14 I'm still... 7 I have no self-confidence, I am really shy. 5, 6, 7, 8 I don't want to answer this question. 14, 15 But I do, I tell him what I got out of the talk, you know? 6, 13, 17 I am wondering, why would he ask me?  In the process of asking me, he engaged me. 15 You know? 17 I am a part of this team, which was amazing. 5, 8 I felt that, too. 6 And after I said my answer, he said, ""That's good, I'm glad because I am going to be talking to a group of physicians that are not physiologists and I gotta be sure that I can explain it in a way that they will understand. 6, 7, 13, 14, 18, 19 [laughter] 9 And I'm like, ""Wow. 9, 14 This is incredible."" 7 I was valued in a way that I didn't expect.  It was just an amazing experience. 15 So, I am being influenced by science in the lab, but also by people and caring. 14 And in AA I am being influenced by the Twelve Steps and love and spirituality, I think. 17 My life grows in all of those spheres. 7, 8 I am six months in and, like I said, I am feeling better than I ever have in my life. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 17, 18 I miss a Sunday morning. 9, 19 I just don't go.  I didn't consciously decide not to go, I don't even know why I didn't go. 17 I was just feeling so good I didn't go, thinking that I didn't really have to. 6, 7, 8, 13, 17, 18, 19 Sunday, I miss. 19 Monday, I open the cabinet, grab some cocaine and walk to the bathroom. 9, 10, 12, 19, 20 And it wasn't even on my mind. 6 There was no deliberate plan of any kind.  What I didn't recognize in that moment, is that those three guys at the first meeting, had died in that six-month period. 6, 7, 8, 15, 16, 17 They were like these angels. 9, 14 They just disappeared. 7 They died. 17 And I didn't even think of it, it didn't even occur to me that this was an issue or a problem for me. 7 I was so self-focused, so self.... 5, 9 I didn't go to funerals, I didn't even think of them, I didn't do anything because I didn't think it bothered me a bit. 7, 20 AS: But you knew that they had died? 6, 12, 17 And There I was using. 10 I didn't think that had anything to do with it.  It took me years to figure out... which is weird to say that. 7, 14, 16 AS: No, I think that is perfectly normal. 18 MS: [laughter] 9 Yeah, maybe that has something to do with it. 16 So, I had been meaning to ask this guy John to be my sponsor. 6, 13 And the reason I hadn't is because I hadn't done anything besides just show up at the meeting. 6, 7, 9, 10, 17 I didn't read about it, I didn't socialize with anyone, I didn't do any of the steps. 7, 12, 16, 18 AS: Was John one of the three?  MS: No, luckily.  John was like thirty-five, I guess. 19 He had five years sober and I always liked what he said. 9, 10, 13, 14, 16 I just liked listening to him. 9, 14 He kind of talked from a similar spiritual perspective that I thought of. 6, 10, 13 And so, I did the cocaine and I walked back into the lab and... this is the worst day of my life. 7, 8, 10, 11, 17, 19, 20 Six-months and I am no longer sober, and to me, I tried treatment and that didn't work, my own efforts got me two weeks, and AA got me six. 7, 11, 13, 16, 18, 20 That doesn't work either.  And they didn't tell me anything else that I could do. 8, 13 There is nothing else that works. 8 There is nothing else. 8 I don't know of anything else. 8, 17 I was never exposed to anything else. 8, 13 I think that I am hopeless. 13 I did as much as cocaine as I possibly could, more than any other day in my life. 7, 8, 19 I didn't even notice it because the pain was so bad of losing that, of what I had.  So, I call John from the lab and he worked just a few blocks away in downtown Rochester. 12, 14, 17, 20 I didn't know that, but he said that he was just three blocks away from me. 13, 14, 17, 20 He said, ""Come on over to my office."" 13, 14, 18 I lied and said, ""I can't, I have to stay and work until 5. 13, 14 So, I am doing as much cocaine as I can and this doesn't work. 10 The pain doesn't go away. 20 So, I go to his office at five o'clock. 18 He has to coach his son's pee-wee football team out in Biren, so he asked me to follow him. 5, 7, 17 So, we talked just really briefly and I just sit on the sideline and watch him coach football. 6, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15 Then we go to his house. 9, 11 I tell him what I just told you. 13, 16 I went to treatment, that didn't work. 7, 13, 18 AA doesn't work either.  And thank god, John says, ""You know Marv, AA works fine, you just haven't started."" 6, 8, 9, 14, 15, 17 And he said, ""You come to the meetings, but you're not working the steps, you're not reading the books, you're not talking to anybody, you're not sharing yourself with anybody. 6, 7, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17 You need to start doing that. 6 AA works fine. 8, 14 I'm proof.""  So, I said, ""Okay."" 13, 14 And I did exactly what he said. 13, 14 I mean, when I say exactly, he gave me this worksheet. 8, 14, 18 He went to Hazelden, too.  Which was also partially why I was attracted to him as a sponsor. 8, 13 This sheet was a ten-step inventory sheet. 16 So, it had thirty-one days across the top and all of these columns and rows that had on one side, a list of liabilities, and the other side, a list of assets. 9, 18, 19 The liabilities were like laziness, dishonesty.... they were listed there, like twenty or twenty-five adjectives. 6, 12 And then the assets were their opposites, basically. 7, 14, 17 He said, ""Fill this out every night."" in addition to everything else that he told me to do. 8, 13, 14, 16, 19 And I filled it out every night for five years, because I was so scared that I would relapse. 7, 14, 16, 19, 20 And then it got so wrote I had to change it around. 5, 18 But, early on, in those first months, I had a black and white description of my behavior to look at. 6, 11, 15, 16, 19 I was putting a ""X"" by dishonesty every single day, day in and day out. 6, 7, 12, 19 And lazy, and other things. 5, 19 I could see it. 5 I didn't have a sense of my own behavior and that gave it to me. 9, 18 AS: What were you being dishonest about every day? 6, 12, 19 I just couldn't be honest. 6, 12 I was so dishonest for so long that it was almost a ritual. 6, 7, 12, 15 Most of the time it didn't even make sense to be dishonest anymore, but I did. 6, 7, 9, 12, 16, 18, 19 So, John, he kept telling me, ""You know Marv, this is an honesty program."" 6, 8, 12, 13, 17 And that's all he would say. 14 It wasn't done in a confrontative way, it was just, ""Marv, this is an honesty program."" 6, 8, 12 And I would think, ""Well, why would you tell me that?"" 13 [laughter] 9 And he kept doing it.  And finally, I realized, because I am looking this end, hearing this question, that I am always dishonest. 6, 7, 10, 12, 14, 15 It's time to do something about it. 7, 16, 19 He was an ideal person for me. 5, 10, 17 He never confronted me. 13 I would tell him something going on in my life, like I'm having trouble with my girlfriend Linda, or whatever. 7, 8, 12, 13 And he would just tell me some story from his life. 7, 8, 13 It would always have some connection to what I was talking about. 6, 10, 18 But he wasn't analytical.  You hear that a lot of people in AA are always just really, ""Go work Step Two."" 6, 7, 8, 10, 14 It was never like that with John, it was just like, ""Well, this is what I did."" 9, 13, 14 [laughter] 9 AS: That is really great. 6, 7, 8 MS: And I think for an adolescent, if he would have been telling me what to do, I don't know what I would have done. 13, 17 He had kids just a little younger than me. 6, 15, 16, 20 He had a daughter that was maybe two years younger than me-- the oldest. 5, 6, 16 And then maybe two sons after her. 16, 17 I don't know what he was like at home really, but I wasn't that much different that his own kids. 6, 7, 8, 15, 17, 18, 19 AS: How long did you stay with him? 7, 14 MS: I don't even remember. 7, 13, 15 A long time. 7, 16, 19 AS: So, you stayed in Rochester? 14, 16 What did you end up doing?  MS: So, I stayed in the lab and then these docs kept asking me what I was going to do with my life, suggesting that I go to school. 7, 8, 11, 14, 16 Especially the fellows would talk like that with me. 6 I got this envelope in the inner-clinic mail, you know? 17 Those yellow envelopes.  It was addressed to Dr. Marvin Seppala. 7, 9 I still have it actually. 7, 18 Someone just made a mistake and put that on there. 13, 19, 20 And I had already been thinking that I liked what these guys do, and so I started thinking that I wanted to be a doctor like them. 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 15, 18, 20 So, I go to John one day and I tell him, ""You know, John. 13, 17, 19 I gotta go to college because I want to be a doctor."" 14, 20 And this is within my first year of recovery. 7, 8, 16 Most recommendations are don't do anything big in your first year. 7, 16 But I'm not paying attention to that, I really think that I should go to college. 6, 7, 8, 18 I've wanted to go to college in some points in my life but I didn't think it was possible. 7, 8, 10, 14 During my use I had just given up on it. 9, 11 It was not going to happen. 5 Now, it was like, maybe I could go to college. 9, 14, 16 And if John were to have doubted me in any way though, or doubted my ability to do it, I would have just crumbled.  And he knew me as a high school drop-out. 6, 11, 12 High school drop-out, works at Mayo, comes to AA, that's it. 8, 11, 17 So, I don't know what he was thinking when I say that I decide that I want to be a doctor. 14, 17, 20 But he said, ""You know Marv, if it is God's will, it will happen."" 5, 13, 14, 17 That's how he answered me. 7 Those are his exact words.  And I thought, wow, I guess that it is true. 10, 14, 19 If it is God's will, it will happen. 5 So, I just hung on to it.  I started looking into schools and trying to figure out where I wanted to and how I was going to do it. 6, 7, 11, 14, 15 My parents, I didn't even ask for money. 7, 12 I hadn't even seen them. 5, 13 I had talked to my dad that one time and that was it. 6, 7, 13, 16, 19 And I assumed they wouldn't help because they said they wouldn't help. 13, 14, 18 And my younger brother was off at college at the University of Minnesota and we didn't really have a lot of money, so I kind of thought that there was no use even going down that path. 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 16 I hadn't had any contact with them.  I assumed they would stick with what they said. 13, 14 So, my kids are in their thirties now, and they both applied to multiple schools, right? 8, 11, 14, 15, 17 Like eight schools or something. 11 And I decided in the end... 8 I talked to one of the fellows a little bit about applying to college, but I didn't really talk much about it. 6, 7, 8, 12, 13, 20 I just decided that I was just going to do it on my own for some reason. 7, 8, 10, 17 Just stupidly, you know? 17 So, I apply to one school. 11 I apply to St. Olaf and I decide if I get in, I get in and if I don't, I don't. 20 And I got in.  So, on my one-year anniversary from that six-month relapse, I walk into my first classes. 6, 7, 12, 16 The neat thing is that I was in this dorm with all of these guys and they are all coming to colle