"11","Englund_Gloria","Andrew Tuttle Narrator Amy Sullivan Interviewer February 16, 2017 Wettingen, Switzerland Andrew Tuttle -AT Amy Sullivan -AS AS: We are in Baden? 7 AT: We’re in Wettingen. 7 AS: Wettingen.  AT: Next to Baden.  AS: Today is February 16, 2017. 19 This is Amy Sullivan.  I’m with Dr. Andrew Tuttle. 7 Would you just say your name? 11, 14 AT: My name is Andrew Tuttle. 7, 11 I explicitly give Ms. Amy Sullivan permission to record what I’m saying. 7, 11, 14 AS: Thank you.  I wonder if this is picking you up. 5 I might put it on top of this, is that okay? 14, 19 AT: Sure. 7 AS: What I was telling you earlier is I like to start with your childhood, where you grew up, your family, some of your childhood experiences. 6, 7, 9, 13, 15, 19 How you ended up here, where you were born, stuff like that. 5 AT: Do you want me to just go? 14 Okay.  I was born in Minneapolis in 1952. 5 I was the only child of my parents then. 7, 9, 12 We lived on Oliver Avenue in Kenwood in Minneapolis. 11, 16 It was a nice, modest house there. 9, 11, 14 My father worked in the M.A. 12 Gedney pickle packaging company. 5, 13 He later becomes the CEO. 5, 16, 17, 18 My mother then was not employed. 10 She was a mother and a housewife as much as I remember. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15 She had been to college and was a very well educated person. 8, 10, 17 She’d gone to college.  She majored in English literature. 7 She was very well read and well spoken. 7, 8 AS: Where did your folks meet? 17 AT: I don’t know. 17 I think it was a family thing. 7, 19 The parents on my mother side belonged to a certain social circle that knew each other. 6, 7, 9, 10, 12, 18 As well as my grandparents went to places like Minikahda Club. 7, 8, 12, 20 Somehow a connection occurred there. 7, 18 My knowledge of exactly how that occurred is kind of sketchy. 7, 17 Now my father has died. 17 Anyways, the way I remember those first years is rather difficult. 7, 10, 13, 15, 16 I have nice memories. 14 My father and my mother and being tickled and stuff like that. 10 But I also remember them fighting viciously, verbally. 7, 13, 15 AS: Even as a young kid? 6, 15 AT: As a very young kid. 6, 15 I think this was at a stage where I hadn’t completely stopped wearing diapers, two or three or something like that. 14, 15 Definitely before kindergarten.  I have scenes in my head of standing at the top of the stairs just watching my parents just rip each other’s throat out. 7, 12, 15, 17 AS: Were they physically abusive? 14, 17 It was verbally.  I was a difficult child. 9, 10 Retrospectively  I most certainly had ADHD. 14 I was unmanageable. 15, 18 My parents constantly got calls from kindergarten. 7, 12, 14, 17 Later on I spent most of the time in the principal’s office in grade school. 7, 11, 16, 18, 19 I was disruptive.  Give me a hammer  I’ll attack the front walkway of our house and see how easy it is to break concrete apart. 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 Bicycles, or a car I can let the air out of the tires. 7, 14 I was a troublemaker. 18 I got into fights and was just hyperactive. 13 I was all over the place. 8 AS: Were you still watching your parents fight at this point? 7, 10, 12, 13, 15 AT: That’s not that central.  More central is the way that I met disapproval with adults. 12 Actually kids of my own age who knew that they could get me to do stuff. 6, 12, 15, 20 Then they’d go tell on me. 13 AS: You were that kid. 15 AT: It was kind of a formative experience because I felt myself being that troublemaker and that guy who could never do something right. 6, 8, 13, 14, 15, 18 I think fortunately I was intelligent and could pick things up quickly. 5, 13, 19 I remember my dad once, this must have been before I was six and half or seven years old because that’s when we moved to California, he was just absolutely beside himself because I’d taken some tools and taken his bicycle apart. 7, 8, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 20 That’s kind of a memory I can chuckle about now but at the time it was, “I’m just trying out these tools. 7, 16, 17, 19 Why are you mad at me?”  We moved to California before I was seven or after seven. 11, 14 I had just started first grade in Minneapolis and we moved to California and I continued first grade there. 6, 11, 14, 15, 16, 19 We lived in Berkeley where my mother worked. 10, 11, 12, 16 This was after my parents got divorced. 7, 12 AS: When did they get divorced? 20 AT: They got divorced in Minneapolis.  Just after they got divorced my mother moved with me to California where her parents had moved to previously. 7, 10, 11, 12, 14 AS: Your father didn’t move to California? 14 AT: No, this was just my mother. 10 I moved with her to California. 11, 14 First we stayed with my grandparents there, my aunt and uncle who were still adolescents at that time. 7, 12, 14, 16, 19 A very big age difference between my mother and her sister and her much, much younger brother who was four years older than me. 6, 7, 10, 15, 16 He wasn’t even in his teens when we moved there. 11, 14 He was still a kid. 7, 15 We quickly moved to Berkeley where we had an apartment. 5, 8, 11, 14 My mother worked in the Lawrence Radiation Laboratory up on the hills of Berkeley as a librarian. 7, 10, 12 That’s where she met my later step-father who was working there as a nuclear physicist. 5, 12, 16 They had a relationship, got married, and in 1962 we moved to Switzerland which was an adventure in itself. 7, 11, 12, 14, 15, 16 We came by boat from San Francisco. 13, 17 A steamer that went through the Panama Canal and across the Atlantic Ocean and across France with a steam engine. 5 AS: Was he Swiss?  AT: No he was German, from Munich.  AS: Is your mom American? 17 AT: Yes.  So is my dad.  My mom had her roots in Ireland and Scotland. 7, 17 My dad’s ancestors come from Southern England. 17 Anyway, we got to Switzerland and I was nine years old. 16 I have a late birthday in December. 5, 19 I’m actually a year younger than the year I’m living in. 6, 16, 18 I became ten in that year but we moved here in Spring. 11, 13, 14, 16, 17 We very quickly moved to a very small farm village in Switzerland where I was in school with the only Swiss students, pupils. 5, 9, 11, 12, 14, 15, 19 It was still an adventure because here I’d come from urban Berkeley to this tiny Swiss village where most of the kids who came to school were farm kids. 7, 9, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19 After school we could wander over to the farm. 9, 11, 19 We could watch their parents milking the cows and help them gather cut grass from the fields to feed the cows with. 7, 12, 14, 15, 18, 20 I just thought it was really cool. 6, 7, 8, 10 Within a three minute walk you could be in the woods and the forest. 7, 14 If you walked you would come to a little lake and you could go swimming there and jump off the limbs of trees into the water. 7, 17, 20 It was cool.  My stepfather was a passionate mountaineer. 16, 17 I have to credit him with introducing me to the Alps. 7 We did a lot of Alpine tours and not actual climbing but long, long several day tours up high over glaciers and staying in Alpine cabins. 5, 7, 11, 13, 14, 19 That’s where I gained my own passion. 17 Later on I became a rock climber and did a lot of rock climbing and mountain climbing and stuff like that. 13, 17 I still love going up in the mountains and taking long hikes. 7, 17 He was also a difficult guy and my mother was a difficult person. 6, 10, 17 She was the central person for me throughout my childhood, right up to my early twenties, I was very focused on her and very emotionally. 6, 8, 9, 10, 14, 17, 19 She was the person I’d lived with all my life. 7, 8, 10, 11, 16, 17 Only now with a certain temporal distance and knowing what I know about psychology and dealing with life myself, I know that she was a very, very emotionally difficult person. 5, 7, 8, 10, 17 One that could get somebody to fight with her. 13, 20 With my stepfather it became physically violent. 13, 14, 16, 17 I witnessed her being beat up a lot.  He was a brilliant scientist, well liked. 8, 9, 14 AS: Did he work at the technical place? 8 AT: He worked in conjunction with the Swiss Institute of Technology. 12 He was building what today is known as the Pau Scherrer Institute. 5, 7, 12, 17, 19 Then it was the Swiss Institute for Nuclear Research.  A short way from here they constructed a cyclotron and now they have a bevatron and a synchrotron. 17 It’s a big nuclear research facility that he oversaw the development and construction of. 6, 7, 12 He was a prominent physicist in his field then. 20 He also drank pretty heavily. 5, 7, 14, 18 They fought viciously almost every night. 15, 19 Occasionally it would escalate to physical. 5 AS: By this time, you’re ten? 7, 16, 19 Eleven?  Was this happening when you had moved here or was it before? 5, 7, 11, 14 AT: They were verbally fighting before. 13 Right from the outset they were verbally fighting. 13 I did not enjoy all of the stress. 7 In my mid-teens I started detaching myself from them. 6, 15 AS: They stayed together? 11, 14, 16, 20 AT: Yes, she had three more children by him. 7, 9 Three half-sisters of mine. 15, 16 The middle one, the second one suffers from Downs Syndrome. 12, 14, 16 She lives in a supervised living situation here in Wettingen. 6, 7, 11 My oldest sister, Christa, she lives not far from here. 9, 11, 16 She’s very much like my mother. 10 She’s a difficult person. 10, 17 She’s one who’s kind of emotionally unstable and will very quickly take offense at something you say that she interprets in a certain way. 5, 7, 14, 18, 20 She’ll start attacking you back. 6, 11, 17, 19 Most of her boyfriend relationships have been characterized by a lot of fighting. 7, 13, 15, 16 That’s kind of how I see my mother now from this point in life. 5, 7, 8, 10, 17 She was a difficult person. 10, 17 If my stepfather beat her she sure knew how to get him to beat her. 6, 7, 12, 16, 20 Nothing justifies each other but it’s kind of something that you can’t just see unidirectionally. 5, 7 I don’t think he really was that kind of person. 6, 7, 8, 10, 17 He never touched me. 13 He was always very correct, very fair. 7, 10 That made it difficult for me to relate with him. 5, 7, 10, 13 I saw him beating up my mother but my relationship was sort of okay. 6, 7, 8, 10, 14, 15 What am I supposed to feel or think? 13, 14, 18 It was very confusing. 10 He was actually a good guy but he really destroyed a lot of stuff. 6, 7, 8, 18, 19 My attention deficit disorder sort of abated. 5, 6, 8 I was able to adapt to the Swiss school system. 11, 18 My antics were a bit, for a while, kind of legitimized because I was a foreigner who didn’t know how to behave. 7, 17, 19, 20 I very quickly learned the language and thought living here was just so much great fun. 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 15 School was kind of cool too.  It was this Little House on the Prairie type school with three grades in one room. 9, 11, 19 The teacher was really good. 6, 7, 8, 19 He was the kind of person who had a very firm authority but in a way that was gentle. 10, 17 Everybody just sort of naturally did what he wanted. 8, 14 AS: Even you?  AT: Yes.  AS: Interesting. 7 AT: In those times corporal punishment by teachers was not forbidden here. 7, 16, 19 I got him once to the point where he took me out of the classroom, not in front of the other pupils, and slapped me. 6, 9, 10, 12 That’s really not the kind of teacher that he was. 6, 7, 8 The teacher upstairs, it was known that he kept a hazel switch in the corner which he liberally used on students. 9, 11, 12, 17 That was the 60s.  That was when we lived in the Zurich region. 7, 11, 16 A few years after I had completed grade school we moved into Wettingen, here, which is a different canton and has a different school system. 7, 11, 14, 16, 18, 19 I was able to from the so-called second fahrschule, the sort of midlevel middle school in Zurich which actually is a little bit higher than the secondary school here, at that time was at least, and moved into the mit