t in socially? 18 AT: I didn’t fit in socially. 18 None of the students lived nearby where I was living anyways. 6, 11, 12, 16 Everyone was driven there or drove there themselves from various parts. 8, 14 Most of them were from Edina or something like that.  We were living in Kenwood. 6 I barely had any social contacts. 7, 12, 18 AS: And you got plopped down when those kids had been together for years. 11, 15, 16, 20 AT: Yes.  I was able to speak English as a local. 18 Nobody realized that I had a reason to have a hard time adjusting or anything like that. 6, 7, 10, 16, 17, 19 It was expected that I was able to do all this stuff which I was confused by and alienated by. 9, 18 After eight months I should have talked with my father about it but was somehow unable to at that age and stage. 6, 11, 13, 15, 17, 18 I ran away. 20 I was able to scrounge up the money to get a Greyhound bus to Chicago. 7, 12, 16, 18, 20 In Chicago I hitchhiked out to Deerport and presented a sob story to the Swiss people there. 7, 13, 16, 19 That I’d been stranded in America.  They put me on a plane. 19 They could confirm that I actually had parents there. 7, 12, 18 They put me on a plane back to Switzerland. 11, 17, 19 AS: Who paid for the ticket? 8 AT: My mother and stepfather eventually. 10, 16 AS: You didn’t even say goodbye to your father? 14 AT: I did later. 5, 16 AS: Were you getting along with him? 7, 15, 20 AT: Yes, I was but I just felt so lost and misunderstood. 6 AS: He had other children? 7, 9 AT: I actually felt that this was my personal failure. 6, 7, 10, 17, 18 I had asked to stay with him and now I was failing him and not fulfilling his expectations or anything like that. 14, 17 It felt awful. 6, 7 AS: Had he remarried? 7, 12, 16 AT: Yes, and already had Karl, my brother, and Jeff. 6, 7, 16, 18 John  I’m not sure. 7 No I don’t think he was born yet. 5, 15 Back in Switzerland I dived into the 1970s psychedelic hippie stuff.  I dove.  I consumed a lot of cannabis and LSD and stuff like that.  The whole psychedelic thing. 19 I don’t think I ever overdid it. 13 Were you living at home then? 6, 17, 19 AT: I was living at home which I did for another year and a half. 6, 16, 17, 19 When I was nineteen a buddy and I were able to rent an old dilapidated farm house a short way from here that had cold water and an outhouse out back for like a hundred buck a month. 7, 9, 11, 16, 17, 18, 19 That was affordable. 18 I said, “Bye Mom” and just moved out. 11, 13, 14 I moved together with him and completed my school from there. 11, 14, 16, 20 I took a year off and worked on construction. 12, 16 I travelled some, rode my motorcycle a lot.  I had a big old beautiful 1951 BMW. 16 I rode all over Europe.  Around Italy and Sardinia and places like that. 8, 20 I always have had kind of a tendency to travel on my own. 10 I grew up as a single kid essentially even though I have a lot of half-brothers and half-sisters. 7, 15, 16, 19 I never felt like I was really brothers and sisters with them. 6, 7, 8, 13, 15, 16 They were age wise so far apart. 8, 9, 15 I was the only link between my biological father and my biological mother. 10 I almost kind of saw myself as a single kid. 6, 7, 15 I knew how to be alone. 6, 12 Travelling alone, I have travelled with other people before. 12 If nobody is available wanting to do the same thing I just go by myself. 10, 14, 18, 19 You always meet people along the way. 10 AS: Is that when you went to Bangkok?  AT: When did I go to Bangkok?  No, I’d already started medical school. 6, 7, 11, 15, 18 I did a lot of travelling.  A year after I completed the local high school, the gymnasium, I went to medical school together with the guy I was living with, Chris. 6, 11, 16, 20 He later became an anesthesiologist. 5, 13, 16, 17 It was a great time. 7, 8, 16, 19 Medical school was fun. 11 I extended it by a year because I didn’t want to get stressed out in having to complete it in just six years. 7, 14, 16, 20 I took a lot of time off in between to travel. 7, 16, 19 That is the time I went to Southeast Asia. 7, 16, 19 Once I spent three months hitchhiking through the United States. 7, 11, 19 I did that twice and then went down to Central America and to Mexico and stuff like that. 16 I really enjoyed travelling. 6, 7, 8 It was so cool to meet all these different people along the way. 7, 18 People would be interested in where you’re from and I’d get invited to stuff. 7 It was really, really cool. 6, 7, 8 In a nutshell that’s kind of how things went. 5, 14, 19 I graduated from medical school in 1980. 11 The year that I became twenty-eight. 13, 16, 17 My mother died when I was twenty-three. 10, 17 She had breast cancer. 7 Just after I graduated from medical school my stepfather died from lung cancer. 11, 16, 17 He was a heavy smoker.  AS: You had younger sisters. 6, 15, 16 Were they on their own already? 6, 7, 18 AT: No. After the death of my mother my stepfather remarried with the nanny that had looked after my half-sister while my mother was still in the hospital before she died. 7, 8, 10, 12, 13, 16, 17 A weird thing. 19 She had two further children by him, a boy and a girl. 7, 9, 12 She was stuck with five children after he died. 7, 9, 17 I wasn’t part of that though. 8 AS: That was not your circus.  Can you talk about how you got into addiction medicine? 6, 8, 15 Not addiction medicine, psychiatry. 8, 15 AT: I stumbled into it.  I’ve always been interested, even in medical school I’d pick up some kind of weird book on psychology or some kind of life view approach thing or something. 5, 7, 8, 10, 11, 19 Primal scream therapy or whatever. 7, 18 I didn’t really get in touch with psychiatry. 6, 7, 8, 20 I never saw myself as a psychiatrist. 6, 8, 13 I thought it was interesting but I never saw myself as such because I thought I was too deranged and disturbed myself. 6, 7, 9, 10, 13 These guys who were into psychiatry, we had all of these fantastic ways of speaking and explaining stuff. 6, 8, 15 I’d never be able to do that. 13, 18 AS: Your classmates? 6, 12 AT: Classmates or older people. 15, 16 People would say something analytical and I’d be like, “Wow, I never would have thought of that. 9, 10, 13, 14 How do they know that?” 17 After graduating from medical school I was kind of disenchanted with medicine all together. 8, 11, 16, 20 It’d been seven years. 16 The final exams were a very lengthy thing. 19 These were eighteen or twenty individual exams drawn out over a half a year. 16 Specialty, oral, written, stuff like that.  I was kind of fed up with it.  After graduating I decided I’d do something else for a while. 8 I worked at the post office. 12, 18 I worked at a refrigerator repair place, which was fun. 7, 8, 12 I had my own little van with refrigerator repair parts. 7, 8, 20 I’d go to people’s house. 9, 11 AS: Someone trained you to do that?  AT: They did at the factory.  They showed me how all the refrigerators worked and how to diagnose what’s wrong with them. 6, 7, 9, 12 AS: You do pick things up quickly. 5, 19 AT: For a couple months I also worked at a truck mechanics place. 7, 8, 11, 12 It was a way to earn money. 7, 12 That was the year I got enough money together not only to pay for my motorcycle but I wanted to do an extensive backpacking trip to the Caribbean. 7, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20 I was kind of looking for somebody to take of my apartment and my cats while I was gone. 6, 8, 12, 20 That was when I met Susan. 12 AS: Did she take care of the cats or did she go on the trip? 7, 14, 20 We very quickly became enamored. 5, 7, 13, 17 She has just come over here and was glad to have a place to stay. 8, 14, 17 I was going to be gone for a couple months. 7, 11 She took care of my apartment and fed my cats. 7, 8, 14, 20 I went to the Caribbean where I started missing her a lot. 6, 15 Two and a half weeks into the trip in Antigua I met a veterinarian from the United States who was there for some government project to look at the cows or something. 12, 16 We got drunk together and he had a motorcycle and wasn’t able to start it. 6, 8, 11, 16, 18, 20 I could see that it was flooded. 5 I kicked the carburetor and adjusted it and started it for him. 6, 7, 11, 14, 15 “Okay.  I’m going over to the other bar there. 12 You want to come along?” 7, 14, 15, 17 Along the way we wiped out and spilled.  He had some lacerations, I just had some contusions.  Nothing serious happened. 5 It kind of was a jolt.  Here I was in what they call the hospital in Antigua and he was getting sewed up and I was kind of sitting there really drunk. 6, 7, 8, 11, 14, 17, 18 Shortly thereafter 7 I decided this is not the way I envisioned this trip. 8, 12 So I booked a flight to Minneapolis, spent a week with my parents and almost every day on the phone with Susan. 7, 12, 14, 15, 16, 19 Then a flight back to Switzerland. 11, 17, 19 Six months later we got married. 5, 11, 12, 16 After I returned to Switzerland, that was 1981, I was able to secure a job at the medical examiner’s in Zurich where I had worked as a student previously for a couple of months and where I first got into contact with death by intravenous drug abuse. 7, 9, 10, 11, 12, 16, 18 I started writing my doctoral dissertation on that which I completed after I started working there in 1982. 6, 15, 20 In 1980, 1981 was the year I took off and 1982 we got married. 12, 16 That’s where I got really involved in addiction. 6, 7, 8, 15 I started getting really interested especially in opiate dependency. 6, 7, 8, 15, 20 After a year and a half of that I went and I was kind of looking for jobs that had a manageable workload where I didn’t have to stay up a lot at night. 6, 14, 15, 16, 18, 19 I just couldn’t handle that very well. 8, 13 I went to work for about a year and a half at an orthopedic rehabilitation clinic. 7, 13, 16 I had people who came there sort of electively. 8, 13, 17 You had to manage their rehabilitation and stuff. 7, 15 You’d go home at night even if you had on-call duty you could just sleep there. 14, 17, 19 It was kind of a cushy job, well paid. 8 Residents generally got well paid here in Switzerland. 8, 9 A common starting salary after graduating as a resident would be sixty or seventy thousand dollars a year. 5, 6, 7, 9, 16, 18 My original wish was I wanted to be a general practitioner. 12, 14 I applied for a residency and got one in Hennepin County Medical Center. 7, 9 We moved over there thinking I was going to do a complete residency in family medicine, family practice. 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 14, 19 That first year I was there was just horrible. 16 I had to work one hundred and ten, one hundred and twenty hours a week, seven days a week. 16, 18, 19 Every third or fourth night was just working through and continue working the next day. 16, 19, 20 I got really depressed. 6, 7, 8 It was almost a reenactment of when I was sixteen and had gone to visit my father. 7, 15 It was like after about eight or nine months I just threw in the towel and said, “Screw it.” 7, 11, 13, 14 We packed up our stuff and moved back to Switzerland. 11, 13, 14, 17, 19 I felt horrible again because I felt like I’d disappointed my father. 6, 10 He was so glad that I’d come there. 17 It was kind of hard to overcome. 6, 17 I immediately got a position back at the rehab clinic where I had worked. 7, 11, 12, 17, 19 I just was trying to figure out what I wanted to do. 7, 14 I decided to get into psychiatry. 8, 20 I got a residency job at the state mental institution. 7, 9, 17 I immediately liked it. 9, 12, 14 I was immediately liked by patients and personnel alike. 9, 10, 12, 14, 15, 17 I remember that I always wondering, “Why don’t the other doctors get involved more with the patients?” 7, 10, 13, 15, 20 I was spending time in the wards, talking with people. 6, 7, 12, 16, 19 AT: Yes, and the other doctors would come by once or twice a week and make their rounds and otherwise just ask the nurses what was going on. 16, 17, 18, 20 I kind of got stuck there.  I thrived and was doing well, was being paid well. 8 I had manageable hours. 15, 18 Sometimes I’d have to be on call but it was exceptional. 7, 12, 14, 16, 17, 19 That was actually at a time when a law was passed in Switzerland that even medical residents were not allowed to work more than sixty-five hours a week. 7, 9, 11, 16, 17, 18, 19 AS: That was in the 80s.  AT: After America a sixty-hour week seemed like nothing. 5, 16 I did that and I worked in various university clinics. 7, 12 I spent a year in Basel and a couple years in the outpatient services here nearby. 7, 16 Then I opened my own practice in 1993. 6, 20 That’s how I got into psychiatry. 8 AS: What happened with the addiction medicine interest? 5, 7, 8, 15 AT: It was always kind of a special interest area of mine. 7, 10 I had lots of methadone patients when I opened my practice. 6, 15, 20 AT: Yes.  That was when methadone was still the substitution medicine. 7, 8 AS: When was the Needle Park?  AT: That started at the very end of the 80s and blossomed in the beginning of the 90s and was there for a few years. 6, 15, 16 After I opened my practice it was still a thing. 6, 7, 19, 20 I think in ‘94 or ‘95 it had already been cleaned. 6, 7, 15, 16, 18 It moved first from one place to the other. 8, 11, 14, 16 AS: From the park to the station.  AT: It moved from Platzspitz to the Letten which was even more horrific than at the first place. 8, 11, 14, 16 Then they clamped down on it and wiped it out.  Police all over the place in areas where it could reoccur, preventing scenes like that from re-sprouting. 7, 8 AS: Were they arresting people at that point? 7, 10 What they doing with people?  How can you arrest a thousand people in one day because they’re using heroin? 7, 10, 19 AS: There was never the criminal, the immediate… 13 AT: Of course there was a criminal element.  AS: To arrest people, was that mostly for dealers? 5, 7, 10, 14 AT: Of course, but how do you make the distinction? 18 Everybody who gets involved in heroin at some point becomes a dealer because they have to deal their own stuff. 10, 14, 17, 18, 20 Of course there are people who are more focused on distributing. 9 The Albanians had a reputation for doing that. 7, 19 It was often somebody connected with some group or criminal organization. 18 Somebody would buy it in a great quantity from somebody and then they’d distribute it in smaller quantities to somebody else and they’d distribute it to the individual people on the scene. 7, 8, 12, 20 Then they would redistribute it and so on. 7 Where do you make the line? 18 AS: Who to arrest? 7 AT: Where is the victim and where is the perpetrator? 19 Where’s the difference? 7 It’s almost a continuum. 15 Some people were arrested just because they were carrying something with them. 7, 14 They were seldom persecuted. 14 Some people were persecuted. 14 Some people  I’m not sure whether it was sensible to be persecuted. 7, 14 A friend of mine who was a dentist, he spent two years in a regional penitentiary because he was caught with cocaine and he was selling it. 7, 9, 13, 16, 19 He was a dentist.  He was making good money off of his profession. 6, 7, 12, 19 It’s not like he needed to become rich by selling cocaine. 9, 10, 14, 17, 18, 19 It was more something he was just involved in because he was consuming heavily himself.  They put him away. 19, 20 Other people I know died. 17 AS: During that time? 7, 16, 19 AT: Yes.  AS: Friends?  AT: People I knew. 6, 12 Fortunately, none of my closer friends. 6, 7, 12, 13 Maybe the dentist has died since. 17 I don’t think it’s drug related. 5, 7, 10 As Thilo Beck says, his lifestyle. 7, 8, 14, 17 Last time I saw him he was obese and looked pasty and unhealthy. 6, 7, 8, 13, 16, 19 AS: Do you remember what your dissertation was about? 7, 13, 15 What made it unique in the time that you wrote it? 7, 13, 16, 19 AT: The time that I started writing it heroin addiction was just starting to bloom. 5, 6, 7, 8, 15, 16, 19 The title of the dissertation was, “The Exceptional Deaths.”  A term for a medical examiner, somebody who doesn’t die of natural causes. 9, 11 A death that is unexplainable, unnatural, or extraordinary death. 18 Literal translation is extraordinary death.  Of intravenous drug abusers, a canonistic study of one hundred cases. 5, 9, 10, 12 Most of those hundred cases occurred in 1979 and 1980. 7, 12 It was like a flat curve and then it went up like that.  AS: Just like we’re starting to see. 5, 6, 7 During the 80s the heroin abuse climbed and climbed and climbed. 9, 10 Where previously a couple of people had died per year from it, it was dozens in small Switzerland. 7, 12, 16, 17 Or over one hundred per year. 16 Then at the end of the 80s like Beck said, the most intense drug scenes in the world happened in the middle of Zurich. 5, 10, 12, 13, 14 People pouring in from Germany, from France just to come there to get drugs. 10, 17, 18, 20 AS: Do you know where the heroin was coming from? 7, 10, 17 AT: Mostly from Afghanistan I believe. 9 AS: Were they able to curb the… 18 AT: Some from Morocco probably also. 12, 13 AS: When the introduction of the methadone therapy happened, was there also a simultaneous bust of the heroin market? 5, 10, 12, 18 Do you know how that kind of worked out? 12, 17 Was there a police effort towards getting rid of it? 15, 17, 20 AT: Yes, there was.  AS: Did those things happen simultaneously? 5, 19 AT: Yes.  It very quickly became evident that it’s useless to pursue the users. 5, 9, 13, 17 You have to find out who the distributors are, the dealers. 9, 10, 14 The police efforts were concentrated on that. 17 A lot of people got caught up in the net but the focus was where is it coming from and how do we cut this off? 7, 14 AS: Were they or weren’t they working in conjunction with each other?  Was the impulse towards the care for the addicts, getting people off the street, did that happen separately or were they cooperating at all? 5, 7, 13, 14, 15, 20 AT: As I remember it, it was separately but there were attempts with communication and cooperation. 7, 13, 15 Politically at that time, it was so open and so visible and so in everybody’s faces. 7, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20 It could not be ignored. 7 It could not be denied.  It was part of our society. 8 Almost everybody knew a family whose kid had got caught up in that. 6, 7, 12, 15, 19 It was just devastating.  Society had to deal with it.  They came to this understanding; we can’t just deal with it by repressing it. 7, 13, 17 We have to also do prevention. 7 We have to do treatment. 7, 13, 18 The four pillars that we say, I can’t think of what they are exactly. 14 It’s a more differentiated approach and not just forbidding it. 7, 18 You can’t forbid something, prohibit something that so many people are doing anyways regardless of it being prohibited. 7, 18, 20 It’s not going to go away just by outlawing it. 16, 20 A more permissive attitude sort of came forth then. 5, 8, 13, 17 They started leaving this expectation that people who were on drugs were just going to stop using them and become abstinence and be detoxed and then be okay. 6, 10, 14, 15, 17, 18 It hardly ever works that way. 6, 8, 13 Occasionally somebody does and that’s good. 6, 19 Mostly not.  AS: You opened your own practice, how did patients who had opiate issues find you? 6, 7, 9, 15, 20 Are all psychiatrists prepared to deal with opiate addicts? 7, 8, 13, 15 I’m just trying to understand your medical system. 11 We would say you’re an addiction medicine doctor or you’re just a psychiatrist. 7, 8, 14, 15, 20 Those two in the U.S. don’t often overlap in private practice. 5, 6, 18 AT: I’d say generally psychiatrists don’t want to or need to treat people with this kind of addiction. 7, 8, 14, 15 Oftentimes because it’s viewed as something very strenuous you’re going to wind up with your bills not getting paid, stuff like that. 7, 8, 16, 19 The patients are going to be lying to you all the time. 7, 12, 15, 16, 19 This also stems from the attitude, “I’m the doctor. 20 I’m going to counsel you on what you need to do to overcome your problems.” 7, 17 Especially in addiction you can’t do that. 8, 15 You have to find out where that person is at that moment and take it from there. 9, 10, 15, 17, 20 You can’t superimpose this expectation of yours which doesn’t fit the frame of reference of the patient. 7, 20 You have to very carefully feel out the frame of reference of this person. 7, 10, 13, 14, 17, 18, 20 Including his substance abuse or her substance abuse and where they’re standing and why they have come to you. 7, 9, 17 What they actually want from you. 14, 18 Without saying, “This is what I want from you. 14 They’re coming to you with an expectation that you’re going to help them in a certain way. 7, 18 You have to find out what that is. 9 It might not be realistic but it usually is not realistic in a way that they are expecting me to do much more for them. 7 Ultimately them achieving much more than they are actually able to do at that moment. 15, 17, 18, 19 Oftentimes my first job is to just find out where they are, give them the feeling that they’re being listened to and understood, and then start toning down their expectations. 6, 7, 9, 11, 13, 16, 17, 18, 19 “Listen.  You can’t just stop taking that.  You can’t just detox and everything will be okay. 14 Let’s try methadone or Dolophine or oral morphine, the slow release type. 7 You have to be open to various options and approaches.” 20 Oftentimes you need to accept the fact that in the background they’re using other substances. 7, 9, 10, 11, 16, 17, 19 Each case is its own individual case.  Of course there are certain patterns that the addict does this and that. 15 It’s very personal. 10, 17 AS: Has your practice always been that way? 6, 10 Do you think that the time you spent working at the hospital, the state hospital where you spent more time with patients, do you feel like that influenced your attitude towards addiction and towards people who were struggling with addiction? 7, 8, 13, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 AT: I started to. 6, 15 It’s been a long road. 7 I’ve been in this business now for almost thirty years. 9, 12, 15, 16, 17 AS: Maybe you could talk about how it’s changed? 5, 6 AT: It has a lot to do with my own personal experience too. 10, 15, 17 A lot of personal stuff and realizing how vulnerable I am. 7, 10, 17, 18 This is not something that is just a bad life choice. 7, 8 This is something that can happen to you. 5 I mentioned in one of the letters that I had my own brush with morphine. 12 This is something that took me completely by surprise. 14 This was shortly before I opened my practice. 6, 20 My friend, the anesthesiologist, had just gotten some practice permit. 6, 7, 13 He said, “Let’s see what this whole thing is about this flash.” 5, 13, 14, 19 AS: Flash?  AT: The flash, the rush, when you inject an opiate.  He had morphine ampules and we shot intravenously ten milligrams. 20 It was at first, “This is kind of relaxing and nice.” 7, 14, 16 But actually a little bit too much because I kind of was woozy and drowsy. 18, 20 I tried it again but with only five milligrams, a very small amount comparatively. 12 That was, “Oh my God.”  All my troubles with attention deficit disorder, my problems with concentration, my problems with the strenuous—with keeping up a conversation with anybody and staying focused on the subject and not drifting away mentally and my ability to read and retain stuff was just better. 5, 6, 7, 9, 14, 17, 20 I went to twice a week. 16 It was helpful. 18 It was that point where I started feeling discouraged and craving. 6, 10, 13, 15, 17, 18 I got addicted. 15 I detoxed three or four times. 7, 16, 19 If you’re taking something you’ve just really got to stay away from it because then my disdain for being dependent on something like that and my willingness to compromise. 6, 7, 8, 14, 20 I’m clean but I’d still call myself an addict. 7, 14, 15, 16, 17 I have vast amounts of oral morphine in my practice because I have to distribute it. 6, 12 I never ever, ever keep injectable morphine in my practice. 6, 13, 17, 18 I know that it’s too tempting. 17 I could go buy it any time from the pharmacy. 7, 9, 16, 19, 20 Because you’re a doctor. 7, 20 It’s just I know I cannot fool myself into thinking, once it will be okay. 14, 17 They come in packs of ten and I won’t be able to not use up the entire pack of ten. 7, 9, 13, 17, 18 You can also buy them in boxes of one hundred ampules. 20 They have ten milligram and twenty milligram ampules.  It’s a really easy split. 6, 7, 8, 11 I just keep it at a distance. 17 AS: If someone needs that they can go somewhere else. 7, 8, 15 AT: This was a very, very profoundly humiliating experience. 11, 15 AT: I never thought that could happen to me. 5, 10, 13 It never did with any other substance. 9, 13 I can smoke a joint tomorrow and then not think about it for a year. 16 I like a glass of wine but I don’t crave it. 9, 14 I could easily go days or weeks without it. 16, 18, 19 I had cocaine, I didn’t like the effect because it made me all tight and nervous and crabby. 9, 13, 14 I talked a mile a minute but I didn’t like the way I was physically feeling when I was on it. 6, 9, 13, 14, 17, 18 I avoid it.  AS: How long did that last for you? 7 Did you take it like three or four times? 7, 16, 19, 20 AT: Altogether like ten years. 11, 16, 20 AS: Ten years? 16 How did that go over in your family life? 7, 8, 19 AT: Not well. 8 Susan started to notice. 6, 15 She could tell that I was using. 10, 13 Sometimes she thought I was using and wasn’t. 7, 10, 12, 16, 19 She was never sure. 7, 13 I lied about it or denied it or denied it when I actually wasn’t doing but she didn’t believe me. 9, 18 Stuff like that.  It was a difficult thing. 10, 19 Like Thilo Beck said, I’m a doctor. 13, 14, 20 I can buy the clean stuff and inject it cleanly. 15, 16, 20 I might have injected two or three thousand times but you can’t see anything on my veins. 5, 7, 16, 19 AS: Because you’re a doctor? 7, 20 AT: I’m a doctor. 20 I know how to do it. 17 I know I need to stay away from that. 14, 17, 20 AS: Did you use methadone? 9 AT: No, I never wanted that stuff. 13, 14 I just stopped. 15 AS: But it took you a few times? 7, 16, 19 AT: Yes.  I’d be using it for two weeks and working and performing just fine. 10, 14, 16 Once or twice one of my addict patients suspected me because they just knew. 6, 12, 15, 16 AS: And said that to you? 13, 14 AT: I talked my way out of it. 6, 13 “I’m so kaput today because I didn’t sleep last night.” 5, 19 Then I was off of it and clean. 15, 16 They weren’t sure anymore. 7 AS: What was the humiliating part? 8 AT: I was not in control. 10 I was actually being controlled by the substance. 9, 10, 18 AS: You have a deeper understanding now? 17 AT: I know how powerful that can be. 17 AS: When you talk about a personal connection. 6, 10, 17, 18 AT: I know how you can be thinking rationally and you’ll be doing something completely contrary. 14, 17 Knowing as I’m doing it that I don’t want to do it but I’m doing it anyways. 14, 17 “Oh my God that feels good. 6, 13, 18, 19 What an asshole now I did it again.” 17 AS: That consciousness is always there. 10 AT: The other part is like somebody else is holding the steering wheel and driving you. 8, 16, 18 It’s a profound thing and I think it’s kind of unique for the opiates. 11, 17, 19 They have such an intricate way of interacting with the receptors in your brain and so specific in the way they interact with your brain. 5, 7 They quickly are after a relatively short time can change the way that your brain is functioning and the way of steering your thoughts and your behavior. 5, 7, 10, 16, 19 AS: Do you feel like you got that back? 11, 13, 17, 18, 19 AT: Yes, but I am very respectful of it. 7 I will never have that in my practice or close to me because I couldn’t resist. 6, 7, 13 AS: What about your friend the anesthesiologist? 13 AT: He didn’t get into that. 20 Maybe he was less vulnerable than me. 18 Maybe he never had attention deficit disorder or something like that. 5, 6, 13 I never identified with my patients. 13, 15 I started to understand them better but I never felt, “You’re the same as me.” 6, 7, 13, 15, 17 It’s not like I chummed up to them. 9, 14 AS: You understood more about what they were going through.  You had not previously had an experience where you couldn’t control— AT: I was pretty understanding before but you can’t really know what it is. 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 14, 15, 17 It’s not something that you should have to know. 17 You shouldn’t have to have that experience. 15 The price is just way too high. 11 In that sense it’s very humiliating. 9 I never feel ever even this much superiority over my patients. 13, 15, 18 I know why they lie. 17 I know that works. 8, 17 I know how much they hate themselves for lying. 12, 17 The whole shame thing and everything is just mind blowing. 6, 19 AS: That’s powerful.  What I wanted to ask is what’s changed in your practice besides you? 5, 6, 14 What changes have you seen? 5, 13 Beck was talking about the substantial decrease of the numbers and the increase in age because heroin’s not in. 6, 7, 10, 14, 15 How has your practice changed? 5, 6 What have you noticed around opioids? 5 AT: Hard to say what has changed around me or what I have changed myself. 5, 6, 14 I used to work a lot more, see patients five or five and a half days a week. 5, 9, 16, 18, 19 I was insane.  A few years back really started to realize how morphine was helping me to work more. 6, 7, 8, 11, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19 AS: How long ago did you stop? 7, 16 AT: A couple years was the last time I used it. 7, 9, 16, 19 There were gaps.  AS: But it was over a period of ten.  AT: I was very worried about myself.  AS: What made you not take methadone? 13, 20 AT: I took methadone or oral morphine just to bridge over a certain gap of time before I knew I could take two or three weeks off to detox. 6, 7, 12, 16, 19, 20 AS: You know what you’re doing. 7, 17 Take two or three weeks off of work to detox because that’s how long it would take? 7, 16, 20 AT: It would take me four or five days to get over the worst but then you’re shaking depending on how long you’ve used. 7, 9, 18, 19, 20 You’re going to have post-acute withdrawal symptoms for up to a year or two. 7, 14, 16 AS: Those are serious.  Back to your patients. 15 How did it change? 5 AT: I reduced the number of addict patients I treat. 7, 14, 15 Most of the patients that are being treated by me I’ve been treating for years. 7, 15, 16 I haven’t taken on many new ones. 6, 12, 18, 20 AS: Just addict patients? 15 AT: Beck mentioned, I can confirm that. 12 Most people I see are… 5 AS: In their forties or fifties.  AT: I can’t remember the last time I’ve seen a teenaged user. 5, 7, 9, 13, 15, 16, 19 AS: But when you started your practice? 6, 15 AT: I had sixteen, seventeen year olds. 16 My youngest patients were sixteen and already heavy heroin users. 6, 7, 9, 15, 18 It was a long battle on methadone and this and that. 7 There’s still cocaine there. 7 We’ll prescribe methylphenidate, Ritalin. 7, 10, 12 AS: Does that help with cocaine addiction? 8, 15, 18 AT: Sort of.  It’s a stimulant. 19 It’s not like they’d totally not crave it.  In some way or another it helps them maintain a certain stability. 18 I’ll go along with it. 7, 15 As long as it works it works. 7, 8 The pragmatic approach.  It’s a difficult thing when you treat addicts. 7, 10, 13, 15, 19 It’s not a quick thing. 19 You’re in for a long haul always. 7, 10 AS: Your medical model is set up to accommodate that? 11 AT: To a degree. 7, 19 I work together with pharmacies. 9, 11, 16, 20 I work with federal practitioners. 12 I actually am one of the very, very few, I don’t know another psychiatrist except for Arud in Zurich which is a huge practice there, I take blood and there’s a central lab in Baden that I bring it over to and do lab work there. 6, 8, 17, 18, 20 I do maintain a very, very small amount of physical contact with my patients. 12, 15 I measure their blood pressure or listen to their heart. 6, 7, 14 AS: We were talking about your patients, the age of your patients and how its changed. 5, 6, 15 It’s rare that I get somebody below twenty for anything anymore which is okay. 7, 14, 20 I’m older myself. 15, 16 I think it might have to do with the fact that when I started my practice I was much younger and probably projected a much more dynamic, youngish me which younger patients could identify with more. 6, 12, 13, 15, 16 AS: How are people referred to you in private practice? 5, 6, 7, 20 AT: I’d say about a fifth of them just hear about me and call me up. 14, 17 The rest, half of the rest get referred by practitioners and the other half by the psychiatric institute. 7, 12, 16, 20 Most of my patients are not addicts. 13, 15 AS: It seemed like you said this earlier, did you purposely reduce the number of addict patients or have they naturally declined? 5, 7, 13, 14, 15 AT: It’s hard to say. 6, 14 I purposely sort of withdrew a little bit from that because it’s really taxing. 6, 7, 8, 20 In private practice if you don’t have an infrastructure and a lot of personnel and social workers and stuff like that to help additionally it’s a lot of work. 5, 6, 7, 10, 17, 18 Because of the lifestyle that Beck was talking about. 6, 7, 8 AT: The different aspects. 7, 18 AS: All the stigma and the problems. 7 AT: Their whole living situation, who they’re living with, their economic situation, their job. 6, 7 All this stuff.  How are they buying food? 12, 20 Who’s paying for it? 6, 18 Where’s it coming from? 7 Do they have social services of the municipality there to help them? 18 AS: When you take on an addict patient you’re taking on all that. 7, 15, 20 AT: The whole thing. 19 Which I don’t do myself but I have to be in phone contact with the social services of the municipality or their primary care physician or with their em