ut ten times more easily than morphine. 5, 7, 9, 10, 16, 18, 19 If you inject it this huge wall of heroin is immediately entering your brain. 5, 10, 12 The sharp rise in the concentration might be a temporal overdose.  Your brain doesn’t have enough time to adjust to this amount of effect. 5, 7, 12, 16, 19, 20 Your breathing just shuts down, your heart stops. 6, 7, 14, 19 That’s an overdose.  Apart from that it’s not particularly dangerous. 8 If you take an amount of heroin that you can tolerate your health isn’t going to be impaired. 7, 10, 12, 20 You’re just going to be dependent on it. 7 AS: That can turn out to be a problem. 7 AT: It can be a problem. 7 I like being able to move freely. 7, 14, 18 I want to go to the states for a few weeks and not have to worry about having something with me that maintains me. 14, 16, 17 These are the motivational factors that Beck was talking about. 6 I have lots of reasons that I don’t want to. 7, 10, 14, 15, 17 AS: With the motivational thinking or interviewing.  Those are powerful.  I think my son-in-law had a counselor who used that. 9, 16, 17, 20 I remember he was talking about that he really liked it. 6, 7, 8, 9, 13, 14, 15 He liked a therapist using that model. 9, 10, 14 AT: The whole politics towards this needs to change. 5, 15 It’s just so tiresome because there are experts who have a lot of knowledge and experience about it but their hands are tied by the greater way that it’s being seen by society and by the health department and by the politics. 5, 7, 8, 13, 15, 17 And the different administrations that come in and the ruling parties and how quickly you can backtrack and lose ground on something. 5, 7, 8, 11, 13, 17, 18, 19 AT: How flexible are you as a therapist?  How flexible can you use substitution agents or other treatment modalities that you can offer? 7, 9, 13, 15, 18 Talk therapy, group therapy, institutionalization, whatever works or is desired or is acceptable or makes sense. 7, 8, 9, 18 This whole thing ab